@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Graph#stronglyConnCompR
stronglyConnCompR ∷ Ord key ⇒ [(node, key, [key])] → [SCC (node, key, [key])]

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Graph#size
size ∷ (Int, Int) → Int

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Graph#bounds
bounds ∷ JArray a → (Int, Int)

-- | All vertices of a graph.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Graph#vertices
vertices ∷ JArray [Int] → [Int]

-- | All edges of a graph.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Graph#edges
edges ∷ JArray [Int] → [(Int, Int)]

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Graph#mapT
mapT ∷ (ArrayElem a, ArrayElem b) ⇒ (Int → a → b) → JArray a → JArray b

-- | Build a graph from a list of edges.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Graph#buildG
buildG ∷ (Int, Int) → [(Int, Int)] → JArray [Int]

-- | The graph obtained by reversing all edges.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Graph#transposeG
transposeG ∷ JArray [Int] → JArray [Int]

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Graph#reverseE
reverseE ∷ JArray [Int] → [(Int, Int)]

-- | A table of the count of edges from each node.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Graph#outdegree
outdegree ∷ JArray [Int] → JArray Int

-- | A table of the count of edges into each node.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Graph#indegree
indegree ∷ JArray [Int] → JArray Int

-- | Identical to <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Graph#graphFromEdges" >graphFromEdges</a>, except that the return value does not include the function which maps keys to vertices. This version of <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Graph#graphFromEdges" >graphFromEdges</a> is for backwards compatibility.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Graph#graphFromEdges_tick
graphFromEdges' ∷ Ord key ⇒ [(node, key, [key])] → (JArray [Int], Int→(node, key, [key]))

-- | Build a graph from a list of nodes uniquely identified by keys, with a list of keys of nodes this node should have edges to. The out-list may contain keys that don't correspond to nodes of the graph; they are ignored.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Graph#graphFromEdges
graphFromEdges ∷ Ord key ⇒ [(node, key, [key])] → (JArray [Int], Int→(node, key, [key]), key→Maybe Int)

-- | A spanning forest of the graph, obtained from a depth-first search of the graph starting from each vertex in an unspecified order.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Graph#dff
dff ∷ JArray [Int] → Forest Int

-- | A spanning forest of the part of the graph reachable from the listed vertices, obtained from a depth-first search of the graph starting at each of the listed vertices in order.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Graph#dfs
dfs ∷ JArray [Int] → [Int] → Forest Int

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Graph#generate
generate ∷ JArray [Int] → Int → Tree Int

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Graph#prune
prune ∷ (Int, Int) → Forest Int → Forest Int

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Graph#chop
chop ∷ Forest Int → ArrayOf s Bool → ST s (Forest Int)

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Graph#preorder
preorder ∷ Tree a → [a]

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Graph#preorderF
preorderF ∷ Forest a → [a]

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Graph#tabulate
tabulate ∷ (Int, Int) → [Int] → JArray Int

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Graph#preArr
preArr ∷ (Int, Int) → Forest Int → JArray Int

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Graph#postorder
postorder ∷ Tree a → [a]

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Graph#postorderF
postorderF ∷ Forest a → [a]

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Graph#postOrd
postOrd ∷ JArray [Int] → [Int]

-- | A topological sort of the graph. 
--   The order is partially specified by the condition that a vertex <i >i</i> precedes <i >j</i> whenever <i >j</i> is reachable from <i >i</i> but not vice versa.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Graph#topSort
topSort ∷ JArray [Int] → [Int]

-- | The connected components of a graph. 
--   Two vertices are connected if there is a path between them, traversing edges in either direction.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Graph#components
components ∷ JArray [Int] → Forest Int

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Graph#undirected
undirected ∷ JArray [Int] → JArray [Int]

-- | The strongly connected components of a graph.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Graph#scc
scc ∷ JArray [Int] → Forest Int

-- | A list of vertices reachable from a given vertex.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Graph#reachable
reachable ∷ JArray [Int] → Int → [Int]

-- | Is the second vertex reachable from the first?
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Graph#path
path ∷ JArray [Int] → Int → Int → Bool

-- | The biconnected components of a graph. 
--   An undirected graph is biconnected if the deletion of any vertex leaves it connected.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Graph#bcc
bcc ∷ JArray [Int] → Forest [Int]

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Graph#do_label
do_label ∷ JArray [Int] → JArray Int → Tree Int → Tree (Int, Int, Int)

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Graph#bicomps
bicomps ∷ Tree (Int, Int, Int) → Forest [Int]

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Graph#collect
collect ∷ Tree (Int, Int, Int) → (Int, Tree [Int])

-- | A HashMap implementation based on a <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hash_array_mapped_trie" >Hash Array Mapped Trie</a>
--   The hash array mapped trie achieves almost hash table-like speed while using memory much more economically. Also, a hash table may have to be periodically resized, an expensive operation, whereas HAMTs grow and shrink dynamically.<h2 > Comparison with <span class="unknown" >Data.TreeMap</span></h2><h3 > Advantages of the <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#HashMap" >HashMap</a></h3><ul > <li > The hash map can be used with key types that do not have a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Ord" >Ord</a> instance. </li> <li > It is less affected by slow implementations of the (<a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Eq._eq_eq" >Eq.==</a>) operation on keys. </li> <li > There is less aggregated memory overhead per key/value pair. </li> </ul><h3 > Disadvantages of the <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#HashMap" >HashMap</a></h3><ul > <li > Performance is severely affected when the hashing function tends to produce many collisions.</li> <li > It does not support getting the minimum/maximum key in logarithmic time, nor processing in key order in linear time.</li> </ul><h2 > Creating Hash Maps</h2>
--   Get an empty map with <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/./Monoid.html#Monoid.mempty" >Monoid.mempty</a> or <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeList.html#ListEmpty.empty" >ListEmpty.empty</a>, make a singleton one with <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#singleton" >singleton</a> or turn an association list into a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#HashMap" >HashMap</a> with <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#fromList" >fromList</a>. The more general function <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#fromListWith" >fromListWith</a> allows custom handling of associations with duplicate keys.<h2 > Add, Change or Remove Associations</h2>
--   Use <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#insert" >insert</a>, <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#delete" >delete</a>, <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#adjust" >adjust</a> and <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#replace" >replace</a>. The more general form of <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#insert" >insert</a> is <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#insertWith" >insertWith</a> which accepts a function to combine the given value with an already existing one.<h2 > Lookups</h2>
--   The basic function is <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#lookup" >lookup</a>, of which <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#member" >member</a> and <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#lookupDefault" >lookupDefault</a> are variants. The operator (<a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#_excl_excl" >!!</a>) may be used when the existence of the keys looked for is out of the question.<h2 > Set operations</h2>
--   There is <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#union" >union</a>, <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#difference" >difference</a> and <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#intersection" >intersection</a>. More general functions <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#unionWith" >unionWith</a> and <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#intersectionWith" >intersectionWith</a> allow combination of the affected values.<h2 > Folds</h2>
--   Left folds as well as right folds are provided by <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#foldValues" >foldValues</a> and <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#foldrValues" >foldrValues</a>. Variants <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#foldWithKey" >foldWithKey</a> and <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#foldrWithKey" >foldrWithKey</a> allow examination not only of the value, but also of the key.
--   Frequently needed functions such as <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#values" >values</a>, <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#keys" >keys</a>, <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#each" >each</a> and <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#size" >size</a> are just predefined folds for your convenience.<h2 > Filtering</h2>
--   Create a subset of an existing map with <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#filterValues" >filterValues</a> or <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#filterWithKey" >filterWithKey</a>.<h2 > Transformations</h2>
--   <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#mapValues" >mapValues</a>, <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#mapWithKey" >mapWithKey</a> and <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#traverseWithKey" >traverseWithKey</a> should cover any need to transform an existing map.<h3 > Naming Conventions</h3>
--   Functions whose name have the <i >With</i> suffix take a custom function to combine two values and are thus more general than the ones without that suffix. Most often it is the case that
--  <pre>
--  
--   xxx = xxxWith const
--  </pre>
--   Functions whose name have the <i >Values</i> suffix operate on the values of the mappings contained in the map and take an appropriate custom function as argument. The <i >Values</i> suffix also serves to avoid conflicts with Prelude functions (i.e. <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeList.html#map" >map</a>, <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeList.html#filter" >filter</a>, <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/./Foldable.html#Foldable.fold" >Foldable.fold</a>, <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/./Foldable.html#Foldable.foldr" >Foldable.foldr</a>).
--   The companions of the <i >Values</i> functions have the suffix <i >WithKey</i> and accept functions that take an extra argument for the key. The key portion of a mapping or association is always passed first, followed by the associated value.
module frege.data.HashMap

-- | <i >O(1)</i> Create a singleton map
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#singleton
singleton ∷ Eq k ⇒ k → v → HashMap k v

-- | <i >O(n)</i> Compute the size of the map
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#size
size ∷ HashMap k v → Int

-- | <i >O(n)</i> Retrieve a list of the values in the map
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#values
values ∷ HashMap k v → [v]

-- | <i >O(n)</i> Retrieve a list of the keys in the map
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#keys
keys ∷ HashMap k v → [k]

-- | <i >O(n)</i> Retrieve a list of the associations in the map
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#each
each ∷ HashMap k v → [(k, v)]

-- | <i >O(log n)</i> 
--  <pre>
--  
--   insert k v m
--  </pre> 
--   is a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#HashMap" >HashMap</a> <i >h</i> such that 
--  <pre>
--  
--   lookup k h = Just v
--  </pre> 
--   and lookup for any other key <i >o</i> 
--  <pre>
--  
--   lookup o h = lookup o m
--  </pre> 
--   Less formally said, <i >k</i> is associated with <i >v</i> in the resulting map, updating a previously existing association of <i >k</i> if it exists, while all other associations are left untouched. 
--   In the case of an update, the new value will get forced, see <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#insertWith" >insertWith</a> for details.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#insert
insert ∷ Eq k ⇒ k → v → HashMap k v → HashMap k v

-- | <i >O(log n)</i> 
--  <pre>
--  
--   insertWith f k v m
--  </pre> 
--   If <i >m</i> does not contain <i >k</i>, this works like <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#insert" >insert</a>. Otherwise, the existing association of <i >k</i> with some value <i >v'</i> is replaced by an association of <i >k</i> with the result of evaluating 
--  <pre>
--  
--   f v v'
--  </pre> 
--   in the resulting map. 
--   Strict evaluation is necessary to prevent building up of large thunks of the form 
--  <pre>
--  
--   f v3 (f v2 (f v1 v0))
--  </pre> 
--   Note that 
--  <pre>
--  
--   insert = insertWith const
--  </pre> 
--   and that this will evaluate the <b >new</b> value in case of an update. If you want to prevent this, use 
--  <pre>
--  
--   replace k v = insert k v . delete k
--  </pre> 
--   The replaced value will be evaluated only if the given function is strict in the second argument. Since <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#_const" >const</a> is lazy in the second argument, the following will be fine: 
--  <pre>
--  
--   insert &quot;foo&quot; 7 (insert &quot;foo&quot; undefined (delete &quot;foo&quot; m))
--  </pre> 
--   That is, the value that is inserted for a given key first is not evaluated on insertion, and only evaluated on update if the update function demands it, which is not the case for a plain <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#insert" >insert</a>.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#insertWith
insertWith ∷ Eq k ⇒ (v → v → v) → k → v → HashMap k v → HashMap k v

-- | <i >O(log n)</i> 
--  <pre>
--  
--   delete k m
--  </pre> 
--   is a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#HashMap" >HashMap</a> h such that 
--  <pre>
--  
--   lookup k h = Nothing
--  </pre> 
--   and for any other key <i >o</i> 
--  <pre>
--  
--   lookup o h = lookup o m
--  </pre> 
--   Less formally, the association of <i >k</i> with some value, if any, is removed in the result, while all other associations are retained. 
--   If <i >m</i> didn't contain <i >k</i> in the first place, 
--  <pre>
--  
--   delete k m = m
--  </pre>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#delete
delete ∷ Eq k ⇒ k → HashMap k v → HashMap k v

-- | <i >O(log n)</i> 
--  <pre>
--  
--   lookup k m
--  </pre> 
--   If <i >k</i> is associated with some value <i >v</i> in map <i >m</i>, it returns 
--  <pre>
--  
--   Just v
--  </pre> 
--   and otherwise 
--  <pre>
--  
--   Nothing
--  </pre>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#lookup
lookup ∷ Eq k ⇒ k → HashMap k v → Maybe v

-- | <i >O(log n)</i> 
--   Checks whether the key is present in the map
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#member
member ∷ Eq k ⇒ k → HashMap k v → Bool

-- | <i >O(log n)</i> 
--   Return the value to which the specified key is mapped, or the default value if this map contains no mapping for the key.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#lookupDefault
lookupDefault ∷ Eq k ⇒ v → k → HashMap k v → v

-- | <i >O(log n)</i> 
--   Return the value associated with the given key in the map. Fails with <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#error" >error</a> if the key is not present.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#_excl_excl
(!!) ∷  Eq k ⇒ HashMap k v → k → v 
infixl  16

-- | <i >O(log n)</i> 
--   Adjust the value tied to a given key in this map only if it is present. Otherwise, leave the map alone.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#adjust
adjust ∷ Eq k ⇒ (v → v) → k → HashMap k v → HashMap k v

-- | <i >O(log n)</i> 
--  <pre>
--  
--   replace k v m = insert k v . delete k $ m
--  </pre> 
--   Insert or update the association of <i >k</i> with <i >v</i> in <i >m</i> but avoid evaluation of <i >v</i> even if <i >m</i> already contains <i >k</i>. 
--   See also notes concerning updates on function <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#insertWith" >insertWith</a>.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#replace
replace ∷ Eq k ⇒ k → v → HashMap k v → HashMap k v

-- | <i >O(m*log n)</i> 
--   Computes the union of two hash maps. 
--   If a key occurs in both maps, the function provided in the first argument will be used to compute the result in the same way as <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#insertWith" >insertWith</a> would do it, that is, the value from the left hash map will be evaluated while the value from the right map may be evaluated only if the function demands it. However, values associated with keys that are member of only one map are left alone.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#unionWith
unionWith ∷ Eq k ⇒ (v → v → v) → HashMap k v → HashMap k v → HashMap k v

-- | <i >O(m*log n)</i> 
--   Computes the union of two hash maps. 
--   If a key occurs in both maps, the value from the left map will be evaluated and taken over to the new map. 
--   Because 
--  <pre>
--  
--   union  =  unionWith const
--  </pre> 
--   the considerations concerning strictness apply for <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#union" >union</a> in the same way as for <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#unionWith" >unionWith</a>.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#union
union ∷ Eq k ⇒ HashMap k v → HashMap k v → HashMap k v

-- | The union of all <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#HashMap" >HashMap</a>s in a list.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#unions
unions ∷ Eq k ⇒ [HashMap k v] → HashMap k v

-- | <i >O(n)</i> 
--   Reduce this map by applying a function to all associations, using the given starting value (typically the left-identity of the operator). Each application of the function is evaluated before using the result in the next application. 
--   This function is strict in the starting value.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#foldWithKey
foldWithKey ∷ (a → k → v → a) → a → HashMap k v → a

-- | <i >O(n)</i> 
--   Reduce this map by applying a binary operator to all values, using the given starting value (typically the left-identity of the operator). Each application of the operator is evaluated before using the result in the next application. 
--   This function is strict in the starting value.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#foldValues
foldValues ∷ (a → v → a) → a → HashMap k v → a

-- | <i >O(n)</i> 
--   Reduce this map by applying a binary operator to all values, using the given starting value (typically the right-identity of the operator). 
--   <b >Warning</b>: this function exists for Haskell compatibility only. Please be aware that right folds suffer from the danger of stack overflows, while left folds don't and are also faster because of tail recursion. Since the order of values is arbitrary anyway, there is often no good reason to insist on a right fold, so please use <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#foldValues" >foldValues</a> instead.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#foldrValues
foldrValues ∷ (v → a → a) → a → HashMap k v → a

-- | <i >O(n)</i> 
--   Reduce this map by applying a binary operator to all mappings, using the given starting value (typically the right-identity of the operator). 
--   <b >Warning</b>: this function exists for Haskell compatibility only. Please be aware that right folds suffer from the danger of stack overflows, while left folds don't and are also faster because of tail recursion. Since the order of values is arbitrary anyway, there is often no good reason to insist on a right fold, so please use <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#foldWithKey" >foldWithKey</a> instead.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#foldrWithKey
foldrWithKey ∷ (k → v → a → a) → a → HashMap k v → a

-- | <i >O(n)</i> 
--   Transform a map by applying a function to every value.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#mapValues
mapValues ∷ (v → u) → HashMap k v → HashMap k u

-- | <i >O(n)</i> 
--   Transform a map by applying a function to every key and its associated value.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#mapWithKey
mapWithKey ∷ (k → v → u) → HashMap k v → HashMap k u

-- | <i >O(n)</i> 
--   Transform a map by applying an applicative functor to every key and its associated value.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#traverseWithKey
traverseWithKey ∷ Applicative a ⇒ (k → v → a u) → HashMap k v → a (HashMap k u)

-- | <i >O(n)</i> 
--   Filter a map, retaining only mappings whose key and value satisfy a given predicate.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#filterWithKey
filterWithKey ∷ (k → v → Bool) → HashMap k v → HashMap k v

-- | <i >O(n)</i> 
--   Filter a map, retaining only mappings whose value satisfies a given predicate.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#filterValues
filterValues ∷ (v → Bool) → HashMap k v → HashMap k v

-- | <i >O(n*log m)</i> 
--   Computes the difference of two maps. 
--   Returns a map that contains the mappings of the first map whose keys do not exist in the second.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#difference
difference ∷ Eq k ⇒ HashMap k v → HashMap k u → HashMap k v

-- | <i >O(n*log m)</i> 
--   Computes the intersection of two maps. 
--   Return a map that contains the mappings of the first map for keys that also exist in the second.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#intersection
intersection ∷ Eq k ⇒ HashMap k v → HashMap k u → HashMap k v

-- | <i >O(n*log m)</i> 
--   Computes the intersection of two maps, combining the values with a given function.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#intersectionWith
intersectionWith ∷ Eq k ⇒ (v → u → w) → HashMap k v → HashMap k u → HashMap k w

-- | <i >O(n)</i> 
--   Build a map from an association list. If the list contains duplicate mappings, the later mappings take precedence.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#fromList
fromList ∷ Eq k ⇒ [(k, v)] → HashMap k v

-- | <i >O(n)</i> 
--   Build a map from an association list. Uses the provided function to merge values associated with duplicate keys.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#fromListWith
fromListWith ∷ Eq k ⇒ (v → v → v) → [(k, v)] → HashMap k v

-- | A map from hashable keys to values based on a Hash Mapped Array Trie. 
--   A map cannot contain duplicate keys; each key can map to at most one value. A <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#HashMap" >HashMap</a> makes no guarantees as to the order of its elements. 
--   A node of the <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#HashMap" >HashMap</a> is either <ul > <li > a key/value pair </li> <li > a list of key/value tuples with pair-wise different keys, where the hash code for all keys is identical (collisions). In the (hopefully) unlikely case of such collisions, the performance of operations using the affected keys degrades to that of similar operations on lists. However, collision lists should be short, if occurring at all.</li> <li > a bitmapped node with a bitmap of size 32 to indicate absence or presence of sub-nodes, followed by an array of up to 32 (sub)nodes.</li> </ul> 
--   This implementation of a <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Persistent_data_structure" >persistent</a> hash array mapped trie uses 32 bit hash values as provided by Java and the Frege <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Eq" >Eq</a> type class. 
--   To find a value, the search starts with the root node. If the node is a key/value pair, the node's key is compared to the search key. When the keys are equal, the value is returned, otherwise the key is not in the map. 
--   If the node is a bitmapped node, the hash code of the lookup key is computed and the presence of the index provided by the last five bits is checked in the bitmap. If it is there, the search continues with the corresponding node from the node array, otherwise the key is not in the map. With every recursion, the next five bits of the hash code will be used for indexing. 
--   It remains the case that the node is a collision list. The searched key's hashcode either is the same as the one of the keys in the collision list, in which case the search degrades to a sequential search in that list, or it is different, and in the latter case we know that the key is not in the map without even touching the list. 
--   Hence, the worst case in searching must do the following: <ul > <li > 1 time: compute the hash code of the key </li> <li > 7 times: find the next node through the sub-node array. This is in essence computation of an index with bit operations, followed by a memory read. The reason this is done at max 7 times is that it consumes 5 bits of the hash code every time. With 32 bit hash codes, we have 6 5-bit quantities that can range from 0 to 31, while the last 5-bit quantity has only 2 significant bits, the other ones are always zero. The hashmapped nodes at the 7th level of the map will consequently have at most 4 sub-nodes. (Note that this is an intrinsic limit that is determined by the hash code bit size, <b >not</b> by the algorithm. Should later Java versions choose to provide <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Long" >Long</a> bitcodes, for example, this code will still work with marginal adjustments, just that there would be 13 levels of bitmapped nodes instead of 7.)</li> <li > <i >n</i> times: comparison with the keys in the collision list, where <i >n</i> is the number of elements of the collision list, or comparison with the key of a key/value node (this is equivalent to a collision list of length 1).</li> </ul> 
--   It turns out that - absent hash collisions - lookups will be done almost in <b >constant time</b>. And so will be inserts and deletes, although with a slightly larger constant factor due to the house-keeping necessary for a persistent data structure. However, even this are in the worst case 7 array copies, where 6 of them may be of size 32 and one of size 4. Assuming that the pointers are 4 bytes long, this amounts to copying at most 196*4 bytes of memory. 
--   The map can have at most 2^32 non-bitmapped nodes maintained in 1+32+1024+32768+1048576+33554432+1073741824 bitmapped nodes. But because collision lists can be arbitrary long, the total number of key/value pairs is <b >not limited</b>. <h3 > Constructors</h3>  
--   <span class="code" ><b >private</b> <a name="HashMap.BM" >BM</a> {subnodes ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeArrays.html#JArray" >JArray</a> (<a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#HashMap" >HashMap</a> k v), bitmap ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a>}</span> 
--   
--   Bitmapped node. It has a bitmap of 32 bits that indicate presence or absence of a sub node for a given index which is in the range [0..31], and an array of sub nodes. The size of the array is equal to the number of 1-bits in the bitmap. An index is mapped to an actual array index like so: If the corresponding <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/./Bits.html#Bits.bit" >Bits.bit</a> is set in the bitmap, the number of less significant 1-bits in the bitmap is counted with <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/./Bits.html#Bits.bitCount" >Bits.bitCount</a> and this is then the index in the array. Otherwise there is no sub node for that index.  
--   Invariant 1 
--   <div > The length of <span class="unknown" >subnodes</span> equals the number of set bits in <span class="unknown" >bitmap</span>. </div>  
--   Invariant 2 
--   <div > There is no null pointer in <span class="unknown" >subnodes</span>. </div>  
--   Invariant 3 
--   <div > No subnode is the empty node. </div>    
--   <span class="code" ><b >private</b> <a name="HashMap.CO" >CO</a> {hash ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a>, list ∷ [(k, v)]}</span> 
--   
--   Collision node, holding a list of key/value tuples as well as the <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Eq.hashCode" >Eq.hashCode</a> all keys have in common. This helps us avoid touching the list when the sought key has a different hash code.  
--   Invariant 1 
--   <div > length of <span class="unknown" >list</span> is at least 2. </div>  
--   Invariant 2 
--   <div > all keys in <span class="unknown" >list</span> are different. </div>    
--   <span class="code" ><b >private</b> <a name="HashMap.KV" >KV</a> {hash ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a>, key ∷ k, value ∷ v}</span> 
--   
--   Singleton node holding a key with a value. Also caches the <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Eq.hashCode" >Eq.hashCode</a> of the key to avoid possibly expensive recomputation.   <h3 > Member Functions</h3>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="HashMap.bitmap" >bitmap</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#HashMap" >HashMap</a> α β</b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a></span> 
--   
--   access field <span class="code" >bitmap</span>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="HashMap.collisions" >collisions</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#HashMap" >HashMap</a> β α</b> → (<a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a>, [[β]])</span> 
--   
--   <i >O(n)</i> Compute a 3-tuple of <ul > <li > the number of collision nodes </li> <li > the total number of keys that have a collision </li> <li > a list of lists of colliding keys </li> </ul>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="HashMap.delete" >delete</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Eq" >Eq</a> k ⇒ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#HashMap" >HashMap</a> k v</b> → <b >k</b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#HashMap" >HashMap</a> k v</span> 
--   
--   <i >O(log n)</i> 
--  <pre>
--  
--   hm.delete k
--  </pre> 
--   Variant of <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#delete" >delete</a> that is better suited for left folds and supports dot-notation.   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="HashMap.hash" >hash</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#HashMap" >HashMap</a> β α</b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a></span> 
--   
--   access field <span class="code" >hash</span>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="HashMap.indexMap" >indexMap</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a></b> → <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a></b> → <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a></b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a></span> 
--   
--   transform an index into an actual array index 
--  <pre>
--  
--   indexMap bmap nodes inx
--  </pre> 
--   <i >bmap</i> is the bitmap 
--   <i >nodes</i> is the number of actual subnodes 
--   <i >inx</i> is a hash code or part of a hash code, whose least significant 5 bits are the index 
--   returns a number in the range 0..nodes, where <i >nodes</i> means "no corresponding node"   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="HashMap.insert" >insert</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Eq" >Eq</a> k ⇒ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#HashMap" >HashMap</a> k v</b> → <b >k</b> → v → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#HashMap" >HashMap</a> k v</span> 
--   
--   <i >O(log n)</i> 
--  <pre>
--  
--   hm.insert k v
--  </pre> 
--   Variant of <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#insert" >insert</a> that is better suited for left folds and supports dot-notation.   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="HashMap.invariants" >invariants</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Eq" >Eq</a> k ⇒ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#HashMap" >HashMap</a> k v</b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Bool" >Bool</a></span> 
--   
--   this checks the invariants for a node   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="HashMap.key" >key</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#HashMap" >HashMap</a> β α</b> → β</span> 
--   
--   access field <span class="code" >key</span>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="HashMap.list" >list</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#HashMap" >HashMap</a> β α</b> → [(β, α)]</span> 
--   
--   access field <span class="code" >list</span>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="HashMap.lookup" >lookup</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Eq" >Eq</a> k ⇒ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#HashMap" >HashMap</a> k v</b> → <b >k</b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Maybe" >Maybe</a> v</span> 
--   
--   <i >O(log n)</i> 
--  <pre>
--  
--   hm.lookup k
--  </pre> 
--   Variant of <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#lookup" >lookup</a> that supports dot-notation.   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="HashMap.subnodes" >subnodes</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#HashMap" >HashMap</a> β α</b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeArrays.html#JArray" >JArray</a> (<a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#HashMap" >HashMap</a> β α)</span> 
--   
--   access field <span class="code" >subnodes</span>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="HashMap.value" >value</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#HashMap" >HashMap</a> β α</b> → α</span> 
--   
--   access field <span class="code" >value</span>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#HashMap
data HashMap k v

-- | Bitmapped node. It has a bitmap of 32 bits that indicate presence or absence of a sub node for a given index which is in the range [0..31], and an array of sub nodes. The size of the array is equal to the number of 1-bits in the bitmap. An index is mapped to an actual array index like so: If the corresponding <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/./Bits.html#Bits.bit" >Bits.bit</a> is set in the bitmap, the number of less significant 1-bits in the bitmap is counted with <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/./Bits.html#Bits.bitCount" >Bits.bitCount</a> and this is then the index in the array. Otherwise there is no sub node for that index.  
--   Invariant 1 
--   <div > The length of <span class="unknown" >subnodes</span> equals the number of set bits in <span class="unknown" >bitmap</span>. </div>  
--   Invariant 2 
--   <div > There is no null pointer in <span class="unknown" >subnodes</span>. </div>  
--   Invariant 3 
--   <div > No subnode is the empty node. </div>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#HashMap.BM
private BM {subnodes ∷ JArray (HashMap k v), bitmap ∷ Int}

-- | Collision node, holding a list of key/value tuples as well as the <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Eq.hashCode" >Eq.hashCode</a> all keys have in common. This helps us avoid touching the list when the sought key has a different hash code.  
--   Invariant 1 
--   <div > length of <span class="unknown" >list</span> is at least 2. </div>  
--   Invariant 2 
--   <div > all keys in <span class="unknown" >list</span> are different. </div>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#HashMap.CO
private CO {hash ∷ Int, list ∷ [(k, v)]}

-- | Singleton node holding a key with a value. Also caches the <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Eq.hashCode" >Eq.hashCode</a> of the key to avoid possibly expensive recomputation.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/HashMap#HashMap.KV
private KV {hash ∷ Int, key ∷ k, value ∷ v}

-- | Provide Iterators for <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#String" >String</a> and <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeArrays.html#JArray" >JArray</a>
module frege.data.Iterators

-- | A <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Iterators#StringIterator" >StringIterator</a> is a data structure that lets us view a part of a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#String" >String</a> as a list. 
--   With large <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#String" >String</a>s, performing list work on <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#String" >String</a>s can be expensive, because more recent JVMs implement the <span class="code" >substring</span> operation via copying. 
--   Construction, <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeList.html#ListView.drop" >ListView.drop</a>, <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeList.html#ListView.take" >ListView.take</a>, <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeList.html#ListView.head" >ListView.head</a> and <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeList.html#ListView.tail" >ListView.tail</a> on a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Iterators#StringIterator" >StringIterator</a> are O(1) operations. The drawback is that it holds on to the underlying <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#String" >String</a>. <h3 > Constructors</h3>  
--   <span class="code" ><b >private</b> <a name="StringIterator.SI" >SI</a> {string ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#StringJ" >StringJ</a> a, at ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a>, limit ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a>}</span> 
--     <h3 > Member Functions</h3>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="StringIterator.at" >at</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Iterators#StringIterator" >StringIterator</a> α</b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a></span> 
--   
--   access field <span class="code" >at</span>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="StringIterator.from" >from</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#StringJ" >StringJ</a> α</b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Iterators#StringIterator" >StringIterator</a> α</span> 
--   
--   Construct a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Iterators#StringIterator" >StringIterator</a> from a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#String" >String</a>   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="StringIterator.limit" >limit</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Iterators#StringIterator" >StringIterator</a> α</b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a></span> 
--   
--   access field <span class="code" >limit</span>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="StringIterator.string" >string</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Iterators#StringIterator" >StringIterator</a> α</b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#StringJ" >StringJ</a> α</span> 
--   
--   access field <span class="code" >string</span>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="StringIterator.to" >to</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Iterators#StringIterator" >StringIterator</a> α</b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#StringJ" >StringJ</a> α</span> 
--   
--   realize the substring indicated by this iterator
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Iterators#StringIterator
data StringIterator a

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Iterators#StringIterator.SI
private SI {string ∷ StringJ a, at ∷ Int, limit ∷ Int}

-- | A <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Iterators#ArrayIterator" >ArrayIterator</a> is a data structure that lets us view a part of a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeArrays.html#JArray" >JArray</a> as a list. 
--   With large <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeArrays.html#JArray" >JArray</a>s, doing <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeList.html#ListSource.toList" >ListSource.toList</a> and iterating through the list can get expensive memory-wise. 
--   Construction, <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeList.html#ListView.drop" >ListView.drop</a>, <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeList.html#ListView.take" >ListView.take</a>, <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeList.html#ListView.head" >ListView.head</a> and <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeList.html#ListView.tail" >ListView.tail</a> on a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Iterators#ArrayIterator" >ArrayIterator</a> are O(1) operations with a minimal memory overhead. The drawback is that it holds on to the underlying <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeArrays.html#JArray" >JArray</a>. <h3 > Constructors</h3>  
--   <span class="code" ><b >private</b> <a name="ArrayIterator.AI" >AI</a> {array ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeArrays.html#JArray" >JArray</a> a, at ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a>, limit ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a>}</span> 
--     <h3 > Member Functions</h3>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="ArrayIterator.array" >array</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Iterators#ArrayIterator" >ArrayIterator</a> α</b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeArrays.html#JArray" >JArray</a> α</span> 
--   
--   access field <span class="code" >array</span>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="ArrayIterator.at" >at</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Iterators#ArrayIterator" >ArrayIterator</a> α</b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a></span> 
--   
--   access field <span class="code" >at</span>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="ArrayIterator.from" >from</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeArrays.html#JArray" >JArray</a> α</b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Iterators#ArrayIterator" >ArrayIterator</a> α</span> 
--   
--   make iterator from <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeArrays.html#JArray" >JArray</a>   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="ArrayIterator.limit" >limit</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Iterators#ArrayIterator" >ArrayIterator</a> α</b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a></span> 
--   
--   access field <span class="code" >limit</span>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="ArrayIterator.to" >to</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeArrays.html#ArrayElem" >ArrayElem</a> a ⇒ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Iterators#ArrayIterator" >ArrayIterator</a> a</b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeArrays.html#JArray" >JArray</a> a</span> 
--   
--   realize the subarray indicated by this iterator
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Iterators#ArrayIterator
data ArrayIterator a

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Iterators#ArrayIterator.AI
private AI {array ∷ JArray a, at ∷ Int, limit ∷ Int}

module frege.data.Ix

-- | The <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Ix#Ix" >Ix</a> class is used to map a contiguous subrange of values in a type onto integers. It is used primarily for array indexing. (see the array package). 
--   The first argument <span class="code" >(l,u)</span> of each of these operations is a pair specifying the lower and upper bounds of a contiguous subrange of values. An implementation is entitled to assume the following laws about these operations: 
--  <pre>
--  
--   inRange (l,u) i == elem i (range (l,u))
--  </pre> 
--  <pre>
--  
--   range (l,u) !! index (l,u) i == i
--  </pre> 
--   , when 
--  <pre>
--  
--   inRange (l,u) i
--  </pre> 
--  <pre>
--  
--   map (index (l,u)) (range (l,u)) == [0..rangeSize (l,u)-1]
--  </pre> 
--  <pre>
--  
--   rangeSize (l,u) == length (range (l,u))
--  </pre> <h3 > Known Instances</h3> 
--   <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Ix#Ix_Bool" >Bool</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Ix#Ix_l_c_r" >(,)</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Ix#Ix_l__r" >()</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Ix#Ix_l_ccc_r" >(,,,)</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Ix#Ix_l_cc_r" >(,,)</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Ix#Ix_l_cccc_r" >(,,,,)</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Ix#Ix_Integer" >Integer</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Ix#Ix_Int" >Int</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Ix#Ix_Char" >Char</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Ix#Ix_Ordering" >Ordering</a> <h3 > Member Functions</h3>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Ix.inRange" >inRange</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Ix#Ix" >Ix</a> a ⇒ (a, a) → a → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Bool" >Bool</a></span> 
--   
--   Returns <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#HaskellBool.True" >HaskellBool.True</a> the given subscript lies in the range defined the bounding pair.   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Ix.index" >index</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Ix#Ix" >Ix</a> a ⇒ (a, a) → a → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a></span> 
--   
--   The position of a subscript in the subrange. 
--   Must specify one of index, unsafeIndex 
--   <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Ix#Ix.index" >Ix.index</a> is typically over-ridden in instances, with essentially the same code, but using indexError instead of error Reason: we have <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeText.html#Show" >Show</a> at the instances  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Ix.range" >range</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Ix#Ix" >Ix</a> a ⇒ (a, a) → [a]</span> 
--   
--   The list of values in the subrange defined by a bounding pair.   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Ix.rangeSize" >rangeSize</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Ix#Ix" >Ix</a> a ⇒ <b >(a, a)</b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a></span> 
--   
--   The size of the subrange defined by a bounding pair.   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Ix.unsafeIndex" >unsafeIndex</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Ix#Ix" >Ix</a> a ⇒ <b >(a, a)</b> → <b >a</b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a></span> 
--   
--   Like <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Ix#Ix.index" >Ix.index</a>, but without checking that the value is in range.   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Ix.unsafeRangeSize" >unsafeRangeSize</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Ix#Ix" >Ix</a> a ⇒ <b >(a, a)</b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a></span> 
--   
--   like <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Ix#Ix.rangeSize" >Ix.rangeSize</a>, but without checking that the upper bound is in range.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Ix#Ix
class (Eq a, Ord a) ⇒ Ix a

-- | Returns <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#HaskellBool.True" >HaskellBool.True</a> the given subscript lies in the range defined the bounding pair.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Ix#Ix.inRange
inRange ∷ Ix a ⇒ (a, a) → a → Bool

-- | The position of a subscript in the subrange. 
--   Must specify one of index, unsafeIndex 
--   <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Ix#Ix.index" >Ix.index</a> is typically over-ridden in instances, with essentially the same code, but using indexError instead of error Reason: we have <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeText.html#Show" >Show</a> at the instances
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Ix#Ix.index
index ∷ Ix a ⇒ (a, a) → a → Int

-- | The list of values in the subrange defined by a bounding pair.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Ix#Ix.range
range ∷ Ix a ⇒ (a, a) → [a]

-- | The size of the subrange defined by a bounding pair.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Ix#Ix.rangeSize
rangeSize ∷ Ix a ⇒ (a, a) → Int

-- | Like <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Ix#Ix.index" >Ix.index</a>, but without checking that the value is in range.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Ix#Ix.unsafeIndex
unsafeIndex ∷ Ix a ⇒ (a, a) → a → Int

-- | like <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Ix#Ix.rangeSize" >Ix.rangeSize</a>, but without checking that the upper bound is in range.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Ix#Ix.unsafeRangeSize
unsafeRangeSize ∷ Ix a ⇒ (a, a) → Int

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Ix#indexError
indexError ∷ Show a ⇒ (a, a) → a → String → b

-- | This module provides <a href="http://www.ecma-international.org/publications/files/ECMA-ST/ECMA-404.pdf" >JSON support</a> for Frege.
--   JSON support comprises 4 levels:<ol > <li > On the lexical level, we analyze a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#String" >String</a> and produce a list of JSON <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/JSON#Token" >Token</a>s. </li> <li > On the grammar level, we parse a list of <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/JSON#Token" >Token</a>s and produce a JSON <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/JSON#Value" >Value</a>, the internal representation of JSON data. (It is also possible to write custom parsers that produce values of certain data types directly.)</li> <li > On the value level, we convert JSON <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/JSON#Value" >Value</a>s to and from values of algebraic data types. This is accomplished by type classes <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/JSON#ToJSON" >ToJSON</a> and <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/JSON#FromJSON" >FromJSON</a>. Instances for basic types, in particular for all tuple types, are provided.</li> <li > On the presentation level, a JSON <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/JSON#Value" >Value</a> is rendered as <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#String" >String</a> that conforms to the JSON standard and can thus be used to exchange data with other software or over the internet.</li> </ol>
--   The users of this library can get full JSON support by concentrating on the third point, which essentially means that they have to write <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/JSON#FromJSON" >FromJSON</a> and <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/JSON#ToJSON" >ToJSON</a> instances for their data types. It follows a short tutorial on how to do this.<h2 > Encoding of algebraic data types in JSON</h2>
--   The following suggestions will foster a compact and easy to decode <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#String" >String</a> representation of Frege data.
--   (There is currently no support for automatically derived instances yet, but when it gets implemented it shall comply with this suggestions.)<ul > <li > <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Bool" >Bool</a>, numbers, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#String" >String</a>: <span class="code" >true</span>, <span class="code" >false</span>, <i >number</i>, "<i >string</i>" </li> <li > a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Char" >Char</a> <i >c</i> will be encoded as JSON string "<i >c</i>" </li> <li > lists, arrays and the like: <span class="code" >[ value0, value1, ... ]</span> </li> <li > the trivial type <span class="code" >()</span>: <span class="code" >[]</span> </li> <li > tuples and other product types: <span class="code" >[ field1, field2, ... ]</span> </li> <li > enumerations: the constructor name as string </li> <li > type renamings: same as the wrapped type </li> <li > algebraic types: for each variant, make a JSON struct with the constructor name as key. Example:</li> </ul>
--  <pre>
--  
--   { &quot;Just&quot;: 42 }
--   {&quot;Nothing&quot;:null}
--  </pre><ul > <li > If there is more than one component for the constructor, treat the values as tuple:</li> </ul>
--  <pre>
--  
--   { &quot;Data&quot;: [field1,field2,...]}.
--  </pre><ul > <li > A record could also get encoded like: </li> </ul>
--  <pre>
--  
--   { &quot;case&quot;:&quot;Person&quot;, &quot;name&quot;:&quot;Smith&quot;, &quot;age&quot;:42}
--  </pre><ul > <li > inside <span class="code" >[]</span> or <span class="code" >{}</span> brackets, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Maybe" >Maybe</a> values can be abbreviated in such a way that <span class="code" >null</span> stands for <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Maybe.Nothing" >Maybe.Nothing</a> and <span class="code" >v</span> for <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Maybe.Just" >Maybe.Just</a> v, but observe that values of type <span class="code" >(Maybe (Maybe x))</span> cannot be encoded like this, because there would be no encoding for the value <span class="code" >Just Nothing</span>.</li> </ul><h2 > Create JSON documents from your data</h2>
--   This will be done in two steps:<ol > <li > Convert your data to JSON <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/JSON#Value" >Value</a>s, the internal generic representation for JSON data provided by this module.</li> <li > Show the JSON <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/JSON#Value" >Value</a>. This reults in a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#String" >String</a> which is a standard conforming JSON document.</li> </ol>
--   The conversion should be done by implementing type class <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/JSON#ToJSON" >ToJSON</a> for your data. There is just one class operation <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/JSON#ToJSON.toJSON" >ToJSON.toJSON</a> to implement.
--   Because standard Frege types, lists, arrays and all tuple types are already instances of <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/JSON#ToJSON" >ToJSON</a>, this is easy to accomplish, as will be demonstrated below.
--   Given the following definitions:
--  <pre>
--  
--    data Engine = Electric Double --- just performance in kW
--                 | Combustion { fuel :: [Fuel], displacement :: Double, cyls :: Int }
--    data Fuel = DIESEL | GASOLINE | NATURALGAS | LPG
--    data Vehicle = Vehicle { wheels :: Int, engine :: Maybe Engine }
--  </pre>
--   we could make the following instances:
--  <pre>
--  
--   derive Show Fuel      -- we need this in the ToJSON instance
--  </pre>
--   Use the <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/JSON#Value.String" >Value.String</a> constructor to create a JSON string value from an ordinary <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#String" >String</a>.
--  <pre>
--  
--   instance ToJSON Fuel where
--      toJSON = String . show
--  </pre>
--   The instance for <span class="code" >Engine</span> makes JSON structs for the <span class="code" >Engine</span> constructors by associating the constructor name with the values under the constructor. There is a function <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/JSON#struct" >struct</a>, designed to create such structures that have just a single association, which is - according to our encoding suggestions - a most frequent case.
--  <pre>
--  
--   instance ToJSON Engine where
--      toJSON (Electric d)
--              = struct &quot;Electric&quot; d
--      toJSON Combustion{fuel, displacement, cyls}
--              = struct &quot;Combustion&quot; (fuel, displacement, cyls)
--  </pre>
--   The <span class="code" >Vehicle</span> instance demonstractes a more complex JSON struct, where the record field names are associated with their values. The <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/JSON#Value.Struct" >Value.Struct</a> constructor takes a list of associations, created with <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/JSON#assoc" >assoc</a>. The constructor name is reduntant here, as <span class="code" >Vehicle</span> is a product type, so it is not included.
--  <pre>
--  
--   instance ToJSON Vehicle where
--      toJSON Vehicle{wheels, engine}
--              = Struct [
--                      assoc &quot;wheels&quot; wheels,
--                      -- uses the short form for Maybe
--                      assoc &quot;engine&quot; (maybeToJSON engine),
--              ]
--  </pre>
--   We can now construct some vehicles and print a JSON document. The translation of the internal to the external (i.e. <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#String" >String</a>) form is done by the <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeText.html#Show" >Show</a> instance for JSON <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/JSON#Value" >Value</a>s.
--  <pre>
--  
--   bicycle = Vehicle { wheels = 2, engine = Nothing }
--   ebike   = Vehicle { wheels = 2, engine = Just (Electric 0.9) }
--   car     = Vehicle { wheels = 4,
--                       engine = Just Combustion {
--                                fuel = [LPG, GASOLINE],
--                                displacement = 2.0,
--                                cyls = 4 }}
--   vehicles = [car, bicycle, ebike]
--   main = println (toJSON vehicles)
--  </pre>
--   The output looks like:
--  <pre>
--  
--   [{
--    &quot;wheels&quot; : 4,
--    &quot;engine&quot; : {&quot;Combustion&quot; : [[&quot;LPG&quot;, &quot;GASOLINE&quot;], 2.0, 4]}
--   },
--   {&quot;wheels&quot; : 2, &quot;engine&quot; : null},
--   {&quot;wheels&quot; : 2, &quot;engine&quot; : {&quot;Electric&quot; : 0.9}}]
--  </pre><h2 > Reconstruct your data from JSON data</h2>
--   There are 2 ways one could get confronted with JSON data:<ol > <li > A JSON document in the form of a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#String" >String</a> </li> <li > A JSON <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/JSON#Value" >Value</a> </li> </ol>
--   The type class <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/JSON#FromJSON" >FromJSON</a> has two operations to deal with those scenarios: <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/JSON#FromJSON.parseJSON" >FromJSON.parseJSON</a> and <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/JSON#FromJSON.fromJSON" >FromJSON.fromJSON</a>. But only the latter one needs to be implemented, the default implementation of <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/JSON#FromJSON.parseJSON" >FromJSON.parseJSON</a> will parse a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#String" >String</a> to a generic JSON <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/JSON#Value" >Value</a> and pass this to <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/JSON#FromJSON.fromJSON" >FromJSON.fromJSON</a>.
--   While it may cost a bit of memory to first create the JSON <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/JSON#Value" >Value</a>, this two-step approach has a number of advantages. Not the least one being clear separation of lexical and syntactical issues from semantical ones. But it is also the case that writing <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/JSON#FromJSON.fromJSON" >FromJSON.fromJSON</a> functions is quite easy, if not boring. The type checker, the support for basic types, lists and tuples and the internal plumbing make it hard to write a wrong implementation. Whereas writing a parser is comparatively hard and error prone.<h3 > Implementing <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/JSON#FromJSON.fromJSON" >FromJSON.fromJSON</a></h3>
--   Reconstruction of values from JSON data can fail, therefore the <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/JSON#FromJSON.fromJSON" >FromJSON.fromJSON</a> function delivers its result in a failure monad (<a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeMonad.html#MonadFail" >MonadFail</a> - two well known failure monads are <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Maybe" >Maybe</a> and <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Either" >Either</a> <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#String" >String</a>). <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/JSON#FromJSON.fromJSON" >FromJSON.fromJSON</a> is therefore overloaded twice in the return type: one for the actual data type and then the monad.
--   If one has already a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/JSON#ToJSON" >ToJSON</a> instance, it should go without saying that the implementations should satisfy the following law:
--  <pre>
--  
--   decodeEncoded x = fromJSON (toJSON x) == Just x
--  </pre>
--   Here are, in continuation of our example from above, the <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/JSON#FromJSON" >FromJSON</a> instances:
--  <pre>
--  
--   instance FromJSON Fuel where
--       fromJSON (String &quot;DIESEL&quot;) = return DIESEL
--       fromJSON (String &quot;GASOLINE&quot;) = return GASOLINE
--       fromJSON (String &quot;NATURALGAS&quot;) = return NATURALGAS
--       fromJSON (String &quot;LPG&quot;) = return LPG
--       fromJSON s = fail (&quot;cannot decode fuel from &quot; ++ show s)
--  </pre>
--   Note the use of <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeMonad.html#MonadFail.fail" >MonadFail.fail</a> and <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeMonad.html#Monad._return" >Monad.return</a> which is needed because we produce our value in a failure monad like <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Maybe" >Maybe</a> or <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Either" >Either</a> <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#String" >String</a>. In fact, every correct implementation of <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/JSON#FromJSON.fromJSON" >FromJSON.fromJSON</a> will have at least two equations (or, equivalently, case alternatives) where at least one does <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeMonad.html#MonadFail.fail" >MonadFail.fail</a> and at least one is <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeMonad.html#Monad._return" >Monad.return</a>ing an actual value.
--  <pre>
--  
--   import Data.List(lookup)  -- for looking up associations
--   instance FromJSON Engine where
--      fromJSON (Struct as)
--         | Just n   &lt;- lookup &quot;Electric&quot; as   = Electric &lt;$&gt; fromJSON n
--         | Just fdc &lt;- lookup &quot;Combustion&quot; as = do
--                 (fuel, displacement, cyls) &lt;- fromJSON fdc
--                 return Combustion{fuel, displacement, cyls}
--      fromJSON x = fail (&quot;invalid engine: &quot; ++ show x)
--  </pre>
--   We need to look up the keys to find out which variant we have. We then just decode the associated values and recreate our value. Failures for sub-components are propagated upwards automatically, thanks to the monadic approach. For example, when we try to decode an engine from
--  <pre>
--  
--   { &quot;Combustion&quot; : [ [&quot;Water&quot;], 2.7, 3]}
--  </pre>
--   we will get the error
--  <pre>
--  
--   cannot decode fuel from &quot;Water&quot;
--  </pre>
--   Because the fuel cannot get decoded, the decoding of the 3-tuple fails, and our combustion engine will not be constructed.
--   Note how the existence of generic <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/JSON#FromJSON" >FromJSON</a> instances for primitives, tuples and lists makes the decoding a no brainer.
--   Finally we can decode vehicles:
--  <pre>
--  
--   instance FromJSON Vehicle where
--       fromJSON (Struct as)
--           | Just jw &lt;- lookup &quot;wheels&quot; as
--           = case lookup &quot;engine&quot; as of
--               Just je -&gt; do
--                    wheels &lt;- fromJSON jw
--                    engine &lt;- fromJSON je
--                    return Vehicle{wheels, engine}
--               Nothing -&gt; do
--                   w &lt;- fromJSON jw
--                   return Vehicle{wheels=w, engine=Nothing}
--           | otherwise = fail &quot;Vehicels without wheels are not supported.&quot;
--      fromJSON garbage = fail &quot;not even remotely a vehicle&quot;
--  </pre>
--   Observe that this instance allows the following:<ol > <li > key/value pairs can occur in any order </li> <li > additional keys besides <span class="code" >"wheels"</span> and <span class="code" >"engine"</span> are ignored </li> <li > the "engine" key can be missing, and this will be interpreted as a vehicle without engine.</li> </ol>
--   Such a forgiving and fault-tolerant implementation is oftentimes in order. However, if one needs it stricter, one can pattern match the association list directly:
--  <pre>
--  
--   fromJSON (Struct [(&quot;wheels&quot;, jw), (&quot;engine&quot;, je)]) = do
--                    wheels &lt;- fromJSON jw
--                    engine &lt;- fromJSON je
--                    return Vehicle{wheels, engine}
--  </pre>
--   To read a vehicle from a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#String" >String</a>, we just need to run the automatically supplied <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/JSON#FromJSON.parseJSON" >FromJSON.parseJSON</a> function:
--  <pre>
--  
--    case parseJSON &quot;{\&quot;wheels\&quot; : 3 }&quot;  of
--         Just Vehicle{wheels=w} -&gt; -- we have w wheels ...
--  </pre>
--   Like with <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/JSON#FromJSON.fromJSON" >FromJSON.fromJSON</a>, the <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/JSON#FromJSON.parseJSON" >FromJSON.parseJSON</a> function needs to know the type of the item to decode as well as the failure monad to work with. Most often, this can be inferred by the compiler, like in the example above where it is clear that we want a <span class="code" >Maybe Vehicle</span>.<h3 > Very brief guide to <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/JSON#Parser" >Parser</a>s</h3>
--   Sometimes memory and time are extremely scarce, and the data to decode are comparatively simple. This is the time to roll your own custom JSON parser.
--   The parsers provided in this module fall into 4 classes:<ol > <li > <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/JSON#Parser" >Parser</a> <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/JSON#Value" >Value</a> are not interesting for custom parser builders, because they are used to implement the generic <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/JSON#Value" >Value</a> parsers. (The source code could give some inspiration, though ...)</li> <li > <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/JSON#Parser" >Parser</a> <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/JSON#Token" >Token</a> such as <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/JSON#parseComma" >parseComma</a>, <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/JSON#parseColon" >parseColon</a> and so on parse punctuation occuring in JSON syntax, and can be re-used in any other parser.</li> <li > <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/JSON#Parser" >Parser</a> <i >a</i> where <i >a</i> is some basic type like <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Bool" >Bool</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a> or <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#String" >String</a>. You most likely want to reuse those in your cutom parser.</li> <li > <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/JSON#Parser" >Parser</a> combinators like <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/JSON#parsePair" >parsePair</a>, <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/JSON#parseTuple" >parseTuple</a> and <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/JSON#parseList" >parseList</a> take one or two parsers as arguments and build parsers for more complex structures that contain the provided ones.</li> </ol>
--   All <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/JSON#Parser" >Parser</a>s supported by this module operate on list of <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/JSON#Token" >Token</a>s. The function <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/JSON#lexer" >lexer</a> can be used to turn a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#String" >String</a> into such a list, obeying the JSON lexical syntax. Finally, the function <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/JSON#runParser" >runParser</a> actually applies a parser to a token list.
--   So the skeleton of your code should read like this example:
--  <pre>
--  
--   run :: MonadFail m =&gt; String -&gt; m [Float]
--   run = runParser custom . lexer
--          where custom = parseList parseFloat
--  </pre>
--   The "custom parser" here parses a list of floating point values, and on success returns a <span class="code" >[Float]</span> in the failure monad of your choice.
module frege.data.JSON

-- | lexical entities that can appear in a JSON String  <h3 > Constructors</h3>  
--   <span class="code" ><b >protected</b> <a name="Token.BRACEL" >BRACEL</a> </span> 
--   
--   left brace <span class="code" >{</span>   
--   <span class="code" ><b >protected</b> <a name="Token.BRACER" >BRACER</a> </span> 
--   
--   right brace <span class="code" >}</span>   
--   <span class="code" ><b >protected</b> <a name="Token.BRACKL" >BRACKL</a> </span> 
--   
--   left bracket <span class="code" >[</span>   
--   <span class="code" ><b >protected</b> <a name="Token.BRACKR" >BRACKR</a> </span> 
--   
--   right bracket <span class="code" >]</span>   
--   <span class="code" ><b >protected</b> <a name="Token.COLON" >COLON</a> </span> 
--   
--   colon <span class="code" >:</span>   
--   <span class="code" ><b >protected</b> <a name="Token.COMMA" >COMMA</a> </span> 
--   
--   comma <span class="code" >,</span>   
--   <span class="code" ><b >protected</b> <a name="Token.ERROR" >ERROR</a> {offset ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a>, text ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#String" >String</a>}</span> 
--   
--   lexical error indicator   
--   <span class="code" ><b >protected</b> <a name="Token.FALSE" >FALSE</a> </span> 
--   
--   <span class="code" >false</span>   
--   <span class="code" ><b >protected</b> <a name="Token.N" >N</a> {nval ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#String" >String</a>}</span> 
--   
--   a JSON number, <span class="unknown" >atod</span> will work   
--   <span class="code" ><b >protected</b> <a name="Token.NULL" >NULL</a> </span> 
--   
--   <span class="code" >null</span> (o noes!!!)   
--   <span class="code" ><b >protected</b> <a name="Token.S" >S</a> {sval ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#String" >String</a>}</span> 
--   
--   a JSON string, escapes already decoded   
--   <span class="code" ><b >protected</b> <a name="Token.TRUE" >TRUE</a> </span> 
--   
--   <span class="code" >true</span>    <h3 > Member Functions</h3>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Token.nval" >nval</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/JSON#Token" >Token</a></b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#String" >String</a></span> 
--   
--   access field <span class="code" >nval</span>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Token.offset" >offset</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/JSON#Token" >Token</a></b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a></span> 
--   
--   access field <span class="code" >offset</span>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Token.sval" >sval</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/JSON#Token" >Token</a></b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#String" >String</a></span> 
--   
--   access field <span class="code" >sval</span>
