--   access field <span class="code" >getLast</span>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Monoid#Last
data Last a

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Monoid#Last.Last
Last {getLast ∷ Maybe a}

-- | A non-empty list
module frege.data.NonEmpty

-- | A <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/NonEmpty#NonEmpty" >NonEmpty</a> is like a list, but never empty. <h3 > Constructors</h3>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="NonEmpty.NonEmpty" >NonEmpty</a> {neHead ∷ a, neTail ∷ [a]}</span> 
--     <h3 > Member Functions</h3>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="NonEmpty.neHead" >neHead</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/NonEmpty#NonEmpty" >NonEmpty</a> α</b> → α</span> 
--   
--   access field <span class="code" >neHead</span>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="NonEmpty.neTail" >neTail</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/NonEmpty#NonEmpty" >NonEmpty</a> α</b> → [α]</span> 
--   
--   The head of the non-empty list. The tail of the non-empty list.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/NonEmpty#NonEmpty
data NonEmpty a

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/NonEmpty#NonEmpty.NonEmpty
NonEmpty {neHead ∷ a, neTail ∷ [a]}

-- | Constructs a non-empty list with the given head and tail.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/NonEmpty#nonEmpty
nonEmpty ∷ a → [a] → NonEmpty a

-- | Constructs a non-empty list with the given head and tail (an alias for <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/NonEmpty#nonEmpty" >nonEmpty</a>).
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/NonEmpty#_bar_colon
(|:) ∷  a → [a] → NonEmpty a 
infixr  6

-- | Tries to convert a list to a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/NonEmpty#NonEmpty" >NonEmpty</a> returning <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Maybe.Nothing" >Maybe.Nothing</a> if the given list is empty.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/NonEmpty#toNonEmpty
toNonEmpty ∷ [a] → Maybe (NonEmpty a)

-- | Converts a list to a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/NonEmpty#NonEmpty" >NonEmpty</a> using the given default value for the empty list case.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/NonEmpty#toNonEmpty_tick
toNonEmpty' ∷ NonEmpty a → [a] → NonEmpty a

-- | <i >WARNING: Fails if given the empty list.</i> 
--   Tries to convert a list to a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/NonEmpty#NonEmpty" >NonEmpty</a>.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/NonEmpty#unsafeToNonEmpty
unsafeToNonEmpty ∷ [a] → NonEmpty a

-- | Prepends a value to a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/NonEmpty#NonEmpty" >NonEmpty</a>.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/NonEmpty#_dot_colon
(.:) ∷  a → NonEmpty a → NonEmpty a 
infixr  6

-- | Reverses the elements of the (finite) <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/NonEmpty#NonEmpty" >NonEmpty</a>.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/NonEmpty#reverse
reverse ∷ NonEmpty a → NonEmpty a

-- | scanl is similar to foldl, but returns a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/NonEmpty#NonEmpty" >NonEmpty</a> of successive reduced values from the left
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/NonEmpty#scanl
scanl ∷ (b → a → b) → b → NonEmpty a → NonEmpty b

-- | scanl1 is similar to foldl1, but returns a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/NonEmpty#NonEmpty" >NonEmpty</a> of successive reduced values from the left
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/NonEmpty#scanl1
scanl1 ∷ (a → a → a) → NonEmpty a → NonEmpty a

-- | scanr is similar to foldr, but returns a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/NonEmpty#NonEmpty" >NonEmpty</a> of successive reduced values from the right
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/NonEmpty#scanr
scanr ∷ (a → b → b) → b → NonEmpty a → NonEmpty b

-- | scanr1 is similar to foldr1, but returns a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/NonEmpty#NonEmpty" >NonEmpty</a> of successive reduced values from the right
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/NonEmpty#scanr1
scanr1 ∷ (a → a → a) → NonEmpty a → NonEmpty a

-- | iterate f x returns an infinite <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/NonEmpty#NonEmpty" >NonEmpty</a> of repeated applications of f to x
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/NonEmpty#iterate
iterate ∷ (a → a) → a → NonEmpty a

-- | cycle ties a finite <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/NonEmpty#NonEmpty" >NonEmpty</a> into a circular one, or equivalently, the infinite repetition of the original <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/NonEmpty#NonEmpty" >NonEmpty</a>. It is the identity on infinite <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/NonEmpty#NonEmpty" >NonEmpty</a>s.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/NonEmpty#cycle
cycle ∷ ListSource src ⇒ src a → NonEmpty a

-- | The inits function returns all initial segments of the argument, shortest first.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/NonEmpty#inits
inits ∷ NonEmpty a → [NonEmpty a]

-- | The tails function returns all final segments of the argument, longest first.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/NonEmpty#tails
tails ∷ NonEmpty a → [NonEmpty a]

-- | The sort function implements a stable sorting algorithm.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/NonEmpty#sort
sort ∷ Ord a ⇒ NonEmpty a → NonEmpty a

-- | The insert function takes an element and a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/NonEmpty#NonEmpty" >NonEmpty</a> and inserts the element into the <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/NonEmpty#NonEmpty" >NonEmpty</a> at the last position where it is still less than or equal to the next element.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/NonEmpty#insert
insert ∷ Ord a ⇒ a → NonEmpty a → NonEmpty a

-- | unzip transforms a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/NonEmpty#NonEmpty" >NonEmpty</a> of pairs into a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/NonEmpty#NonEmpty" >NonEmpty</a> of first components and a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/NonEmpty#NonEmpty" >NonEmpty</a> of second components.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/NonEmpty#unzip
unzip ∷ NonEmpty (a, b) → (NonEmpty a, NonEmpty b)

-- | zip takes two <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/NonEmpty#NonEmpty" >NonEmpty</a>s and returns a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/NonEmpty#NonEmpty" >NonEmpty</a> of corresponding pairs. If one input <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/NonEmpty#NonEmpty" >NonEmpty</a>s is short, excess elements of the longer <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/NonEmpty#NonEmpty" >NonEmpty</a> are discarded.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/NonEmpty#zip
zip ∷ NonEmpty a → NonEmpty b → NonEmpty (a, b)

-- | A pair of two applicative functors, both applied to the same type
module frege.data.Product

-- | <h3 > Constructors</h3>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Product.Prod" >Prod</a> (f a)   (g a)</span>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Product#Product
data Product f g a

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Product#Product.Prod
Prod (f a)   (g a)

-- | view a tuple as <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Product#Product" >Product</a>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Product#product
product ∷ (γ α, β α) → Product γ β α

-- | make a tuple from a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Product#Product" >Product</a>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Product#unproduct
unproduct ∷ Product α γ β → (α β, γ β)

-- | Implementation of and functions for the <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Stream#Stream" >Stream</a> data type
module frege.data.Stream

-- | Streams are infinite lists. Most operations on streams are completely analogous to the definitions for []. 
--   Beware: If you use any function from the Eq or Ord class to compare two equal streams, these functions will diverge. <h3 > Constructors</h3>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Stream.Cons" >Cons</a> a   (<a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Stream#Stream" >Stream</a> a)<br ></br>
--  <b >infixr</b>  13</span>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Stream#Stream
data Stream a

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Stream#Stream.Cons
Cons a   (Stream a) 
infixr  13

-- | The <:> operator is a left strict infix version of the <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Stream#Stream.Cons" >Stream.Cons</a> constructor. 
--   In this module, it will always be used when the <i >head</i> part of a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Stream#Stream" >Stream</a> result is computed with some function passed as argument. 
--   This way, the strictness of the passed function is indirectly taken in account. 
--   For example, in the result of 
--  <pre>
--  
--   zipWith (,) stream1 stream2
--  </pre> 
--   the data of stream1 and stream2 are not evaluated, because the tuple constructor doesn't do it. 
--   Hence 
--  <pre>
--  
--   let us = repeat undefined in length &bull; take 10 &bull; zipWith (,) us $ us
--  </pre> 
--   will be 10. Whereas 
--  <pre>
--  
--   let us = repeat undefined in length &bull; take 10 &bull; zipWith (+) us $ us
--  </pre> 
--   will be undefined.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Stream#_lt_colon_gt
(<:>) ∷  a → Stream a → Stream a 
infixr  13

-- | The <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Stream#inits" >inits</a> function takes a stream xs and returns all the finite prefixes of xs. 
--   Note that this <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Stream#inits" >inits</a> is lazier then <a href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/./List.html#inits" >inits</a>: 
--  <pre>
--  
--   inits _|_ = [] ::: _|_
--  </pre> 
--   while for <a href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/./List.html#inits" >inits</a>: 
--  <pre>
--  
--   inits _|_ = _|_
--  </pre>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Stream#inits
inits ∷ Stream a → Stream [a]

-- | The <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Stream#tails" >tails</a> function takes a stream xs and returns all the suffixes of xs.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Stream#tails
tails ∷ Stream a → Stream (Stream a)

-- | Apply a function uniformly over all elements of a sequence.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Stream#map
map ∷ (a → b) → Stream a → Stream b

-- | intersperse y xs creates an alternating stream of elements from xs and y
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Stream#intersperse
intersperse ∷ a → Stream a → Stream a

-- | Interleave two Streams xs and ys, alternating elements from each list.  
--   x1,x2,... 
--   <div > `interleave` [y1,y2,...] == [x1,y1,x2,y2,...] </div>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Stream#interleave
interleave ∷ Stream a → Stream a → Stream a

-- | scan yields a stream of successive reduced values from: 
--   scan f z [x1, x2, ...] == [z, z `f` x1, (z `f` x1) `f` x2, ...]
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Stream#scan
scan ∷ (a → b → a) → a → Stream b → Stream a

-- | scan' is a strict scan.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Stream#scan_tick
scan' ∷ (a → b → a) → a → Stream b → Stream a

-- | scan1 is a variant of scan that has no starting value argument: 
--   scan1 f [x1, x2, ...] == [x1, x1 `f` x2, ...]
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Stream#scan1
scan1 ∷ (a → a → a) → Stream a → Stream a

-- | scan1' is a strict scan that has no starting value.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Stream#scan1_tick
scan1' ∷ (a → a → a) → Stream a → Stream a

-- | transpose computes the transposition of a stream of streams.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Stream#transpose
transpose ∷ Stream (Stream a) → Stream (Stream a)

-- | iterate f x function produces the infinite sequence of repeated applications of f to x. 
--   iterate f x = [x, f x, f (f x), ..]
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Stream#iterate
iterate ∷ (a → a) → a → Stream a

-- | repeat x returns a constant stream, where all elements are equal to x.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Stream#repeat
repeat ∷ a → Stream a

-- | cycle xs returns the infinite repetition of xs: 
--   cycle [1,2,3] = Cons 1 (Cons 2 (Cons 3 (Cons 1 (Cons 2 ...
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Stream#cycle
cycle ∷ [a] → Stream a

-- | The unfold function is similar to the unfold for lists. Note there is no base case: all streams must be infinite.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Stream#unfold
unfold ∷ (c → (a, c)) → c → Stream a

-- | The splitAt function takes an integer n and a stream xs and returns a pair consisting of the prefix of xs of length n and the remaining stream immediately following this prefix. 
--   Beware: passing a negative integer as the first argument will cause an error.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Stream#splitAt
splitAt ∷ Int → Stream a → ([a], Stream a)

-- | takeWhile p xs returns the longest prefix of the stream xs for which the predicate p holds.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Stream#takeWhile
takeWhile ∷ (a → Bool) → Stream a → [a]

-- | dropWhile p xs returns the suffix remaining after takeWhile p xs. 
--   Beware: this function may diverge if every element of xs satisfies p, e.g. dropWhile even (repeat 0) will loop.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Stream#dropWhile
dropWhile ∷ (a → Bool) → Stream a → Stream a

-- | span p xs returns the longest prefix of xs that satisfies p, together with the remainder of the stream.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Stream#span
span ∷ (a → Bool) → Stream a → ([a], Stream a)

-- | The break p function is equivalent to span (not <~ p).
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Stream#_break
break ∷ (a → Bool) → Stream a → ([a], Stream a)

-- | filter p xs removes any elements from xs that do not satisfy p. 
--   Beware: this function may diverge if there is no element of xs that satisfies p, e.g. filter odd (repeat 0) will loop.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Stream#filter
filter ∷ (a → Bool) → Stream a → Stream a

-- | The <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Stream#partition" >partition</a> function takes a predicate p and a stream xs<span class="code" >, and returns a pair of streams. The first stream corresponds to the elements of </span>xs@ for which p holds; the second stream corresponds to the elements of xs for which p does not hold. 
--   Beware: One of the elements of the tuple may be undefined. For example, fst (partition even (repeat 0)) == repeat 0; on the other hand snd (partition even (repeat 0)) is undefined.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Stream#partition
partition ∷ (a → Bool) → Stream a → (Stream a, Stream a)

-- | The group function takes a stream and returns a stream of lists such that flattening the resulting stream is equal to the argument. Moreover, each sublist in the resulting stream contains only equal elements. For example, 
--   group $ cycle "Mississippi" = "M" ::: "i" ::: "ss" ::: "i" ::: "ss" ::: "i" ::: "pp" ::: "i" ::: "M" ::: "i" ::: ...
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Stream#group
group ∷ Eq a ⇒ Stream a → Stream [a]

-- | The isPrefix function returns true if the first argument is a prefix of the second.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Stream#isPrefixOf
isPrefixOf ∷ Eq a ⇒ [a] → Stream a → Bool

-- | xs !! n returns the element of the stream xs at index n. Note that the head of the stream has index 0. 
--   Beware: passing a negative integer as the first argument will cause an error.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Stream#_excl_excl
(!!) ∷  Stream a → Int → a

-- | The elemIndex function returns the index of the first element in the given stream which is equal (by <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Eq._eq_eq" >Eq.==</a>) to the query element, 
--   Beware: elemIndex x xs will diverge if none of the elements of xs equal x.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Stream#elemIndex
elemIndex ∷ Eq a ⇒ a → Stream a → Int

-- | The elemIndices function extends elemIndex, by returning the indices of all elements equal to the query element, in ascending order. 
--   Beware: elemIndices x xs will diverge if any suffix of xs does not contain x.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Stream#elemIndices
elemIndices ∷ Eq a ⇒ a → Stream a → Stream Int

-- | The findIndex function takes a predicate and a stream and returns the index of the first element in the stream that satisfies the predicate, 
--   Beware: findIndex p xs will diverge if none of the elements of xs satisfy p.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Stream#findIndex
findIndex ∷ (a → Bool) → Stream a → Int

-- | The findIndices function extends findIndex, by returning the indices of all elements satisfying the predicate, in ascending order. 
--   Beware: findIndices p xs will diverge if all the elements of any suffix of xs fails to satisfy p.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Stream#findIndices
findIndices ∷ (a → Bool) → Stream a → Stream Int

-- | The zip function takes two streams and returns a list of corresponding pairs.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Stream#zip
zip ∷ Stream a → Stream b → Stream (a, b)

-- | The zipWith function generalizes zip. Rather than tupling the functions, the elements are combined using the function passed as the first argument to zipWith.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Stream#zipWith
zipWith ∷ (a → b → c) → Stream a → Stream b → Stream c

-- | The unzip function is the inverse of the zip function.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Stream#unzip
unzip ∷ Stream (a, b) → (Stream a, Stream b)

-- | The words function breaks a stream of characters into a stream of words, which were delimited by white space. 
--   Beware: if the stream of characters xs does not contain white space, accessing the tail of words xs will loop.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Stream#words
words ∷ Stream Char → Stream String

-- | The unwords function is an inverse operation to words. It joins words with separating spaces.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Stream#unwords
unwords ∷ Stream String → Stream Char

-- | The lines function breaks a stream of characters into a list of strings at newline characters. The resulting strings do not contain newlines. 
--   Beware: if the stream of characters xs does not contain newline characters, accessing the tail of lines xs will loop.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Stream#lines
lines ∷ Stream Char → Stream String

-- | The unlines function is an inverse operation to lines. It joins lines, after appending a terminating newline to each.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Stream#unlines
unlines ∷ Stream String → Stream Char

-- | The <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Stream#fromList" >fromList</a> converts an infinite list to a stream. 
--   Beware: Passing a finite list, will cause an error.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Stream#fromList
fromList ∷ [a] → Stream a

-- | Functors representing data structures that can be traversed from left to right.
module frege.data.Traversable

-- | Functors representing data structures that can be traversed from left to right. 
--   Minimal complete definition: <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Traversable#Traversable.traverse" >Traversable.traverse</a> or <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Traversable#Traversable.sequenceA" >Traversable.sequenceA</a>. 
--   The superclass instances should satisfy the following: 
--   In the <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeMonad.html#Functor" >Functor</a> instance, <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeMonad.html#Functor.fmap" >Functor.fmap</a> should be equivalent to traversal with the identity applicative functor (<a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Traversable#fmapDefault" >fmapDefault</a>). 
--   In the <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/./Foldable.html#Foldable" >Foldable</a> instance, <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/./Foldable.html#Foldable.foldMap" >Foldable.foldMap</a> should be equivalent to traversal with a constant applicative functor (<a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Traversable#foldMapDefault" >foldMapDefault</a>). 
--   Note that the functions <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Traversable#Traversable.mapM" >Traversable.mapM</a>, <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Traversable#Traversable.sequence" >Traversable.sequence</a>, <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Traversable#forM" >forM</a> are just specialized versions of <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Traversable#Traversable.traverse" >Traversable.traverse</a>, <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Traversable#Traversable.sequenceA" >Traversable.sequenceA</a> and <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Traversable#_for" >for</a>, and wouldn't be required in Frege. They are included for Haskell compatibility only. In Haskell the specialized functions are needed as Haskell monads are no Applicatives. <h3 > Known Instances</h3> 
--   <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Traversable#Traversable_Maybe" >Maybe</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Traversable#Traversable_Identity" >Identity.Identity</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Traversable#Traversable__lbrack_rbrack" >[]</a> <h3 > Member Functions</h3>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Traversable.mapM" >mapM</a> ∷ (<a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Traversable#Traversable" >Traversable</a> t, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeMonad.html#Monad" >Monad</a> m) ⇒ (a → m b) → t a → m (t b)</span> 
--   
--   Map each element of a structure to a monadic action, evaluate these actions from left to right, and collect the results. This function exists for Haskell compatibility only.  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Traversable.sequence" >sequence</a> ∷ (<a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Traversable#Traversable" >Traversable</a> t, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeMonad.html#Monad" >Monad</a> m) ⇒ t (m a) → m (t a)</span> 
--   
--   Evaluate each monadic action in the structure from left to right, and collect the results. This function exists for Haskell compatibility only.  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Traversable.sequenceA" >sequenceA</a> ∷ (<a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Traversable#Traversable" >Traversable</a> t, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeMonad.html#Applicative" >Applicative</a> f) ⇒ t (f a) → f (t a)</span> 
--   
--   Evaluate each action in the structure from left to right, and collect the results.  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Traversable.traverse" >traverse</a> ∷ (<a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Traversable#Traversable" >Traversable</a> t, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeMonad.html#Applicative" >Applicative</a> f) ⇒ (a → f b) → t a → f (t b)</span> 
--   
--   Map each element of a structure to an action, evaluate these actions from left to right, and collect the results.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Traversable#Traversable
class (Functor t, Foldable t) ⇒ Traversable t

-- | Map each element of a structure to a monadic action, evaluate these actions from left to right, and collect the results. This function exists for Haskell compatibility only.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Traversable#Traversable.mapM
mapM ∷ (Traversable t, Monad m) ⇒ (a → m b) → t a → m (t b)

-- | Evaluate each monadic action in the structure from left to right, and collect the results. This function exists for Haskell compatibility only.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Traversable#Traversable.sequence
sequence ∷ (Traversable t, Monad m) ⇒ t (m a) → m (t a)

-- | Evaluate each action in the structure from left to right, and collect the results.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Traversable#Traversable.sequenceA
sequenceA ∷ (Traversable t, Applicative f) ⇒ t (f a) → f (t a)

-- | Map each element of a structure to an action, evaluate these actions from left to right, and collect the results.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Traversable#Traversable.traverse
traverse ∷ (Traversable t, Applicative f) ⇒ (a → f b) → t a → f (t b)

-- | <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Traversable#_for" >for</a> is <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Traversable#Traversable.traverse" >Traversable.traverse</a> with its arguments flipped.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Traversable#_for
for ∷ (Traversable t, Applicative f) ⇒ t a → (a → f b) → f (t b)

-- | <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Traversable#forM" >forM</a> is <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Traversable#Traversable.mapM" >Traversable.mapM</a> with its arguments flipped. 
--   This function exists for Haskell compatibility only.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Traversable#forM
forM ∷ (Traversable t, Monad m) ⇒ t a → (a → m b) → m (t b)

-- | <h3 > Constructors</h3>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="StateL.StateL" >StateL</a> {run ∷ s → (s, a)}</span> 
--     <h3 > Member Functions</h3>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="StateL.run" >run</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Traversable#StateL" >StateL</a> α β</b> → α → (α, β)</span> 
--   
--   access field <span class="code" >run</span>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Traversable#StateL
data StateL s a

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Traversable#StateL.StateL
StateL {run ∷ s → (s, a)}

-- | The <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Traversable#mapAccumL" >mapAccumL</a> function behaves like a combination of <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeMonad.html#Functor.fmap" >Functor.fmap</a> and <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/./Foldable.html#Foldable.fold" >Foldable.fold</a>; it applies a function to each element of a structure, passing an accumulating parameter from left to right, and returning a final value of this accumulator together with the new structure.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Traversable#mapAccumL
mapAccumL ∷ Traversable t ⇒ (a → b → (a, c)) → a → t b → (a, t c)

-- | <h3 > Constructors</h3>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="StateR.StateR" >StateR</a> {run ∷ s → (s, a)}</span> 
--     <h3 > Member Functions</h3>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="StateR.run" >run</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Traversable#StateR" >StateR</a> α β</b> → α → (α, β)</span> 
--   
--   access field <span class="code" >run</span>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Traversable#StateR
data StateR s a

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Traversable#StateR.StateR
StateR {run ∷ s → (s, a)}

-- | The <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Traversable#mapAccumR" >mapAccumR</a> function behaves like a combination of <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeMonad.html#Functor.fmap" >Functor.fmap</a> and <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/./Foldable.html#Foldable.foldr" >Foldable.foldr</a>; it applies a function to each element of a structure, passing an accumulating parameter from right to left, and returning a final value of this accumulator together with the new structure.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Traversable#mapAccumR
mapAccumR ∷ Traversable t ⇒ (a → b → (a, c)) → a → t b → (a, t c)

-- | This function may be used as a value for `fmap` in a `Functor` instance, provided that <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Traversable#Traversable.traverse" >Traversable.traverse</a> is defined. (Using <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Traversable#fmapDefault" >fmapDefault</a> with a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Traversable#Traversable" >Traversable</a> instance defined only by <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Traversable#Traversable.sequenceA" >Traversable.sequenceA</a> will result in infinite recursion.)
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Traversable#fmapDefault
fmapDefault ∷ Traversable t ⇒ (a → b) → t a → t b

-- | This function may be used as a value for `Data.Foldable.foldMap` in a `Foldable` instance.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Traversable#foldMapDefault
foldMapDefault ∷ (Traversable t, Monoid m) ⇒ (a → m) → t a → m

-- | Multi-way trees (<i >aka</i> rose trees) and forests. 
--   Module 
--   <div > Data.Tree </div>  
--   Copyright 
--   <div > (c) The University of Glasgow 2002 </div>  
--   License 
--   <div > BSD-style (see the file libraries/base/LICENSE) </div>  
--   This is a port of Haskell library code.
module frege.data.Tree

-- | Multi-way trees, also known as <i >rose trees</i>.  <h3 > Constructors</h3>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Tree.Node" >Node</a> {rootLabel ∷ a, subForest ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Tree#Forest" >Forest</a> a}</span> 
--     <h3 > Member Functions</h3>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Tree.rootLabel" >rootLabel</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Tree#Tree" >Tree</a> α</b> → α</span> 
--   
--   access field <span class="code" >rootLabel</span>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Tree.subForest" >subForest</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Tree#Tree" >Tree</a> α</b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Tree#Forest" >Forest</a> α</span> 
--   
--   label value zero or more child trees
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Tree#Tree
data Tree a

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Tree#Tree.Node
Node {rootLabel ∷ a, subForest ∷ Forest a}

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Tree#Forest
type Forest a = [Tree a]

-- | Neat 2-dimensional drawing of a tree.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Tree#drawTree
drawTree ∷ Tree String → String

-- | Neat 2-dimensional drawing of a forest.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Tree#drawForest
drawForest ∷ Forest String → String

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Tree#draw
draw ∷ Tree String → [String]

-- | The elements of a tree in pre-order.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Tree#flatten
flatten ∷ Tree a → [a]

-- | Lists of nodes at each level of the tree.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Tree#levels
levels ∷ Tree a → [[a]]

-- | Build a tree from a seed value
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Tree#unfoldTree
unfoldTree ∷ (b → (a, [b])) → b → Tree a

-- | Build a forest from a list of seed values
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Tree#unfoldForest
unfoldForest ∷ (b → (a, [b])) → [b] → Forest a

-- | Monadic tree builder, in depth-first order
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Tree#unfoldTreeM
unfoldTreeM ∷ Monad m ⇒ (b → m (a, [b])) → b → m (Tree a)

-- | Monadic forest builder, in depth-first order
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/Tree#unfoldForestM
unfoldForestM ∷ Monad m ⇒ (b → m (a, [b])) → [b] → m (Forest a)

-- | An efficient implementation of <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Persistent_data_structure" >persistent</a> ordered maps from keys to values based on <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/AVL_tree" >AVL trees</a>.<h2 > Properties of ordered maps</h2>
--   An AVL tree is a self-balancing binary search tree. In an AVL tree, the heights of the two child subtrees of any node differ by at most one; if at any time they differ by more than one, rebalancing is done to restore this property.
--   Lookup, insertion, and deletion all take O(log n) time in both the average and worst cases, where n is the number of nodes in the tree prior to the operation. Insertions and deletions may require the tree to be rebalanced by one or more tree rotations.
--   AVL trees are height-balanced, but not weight-balanced nor μ-balanced, that is, sibling nodes can have hugely differing numbers of descendants.<h2 > Properties of this implementation</h2>
--   Keys will always be strict, whereas values can remain un-evaluated until two values will have to be combined.
--   Combination of two values takes place when a mapping for an already existing key is inserted in a map. In order to prevent building up of thunks that could lead to stack overflows later, the function combining the values will be evaluated right away, and this may trigger evaluation of one or both values in turn.
--   The default function used by operations like <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#insert" >insert</a> or <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#union" >union</a> is <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#_const" >const</a>; and this will cause evaluation of the <b >new</b> value. Take a look at the following example:
--  <pre>
--  
--   insert 7 undefined (insert 7 25 empty)            -- will fail
--   insert 7 42 (insert 7 undefined empty)            -- will succeed
--   insertWith (+) 7 42 (insert 7 undefined empty)    -- will fail
--  </pre>
--   The last expression will fail because (<a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Num._plus" >Num.+</a>) needs to evaluate both arguments. OTOH, expressions like
--  <pre>
--  
--   fold (\t\v -&gt; insertWith (+) 42 v t) empty [1..1_000_000]
--  </pre>
--   will not cause stack overflow when later the value associated with 42 is actually used, nor will it need heap memory for one million thunks.<h2 > Operations</h2><h3 > Creating Maps</h3>
--   Get an empty map with <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/./Monoid.html#Monoid.mempty" >Monoid.mempty</a> or <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeList.html#ListEmpty.empty" >ListEmpty.empty</a>, make a singleton one with <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#singleton" >singleton</a> or turn an association list into a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#TreeMap" >TreeMap</a> with <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#fromList" >fromList</a>. The more general function <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#fromListWith" >fromListWith</a> allows custom handling of associations with duplicate keys.<h2 > Add, Change or Remove Associations</h2>
--   Use <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#insert" >insert</a>, <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#delete" >delete</a>, <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#adjust" >adjust</a> and <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#replace" >replace</a>. The more general form of <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#insert" >insert</a> is <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#insertWith" >insertWith</a> which accepts a function to combine the given value with an already existing one.<h2 > Lookups</h2>
--   The basic function is <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#lookup" >lookup</a>, of which <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#member" >member</a> and <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#lookupDefault" >lookupDefault</a> are variants. The operator (<a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#_excl_excl" >!!</a>) may be used when the existence of the keys looked for is out of the question.
--   Because a tree map is ordered, we can find the associations with the smallest and largest keys in logarithmic time. See <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#findMin" >findMin</a> and <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#findMax" >findMax</a>.<h2 > Set operations</h2>
--   There is <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#union" >union</a>, <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#difference" >difference</a> and <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#intersection" >intersection</a>. More general functions <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#unionWith" >unionWith</a> and <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#intersectionWith" >intersectionWith</a> allow combination of the affected values.<h2 > Folds</h2>
--   Left folds as well as right folds are provided by <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#foldValues" >foldValues</a> and <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#foldrValues" >foldrValues</a>. Variants <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#foldWithKey" >foldWithKey</a> and <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#foldrWithKey" >foldrWithKey</a> allow examination not only of the value, but also of the key and they walk the tree in key order.
--   Frequently needed functions such as <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#values" >values</a>, <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#keys" >keys</a>, <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#each" >each</a> and <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#size" >size</a> are just predefined folds for your convenience.<h2 > Filtering</h2>
--   Create a subset of an existing map with <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#filterValues" >filterValues</a> or <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#filterWithKey" >filterWithKey</a>.<h2 > Transformations</h2>
--   <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#mapValues" >mapValues</a>, <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#mapWithKey" >mapWithKey</a> and <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#traverseWithKey" >traverseWithKey</a> should cover any need to transform an existing map.<h3 > Naming Conventions</h3>
--   Functions whose name have the <i >With</i> suffix take a custom function to combine two values and are thus more general than the ones without that suffix. Most often it is the case that
--  <pre>
--  
--   xxx = xxxWith const
--  </pre>
--   Functions whose name have the <i >Values</i> suffix operate on the values of the mappings contained in the map and take an appropriate custom function as argument. The <i >Values</i> suffix also serves to avoid conflicts with Prelude functions (i.e. <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeList.html#map" >map</a>, <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeList.html#filter" >filter</a>, <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeList.html#fold" >fold</a>, <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeList.html#foldr" >foldr</a>).
--   The companions of the <i >Values</i> functions have the suffix <i >WithKey</i> and accept functions that take an extra argument for the key. The key portion of a mapping or association is always passed first, followed by the associated value.
module frege.data.TreeMap

-- | <i >O(1)</i> Create a singleton map
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#singleton
singleton ∷ Ord k ⇒ k → v → TreeMap k v

-- | <i >O(n)</i> Compute the size of the map
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#size
size ∷ TreeMap k v → Int

-- | <i >O(log n)</i> 
--  <pre>
--  
--   insert k v map
--  </pre> 
--   returns a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#TreeMap" >TreeMap</a> where <i >k</i> is associated with <i >v</i> such that 
--  <pre>
--  
--   lookup k (insert k v map) = Just v
--  </pre> 
--   If <i >k</i> was already associated with some value in <i >map</i>, then <i >v</i> will get evaluated to WHNF, otherwise it is left alone.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#insert
insert ∷ Ord α ⇒ α → β → TreeMap α β → TreeMap α β

-- | <i >O(log n)</i> 
--  <pre>
--  
--   insertWith f k v m
--  </pre> 
--   If <i >m</i> does not contain <i >k</i>, this works like <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#insert" >insert</a>. Otherwise, the existing association of <i >k</i> with some value <i >v'</i> is replaced by an association of <i >k</i> with the result of evaluating 
--  <pre>
--  
--   f v v'
--  </pre> 
--   in the resulting map. 
--   Strict evaluation is necessary to prevent building up of large thunks of the form 
--  <pre>
--  
--   f v3 (f v2 (f v1 v0))
--  </pre> 
--   Note that 
--  <pre>
--  
--   insert = insertWith const
--  </pre> 
--   and that this will evaluate the <b >new</b> value in case of an update. If you want to prevent this, use 
--  <pre>
--  
--   replace k v = insert k v . delete k
--  </pre> 
--   The replaced value will be evaluated only if the given function is strict in the second argument. Since <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#_const" >const</a> is lazy in the second argument, the following will be fine: 
--  <pre>
--  
--   insert &quot;foo&quot; 7 (insert &quot;foo&quot; undefined (delete &quot;foo&quot; m))
--  </pre> 
--   That is, the value that is inserted for a given key first is not evaluated on insertion, and only evaluated on update if the update function demands it, which is not the case for a plain <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#insert" >insert</a>.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#insertWith
insertWith ∷ Ord α ⇒ (β→β→β) → α → β → TreeMap α β → TreeMap α β

-- | <i >O(log n)</i> 
--  <pre>
--  
--   delete k tm
--  </pre> 
--   is a <span class="unknown" >HashMap</span> m such that 
--  <pre>
--  
--   lookup k m = Nothing
--  </pre> 
--   and for any other key <i >o</i> 
--  <pre>
--  
--   lookup o m = lookup o tm
--  </pre> 
--   Less formally, the association of <i >k</i> with some value, if any, is removed in the result, while all other associations are retained. 
--   If <i >tm</i> didn't contain <i >k</i> in the first place, 
--  <pre>
--  
--   delete k tm = tm
--  </pre>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#delete
delete ∷ Ord k ⇒ k → TreeMap k v → TreeMap k v

-- | <i >O(log n)</i> 
--  <pre>
--  
--   lookup k m
--  </pre> 
--   If <i >k</i> is associated with some value <i >v</i> in map <i >m</i>, it returns 
--  <pre>
--  
--   Just v
--  </pre> 
--   and otherwise 
--  <pre>
--  
--   Nothing
--  </pre>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#lookup
lookup ∷ Ord k ⇒ k → TreeMap k v → Maybe v

-- | <i >O(log n)</i> 
--   Find the minimum element in the tree. For empty trees, this is <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Maybe.Nothing" >Maybe.Nothing</a>.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#findMin
findMin ∷ TreeMap k v → Maybe (k, v)

-- | <i >O(log n)</i> 
--   Find the maximum element in the tree. For empty trees, this is <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Maybe.Nothing" >Maybe.Nothing</a>.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#findMax
findMax ∷ TreeMap k v → Maybe (k, v)

-- | <i >O(log n)</i> 
--   Checks whether the key is present in the map
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#member
member ∷ Ord a ⇒ a → TreeMap a b → Bool

-- | <i >O(log n)</i> 
--   Return the value to which the specified key is mapped, or the default value if this map contains no mapping for the key.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#lookupDefault
lookupDefault ∷ Ord b ⇒ a → b → TreeMap b a → a

-- | <i >O(log n)</i> 
--   Return the value associated with the given key in the map. Fails with <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#error" >error</a> if the key is not present.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#_excl_excl
(!!) ∷  Ord k ⇒ TreeMap k v → k → v 
infixl  16

-- | <i >O(log n)</i> 
--   Adjust the value tied to a given key in this map only if it is present. Otherwise, leave the map alone.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#adjust
adjust ∷ Ord k ⇒ (v → v) → k → TreeMap k v → TreeMap k v

-- | <i >O(log n)</i> 
--  <pre>
--  
--   replace k v m = insert k v . delete k $ m
--  </pre> 
--   Insert or update the association of <i >k</i> with <i >v</i> in <i >m</i> but avoid evaluation of <i >v</i> even if <i >m</i> already contains <i >k</i>. 
--   See also notes concerning updates on function <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#insertWith" >insertWith</a>.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#replace
replace ∷ Ord k ⇒ k → v → TreeMap k v → TreeMap k v

-- | <i >O(m*log n)</i> 
--  <pre>
--  
--   unionWith f left right
--  </pre> 
--   Computes the union of two hash maps by inserting the elements of the <i >left</i> map into the <i >right</i> map. 
--   If a key occurs in both maps, the function <i >f</i> provided in the first argument will be applied to the value from the <i >left</i> map and the <i >right</i> map like so: 
--  <pre>
--  
--   f leftval rightval
--  </pre> 
--   to compute the result that goes into the resulting map. 
--   This works in the same way as <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#insertWith" >insertWith</a>, that is, the value from the <i >left</i> hash map will be evaluated while the value from the <i >right</i> map may be evaluated only if the function demands it. However, values associated with keys that are member of only one map are left alone.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#unionWith
unionWith ∷ Ord k ⇒ (v → v → v) → TreeMap k v → TreeMap k v → TreeMap k v

-- | <i >O(m*log n)</i> 
--   Computes the union of two hash maps. 
--   If a key occurs in both maps, the value from the left map will be evaluated and taken over to the new map. 
--   Because 
--  <pre>
--  
--   union  =  unionWith const
--  </pre> 
--   the considerations concerning strictness apply for <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#union" >union</a> in the same way as for <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#unionWith" >unionWith</a>.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#union
union ∷ Ord k ⇒ TreeMap k v → TreeMap k v → TreeMap k v

-- | The union of all <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#TreeMap" >TreeMap</a>s in a list.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#unions
unions ∷ Ord k ⇒ [TreeMap k v] → TreeMap k v

-- | <i >O(n)</i> 
--  <pre>
--  
--   foldValues f a map
--  </pre> 
--   applies the operation <i >f</i> to the values in the <i >map</i> in no particular order.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#foldValues
foldValues ∷ (a → v → a) → a → TreeMap k v → a

-- | <i >O(n)</i> 
--  <pre>
--  
--   foldWithKey f a map
--  </pre> 
--   applies the operation <i >f</i> to the keys and values in the <i >map</i> using the left identity <i >a</i> as starting value from the left in ascending key order. 
--  <pre>
--  
--   f (f (f a k0 v0) k1 v1) kn vn
--  </pre>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#foldWithKey
foldWithKey ∷ (a → c → b → a) → a → TreeMap c b → a

-- | <i >O(n)</i> 
--  <pre>
--  
--   foldrValues f a map
--  </pre> 
--   applies the operation <i >f</i> to the values in the <i >map</i> in no particular order.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#foldrValues
foldrValues ∷ (v → a → a) → a → TreeMap k v → a

-- | <i >O(n)</i> 
--  <pre>
--  
--   foldrWithKey f a map
--  </pre> 
--   applies the operation <i >f</i> to the keys and values in the <i >map</i> using the right identity <i >a</i> as starting value from the right in descending key order: 
--  <pre>
--  
--   f k0 v0 (f k1 v1 (f kn vn a))
--  </pre>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#foldrWithKey
foldrWithKey ∷ (c → b → a → a) → a → TreeMap c b → a

-- | <i >O(n)</i> 
--   Transform a map by applying a function to every value.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#mapValues
mapValues ∷ (v → u) → TreeMap k v → TreeMap k u

-- | <i >O(n)</i> 
--   Transform a map by applying a function to every key and its associated value.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#mapWithKey
mapWithKey ∷ (k → v → u) → TreeMap k v → TreeMap k u

-- | <i >O(n)</i> 
--   Transform a map by applying an applicative functor to every key and its associated value.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#traverseWithKey
traverseWithKey ∷ Applicative a ⇒ (k → v → a u) → TreeMap k v → a (TreeMap k u)

-- | <i >O(n)</i> 
--   Filter a map, retaining only mappings whose key and value satisfy a given predicate.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#filterWithKey
filterWithKey ∷ Ord k ⇒ (k → v → Bool) → TreeMap k v → TreeMap k v

-- | <i >O(n)</i> 
--   Filter a map, retaining only mappings whose value satisfies a given predicate.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#filterValues
filterValues ∷ Ord k ⇒ (v → Bool) → TreeMap k v → TreeMap k v

-- | <i >O(n*log m)</i> 
--   Computes the difference of two maps. 
--   Returns a map that contains the mappings of the first map whose keys do not exist in the second.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#difference
difference ∷ Ord k ⇒ TreeMap k v → TreeMap k u → TreeMap k v

-- | <i >O(n*log m)</i> 
--   Computes the intersection of two maps. 
--   Return a map that contains the mappings of the first map for keys that also exist in the second.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#intersection
intersection ∷ Ord k ⇒ TreeMap k v → TreeMap k u → TreeMap k v

-- | <i >O(n*log m)</i> 
--   Computes the intersection of two maps, combining the values with a given function.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#intersectionWith
intersectionWith ∷ Ord k ⇒ (v → u → w) → TreeMap k v → TreeMap k u → TreeMap k w

-- | <i >O(n)</i> 
--   Build a map from an association list. If the list contains duplicate mappings, the later mappings take precedence.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#fromList
fromList ∷ Ord a ⇒ [(a, b)] → TreeMap a b

-- | <i >O(n)</i> 
--   Build a map from an association list. Uses the provided function to merge values associated with duplicate keys.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#fromListWith
fromListWith ∷ Ord k ⇒ (v → v → v) → [(k, v)] → TreeMap k v

-- | produces a list of the values in the map, in no particular order.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#values
values ∷ TreeMap a b → [b]

-- | produces the key/value pairs of a map sorted by key
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#each
each ∷ TreeMap a b → [(a, b)]

-- | produces the keys of the map in ascending order
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#keys
keys ∷ TreeMap a b → [a]

-- | <h3 > Constructors</h3>  
--   <span class="code" ><b >protected</b> <a name="TreeMap.Leaf" >Leaf</a> {key ∷ k, value ∷ v}</span> 
--   
--   short for Node 1 Nil Nil k v   
--   <span class="code" ><b >protected</b> <a name="TreeMap.Nil" >Nil</a> </span> 
--   
--   the empty tree   
--   <span class="code" ><b >protected</b> <a name="TreeMap.Node" >Node</a> {höhe ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a>, left ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#TreeMap" >TreeMap</a> k v, right ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#TreeMap" >TreeMap</a> k v, key ∷ k, value ∷ v}</span> 
--     <h3 > Member Functions</h3>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="TreeMap.balance" >balance</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#TreeMap" >TreeMap</a> α β</b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a></span> 
--    
--   <span class="code" ><a name="TreeMap.delete" >delete</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Ord" >Ord</a> β ⇒ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#TreeMap" >TreeMap</a> β α</b> → β → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#TreeMap" >TreeMap</a> β α</span> 
--   
--   <i >O(log n)</i> 
--  <pre>
--  
--   tm.delete k
--  </pre> 
--   Variant of <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#delete" >delete</a> that is better suited for left folds and supports dot-notation   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="TreeMap.drotlr" >drotlr</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#TreeMap" >TreeMap</a> β α</b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#TreeMap" >TreeMap</a> β α</span> 
--    
--   <span class="code" ><a name="TreeMap.drotrl" >drotrl</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#TreeMap" >TreeMap</a> α β</b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#TreeMap" >TreeMap</a> α β</span> 
--    
--   <span class="code" ><a name="TreeMap.filterKV" >filterKV</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Ord" >Ord</a> k ⇒ (<b >k → v → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Bool" >Bool</a></b>) → <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#TreeMap" >TreeMap</a> k v</b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#TreeMap" >TreeMap</a> k v</span> 
--    
--   <span class="code" ><a name="TreeMap.foldL" >foldL</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Ordering" >Ordering</a></b> → (<b >c → a → b → c</b>) → <b >c</b> → <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#TreeMap" >TreeMap</a> a b</b> → c</span> 
--   
--  <pre>
--  
--   foldL o f a map
--  </pre> 
--   Fold a tree by applying an operation to an accumulator and key and value of every node, whereby the nodes are visited in a certain order specified by the first argument. Let the tree be 
--  <pre>
--  
--                         root
--                       /     \
--                      /       \
--                     left    right
--  </pre> 
--   then the result is: <ul > <li > <span class="code" >Eq</span> the operation is first applied to the root node, and the result is passed to the left subtree, and the result of that is passed to the fold of the right subtree. Also known as "preorder" traversal.</li> <li > <span class="code" >Lt</span> the operation is applied to the result of the fold done with the left sub-tree and the root node, and the result of that is passed to the fold of the right subtree. Also known as "inorder" traversal. This causes the operation to get applied to the key/value pairs in ascending key order.</li> <li > <span class="code" >Gt</span> like with <span class="code" >Lt</span>, but the subtrees are processed in reverse order, which results in application of the operation to the key/value pairs in descending order.</li> </ul>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="TreeMap.foldR" >foldR</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Ordering" >Ordering</a></b> → (<b >a → b → c → c</b>) → <b >c</b> → <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#TreeMap" >TreeMap</a> a b</b> → c</span> 
--   
--   foldR o f a map 
--   Like <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#TreeMap.foldL" >TreeMap.foldL</a>, but the function is right associative. 
--   The following yields the key of <i >map</i> in ascending order: 
--  <pre>
--  
--   foldR Gt (\k\v\a &rarr; k:a) [] map   
--  </pre>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="TreeMap.height" >height</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#TreeMap" >TreeMap</a> β α</b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a></span> 
--    
--   <span class="code" ><a name="TreeMap.höhe" >höhe</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#TreeMap" >TreeMap</a> β α</b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a></span> 
--   
--   access field <span class="code" >höhe</span>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="TreeMap.index" >index</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Ord" >Ord</a> β ⇒ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#TreeMap" >TreeMap</a> β α</b> → <b >β</b> → α</span> 
--    
--   <span class="code" ><a name="TreeMap.insert" >insert</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Ord" >Ord</a> a ⇒ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#TreeMap" >TreeMap</a> a b</b> → <b >a</b> → b → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#TreeMap" >TreeMap</a> a b</span> 
--   
--   <i >O(log n)</i> 
--  <pre>
--  
--   tm.insert k v
--  </pre> 
--   Variant of <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#insert" >insert</a> that is better suited for left folds and supports dot-notation.   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="TreeMap.insertI" >insertI</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#TreeMap" >TreeMap</a> <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a> value</b> → <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a></b> → value → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#TreeMap" >TreeMap</a> <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a> value</span> 
--   
--   version of insert that is optimized for <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a> keys   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="TreeMap.insertList" >insertList</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Ord" >Ord</a> a ⇒ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#TreeMap" >TreeMap</a> a b</b> → <b >[(a, b)]</b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#TreeMap" >TreeMap</a> a b</span> 
--    
--   <span class="code" ><a name="TreeMap.insertS" >insertS</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#TreeMap" >TreeMap</a> <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#String" >String</a> value</b> → <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#String" >String</a></b> → value → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#TreeMap" >TreeMap</a> <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#String" >String</a> value</span> 
--    
--   <span class="code" ><a name="TreeMap.insertWork" >insertWork</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Ord" >Ord</a> α ⇒ (β→β→β) → <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#TreeMap" >TreeMap</a> α β</b> → <b >α</b> → β → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#TreeMap" >TreeMap</a> α β</span> 
--   
--   do the dirty work for insert operations   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="TreeMap.insertkvI" >insertkvI</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a></b> → α → <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#TreeMap" >TreeMap</a> <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a> α</b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#TreeMap" >TreeMap</a> <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a> α</span> 
--

--    
--   <span class="code" ><a name="TreeMap.value" >value</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#TreeMap" >TreeMap</a> β α</b> → α</span> 
--   
--   access field <span class="code" >value</span>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#TreeMap
data TreeMap k v

-- | short for Node 1 Nil Nil k v
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#TreeMap.Leaf
protected Leaf {key ∷ k, value ∷ v}

-- | the empty tree
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#TreeMap.Nil
protected Nil

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#TreeMap.Node
protected Node {höhe ∷ Int, left ∷ TreeMap k v, right ∷ TreeMap k v, key ∷ k, value ∷ v}

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#TreeSet
type TreeSet a = TreeMap a ()

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#including
including ∷ Ord α ⇒ TreeSet α → α → TreeSet α

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#contains
contains ∷ Ord α ⇒ TreeMap α β → α → Bool

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/TreeMap#fromKeys
fromKeys ∷ Ord α ⇒ [α] → TreeSet α

-- | <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/wrapper/Identity#Identity" >Identity</a>, along with instances for <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/wrapper/../../prelude/PreludeMonad.html#Functor" >Functor</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/wrapper/../../prelude/PreludeMonad.html#Applicative" >Applicative</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/wrapper/../../prelude/PreludeMonad.html#Bind" >Bind</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/wrapper/../../prelude/PreludeMonad.html#Apply" >Apply</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/wrapper/../../prelude/PreludeMonad.html#Monad" >Monad</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/wrapper/../Monoid.html#Semigroup" >Semigroup</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/wrapper/../Monoid.html#Monoid" >Monoid</a> and <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/wrapper/../../prelude/PreludeList.html#ListSource" >ListSource</a>
module frege.data.wrapper.Identity

-- | The identity functor and monad. 
--   This trivial type constructor serves two purposes: <ul > <li > It can be used with functions parameterized by a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/wrapper/../../prelude/PreludeMonad.html#Functor" >Functor</a> or <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/wrapper/../../prelude/PreludeMonad.html#Monad" >Monad</a>.</li> <li > It can be used as a base monad to which a series of monad transformers may be applied to construct a composite monad. Most monad transformer modules include the special case of applying the transformer to <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/wrapper/Identity#Identity" >Identity</a>. For example, <span class="code" >State s</span> is an abbreviation for <span class="code" >StateT s <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/wrapper/Identity#Identity" >Identity</a></span>.</li> </ul> 
--   Identity functor and monad.  <h3 > Constructors</h3>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Identity.Identity" >Identity</a> {run ∷ a}</span> 
--     <h3 > Member Functions</h3>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Identity.run" >run</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/wrapper/Identity#Identity" >Identity</a> α</b> → α</span> 
--   
--   access field <span class="code" >run</span>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/wrapper/Identity#Identity
data Identity a

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/wrapper/Identity#Identity.Identity
Identity {run ∷ a}

-- | <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/data/wrapper/../Monoid.html#Monoid" >Monoid</a> wrappers for numeric data

-- | Provide functions for use in the fregIDE
module frege.ide.Utilities

-- | initialize the root of the package tree
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/ide/Utilities#initRoot

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/ide/Utilities#updateCache

-- | Force the import to re-create packages next time
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/ide/Utilities#refreshPackages
refreshPackages ∷ StIO ()

-- | Make a new loader for operation in the IDE. The rationale is that <i >not</i> making a new loader for every character typed will save time and space. 
--   The IDE code must decide when to make a new loader. For instance, this could be appropriate when the editor is re-activated, because in the meantime other modules could have been rebuild.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/ide/Utilities#newLoader
newLoader ∷ StIO ()

-- | add magic package names
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/ide/Utilities#magicPNs
magicPNs ∷ [([String], α)] → [([String], α)]

-- | create a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/ide/../compiler/types/Tokens.html#Token" >Token</a> list from an <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/ide/../prelude/PreludeArrays.html#JArray" >JArray</a> backwards
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/ide/Utilities#backwards
backwards ∷ JArray Token → Int → [Token]

-- | This resembles the SourceProposal class. The additional information must be lazy! <h3 > Constructors</h3>

--   
--   The new text being added/substituted if the user accepts this proposal

--   The text shown to the user in the popup view

-- | Called by Eclipse Content Proposer to make proposals. 
--   Usage: <span class="code" >proposeContent global offset tokens index</span>  
--   global 
--   <div > a symbol table, preferably with type information </div>  
--   offset 
--   <div > position of the caret </div>  
--   tokens 
--   <div > array of tokens </div>  
--   index 
--   <div > index into the array, points to the token that starts before the caret </div>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/ide/Utilities#proposeContent
proposeContent ∷ Global → Y RTree → Int → JArray Token → Int → [Proposal]

verbose ∷ (Nice α, QNameMatcher.QNameMatcher α) ⇒ Global → SigmaT α → String

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/ide/Utilities#label
label ∷ Global → SymbolT a → String

-- | Increment the pass number in the state
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/ide/Utilities#passDone
passDone ∷ StG ()

-- | Failure tolerant version of <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/ide/../compiler/types/Global.html#Global.thisTab" >Global.thisTab</a> for use in TreeModelBuilder. In case of syntax errors, there is no symtab yet, hence Global.thisTab is undefined. This, in turn, causes an exception in Eclipse. We can avoid this by just pretending the symbol table was empty.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/ide/Utilities#thisTab
thisTab ∷ Global → Symtab

symbolDocumentation ∷ Symbol → StIO String

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/ide/Utilities#documentationDocumentation
documentationDocumentation ∷ String → StIO String

-- | This is called from the fregIDE documentation provider when the reference resolver didn't find anything. 
--   This indicates the mouse was not hovering over some identifier.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/ide/Utilities#tokenDocumentation
tokenDocumentation ∷ Token → StIO String

-- | find all operators in the current symbol table and tabulate their fixities
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/ide/Utilities#infixDoc
infixDoc ∷ Global → String

-- | Correct the result of <span class="unknown" >frege.compiler.Scanner.dependencies</span>, which returns a singleton list with one element <span class="code" >"frege.prelude.PreludeBase"</span> for source files that don't have any import clauses. Yet, unless this is a prelude package itself, <span class="code" >"frege.Prelude"</span> will be imported. 
--   This discrepancy leads to files not compiling in the FregIDE builder because they are queued before <span class="code" >"frege/Prelude.fr"</span>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/ide/Utilities#correctDependenciesFor
correctDependenciesFor ∷ [String] → String → [String]

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/ide/Utilities#getDependencies
getDependencies ∷ CharSequence → StG [String]

lexPassIDE ∷ CharSequence → StIO (String, Int)

-- | Frege type for a <span class="code" >java.io.StringWriter</span> 
--   Not intended for direct use but rather as something a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/IO#PrintWriter" >PrintWriter</a> can be made of. (Though, because of the <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/./Lang.html#Appendable" >Appendable</a> inheritance, one could still <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/./Lang.html#Appendable.append" >Appendable.append</a> directly.) 
--   To be used like: 
--  <pre>
--  
--   action :: PrintWriter -&gt; IO ()
--   action =  ...
--   actionOnStringWriter :: IO String
--   actionOnStringWriter = do
--         sw &lt;- StringWriter.new
--         pr &lt;- sw.printer
--         action pr
--         pr.close
--         sw.toString
--  </pre> <h3 > Member Functions</h3>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="StringWriter._new" >new</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Unit" >()</a></b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#IO" >IO</a> <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/IO#StringWriter" >StringWriter</a><br ></br>

--   make a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/IO#PrintWriter" >PrintWriter</a> that prints to this <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/IO#StringWriter" >StringWriter</a>

--   
--   Reads a line of text. A line is considered to be terminated by any one of a line feed ("\n"), a carriage return ("\r"), or a carriage return followed immediately by a linefeed.  
--   Returns: 
--   <div > <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Maybe.Just" >Maybe.Just</a> <i >string</i>, where <i >string</i> is the contents of the line, not including any line-termination characters, or <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Maybe.Nothing" >Maybe.Nothing</a> if the end of the stream has been reached.</div>  
--   Throws: 
--   <div > IOException - If an I/O error occurs </div>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/IO#BufferedReader
data BufferedReader 

-- | Reads the next line from a buffered reader using <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/IO#BufferedReader.readLine" >BufferedReader.readLine</a>, and returns the string or throws <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/IO#EOFException" >EOFException</a> on end of file.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/IO#BufferedReader.getLine
getLine ∷ BufferedReader → IO String

native new

-- | Reads a line of text. A line is considered to be terminated by any one of a line feed ("\n"), a carriage return ("\r"), or a carriage return followed immediately by a linefeed.  
--   Returns: 
--   <div > <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Maybe.Just" >Maybe.Just</a> <i >string</i>, where <i >string</i> is the contents of the line, not including any line-termination characters, or <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Maybe.Nothing" >Maybe.Nothing</a> if the end of the stream has been reached.</div>  
--   Throws: 
--   <div > IOException - If an I/O error occurs </div>

--   <span class="code" ><a name="CharSequence.codePointAt" >codePointAt</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/Lang#CharSequence" >CharSequence</a></b> → <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a></b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a><br ></br>
--  <b >pure </b><b >native </b>java.lang.Character.codePointAt</span> 
--   
--   Returns the code point at the given index of the <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/Lang#CharSequence" >CharSequence</a>. If the char value at the given index in the CharSequence is in the high-surrogate range, the following index is less than the length of the CharSequence, and the char value at the following index is in the low-surrogate range, then the supplementary code point corresponding to this surrogate pair is returned. 
--   Otherwise, the char value at the given index is returned. 
--   Note that the corresponding java method is from <span class="code" >java.lang.Character</span>, but logically fits in here better. 
--   See also: <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Char.isSupplementaryCodePoint" >Char.isSupplementaryCodePoint</a>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="CharSequence.fromString" >fromString</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#String" >String</a></b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/Lang#CharSequence" >CharSequence</a><br ></br>
--  <b >pure </b><b >native </b>(java.lang.CharSequence)</span> 
--    
--   <span class="code" ><a name="CharSequence.length" >length</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/Lang#CharSequence" >CharSequence</a></b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a><br ></br>
--  <b >pure </b><b >native </b>length</span> 
--    
--   <span class="code" ><a name="CharSequence.subSeq" >subSeq</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/Lang#CharSequence" >CharSequence</a></b> → <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a></b> → <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a></b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/Lang#CharSequence" >CharSequence</a><br ></br>
--  <b >pure </b><b >native </b>subSequence</span>

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/Lang#StringBuffer
data StringBuffer 

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/Lang#StringBuffer.append
append ∷ Mutable s StringBuffer → Float → STMutable s StringBuffer 
        | Mutable s StringBuffer → Double → STMutable s StringBuffer 
        | Mutable s StringBuffer → Bool → STMutable s StringBuffer 
        | Mutable s StringBuffer → Char → STMutable s StringBuffer 
        | Mutable s StringBuffer → Int → STMutable s StringBuffer 
        | Mutable s StringBuffer → Long → STMutable s StringBuffer 
        | Mutable s StringBuffer → Object → STMutable s StringBuffer 
        | Mutable s StringBuffer → CharSequence → STMutable s StringBuffer
