-- | <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/Lang#Byte" >Byte</a> is the Frege type for the primitive JVM <span class="code" >byte</span> 
--   However, it is given <i >unsigend</i> semantics in Frege. 
--   Use <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/Lang#Byte" >Byte</a> only in <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/../prelude/PreludeArrays.html#JArray" >JArray</a>s or tightly packed records! 
--   Otherwise you'll waste time while not saving space.  <h3 > Member Functions</h3>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Byte.signed" >signed</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/Lang#Byte" >Byte</a></b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a><br ></br>
--  <b >pure </b><b >native </b>(int)</span> 
--   
--   this gives the <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a> corresponding to the <b >signed</b> interpretation of the <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/Lang#Byte" >Byte</a>   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Byte.unsigned" >unsigned</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/Lang#Byte" >Byte</a></b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a></span> 
--   
--   this gives the <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a> corresponding to the <b >unsigned</b> interpretation of the <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/Lang#Byte" >Byte</a>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/Lang#Byte
data Byte 

-- | this gives the <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a> corresponding to the <b >signed</b> interpretation of the <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/Lang#Byte" >Byte</a>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/Lang#Byte.signed
signed ∷ Byte → Int 
pure native (int)

-- | this gives the <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a> corresponding to the <b >unsigned</b> interpretation of the <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/Lang#Byte" >Byte</a>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/Lang#Byte.unsigned
unsigned ∷ Byte → Int

-- | convert an <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a> to a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/Lang#Byte" >Byte</a> by chopping off the leading 24 bits.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/Lang#_byte

-- | A value of this type is used to generate a stream of pseudorandom numbers. The type uses a 48-bit seed, which is modified using a linear congruential formula. (See Donald Knuth, The Art of Computer Programming, Volume 2, Section 3.2.1.) 
--   If two <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/Util#Random" >Random</a> values are created with the same seed, and the same sequence of method calls is made for each, they will generate and return identical sequences of numbers. In order to guarantee this property, particular algorithms are specified for the class Random. 
--   Many applications will find the function <a href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/../prelude/Math.html#random" >random</a> simpler to use. <h3 > Member Functions</h3>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Random._new" >new</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Unit" >()</a> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/../prelude/PreludeIO.html#STMutable" >STMutable</a> <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#RealWorld" >RealWorld</a> <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/Util#Random" >Random</a><br ></br>

-- | From Javadoc: A comparison function, which imposes a total ordering on some collection of objects. Comparators can be passed to a sort method (such as Collections.sort or Arrays.sort) to allow precise control over the sort order. Comparators can also be used to control the order of certain data structures (such as sorted sets or sorted maps), or to provide an ordering for collections of objects that don't have a natural ordering.

-- | This class provides a skeletal implementation of the Set interface to minimize the effort required to implement this interface. The process of implementing a set by extending this class is identical to that of implementing a Collection by extending AbstractCollection, except that all of the methods and constructors in subclasses of this class must obey the additional constraints imposed by the Set interface (for instance, the add method must not permit addition of multiple instances of an object to a set). 
--   Note that this class does not override any of the implementations from the AbstractCollection class. It merely adds implementations for equals and hashCode. <h3 > Member Functions</h3>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="AbstractSet.equals" >equals</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/../prelude/PreludeIO.html#Mutable" >Mutable</a> s (<a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/Util#AbstractSet" >AbstractSet</a> e)</b> → <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Object" >Object</a></b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#ST" >ST</a> s <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Bool" >Bool</a><br ></br>

-- | The Stack class represents a last-in-first-out (LIFO) stack of objects. It extends class Vector with five operations that allow a vector to be treated as a stack. The usual push and pop operations are provided, as well as a method to peek at the top item on the stack, a method to test for whether the stack is empty, and a method to search the stack for an item and discover how far it is from the top. 
--   When a stack is first created, it contains no items. 
--   A more complete and consistent set of LIFO stack operations is provided by the Deque interface and its implementations, which should be used in preference to this class. For example: 
--  <pre>
--  
--   Deque&lt;Integer&gt; stack = new ArrayDeque&lt;Integer&gt;();
--  </pre> <h3 > Member Functions</h3>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Stack.empty" >empty</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/../prelude/PreludeIO.html#Mutable" >Mutable</a> s (<a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/Util#Stack" >Stack</a> e)</b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#ST" >ST</a> s <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Bool" >Bool</a><br ></br>

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/Util#SortedSet
data SortedSet e 

-- | Returns the comparator used to order the elements in this set, or null if this set uses the 
--   <a href="https://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/lang/Comparable.html" >natural ordering</a> of its elements.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/Util#SortedSet.comparator
comparator ∷ Mutable s (SortedSet e) → ST s (Comparator e) 
native comparator

-- | Returns the first (lowest) element currently in this set.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/Util#SortedSet.first
first ∷ Mutable s (SortedSet e) → ST s e 
native first

-- | Returns a view of the portion of this set whose elements are strictly less than toElement.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/Util#SortedSet.headSet
headSet ∷ Mutable s (SortedSet e) → e → STMutable s (SortedSet e) 
native headSet

-- | Returns the last (highest) element currently in this set.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/Util#SortedSet.last
last ∷ Mutable s (SortedSet e) → ST s e 
native last

-- | Returns a view of the portion of this set whose elements range from fromElement, inclusive, to toElement, exclusive.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/Util#SortedSet.subSet
subSet ∷ Mutable s (SortedSet e) → e → e → STMutable s (SortedSet e) 
native subSet

-- | Returns a view of the portion of this set whose elements are greater than or equal to fromElement.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/Util#SortedSet.tailSet
tailSet ∷ Mutable s (SortedSet e) → e → STMutable s (SortedSet e) 
native tailSet

data Deque e 

-- | Inserts the specified element into the queue represented by this deque (in other words, at the tail of this deque) if it is possible to do so immediately without violating capacity restrictions, returning true upon success and throwing an IllegalStateException if no space is currently available.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/Util#Deque.add
add ∷ Mutable s (Deque e) → e → ST s Bool 
native add

-- | Inserts the specified element at the front of this deque if it is possible to do so immediately without violating capacity restrictions.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/Util#Deque.addFirst
addFirst ∷ Mutable s (Deque e) → e → ST s () 
native addFirst

-- | Inserts the specified element at the end of this deque if it is possible to do so immediately without violating capacity restrictions.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/Util#Deque.addLast

native addLast

-- | This class provides a skeletal implementation of the List interface to minimize the effort required to implement this interface backed by a "sequential access" data store (such as a linked list). For random access data (such as an array), AbstractList should be used in preference to this class.

data EventListener 

-- | Hash table and linked list implementation of the Map interface, with predictable iteration order. 
--   More: <a href="https://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/util/LinkedHashMap.html" >JavaDoc</a> <h3 > Member Functions</h3>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="LinkedHashMap.clear" >clear</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/../prelude/PreludeIO.html#Mutable" >Mutable</a> s (<a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/Util#LinkedHashMap" >LinkedHashMap</a> k v)</b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#ST" >ST</a> s <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Unit" >()</a><br ></br>

-- | Hash table and linked list implementation of the Set interface, with predictable iteration order.

--   <span class="code" ><a name="LinkedHashSet._new" >new</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/../prelude/PreludeIO.html#Mutable" >Mutable</a> s (<a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/Util#Collection" >Collection</a> e) → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/../prelude/PreludeIO.html#STMutable" >STMutable</a> s (<a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/Util#LinkedHashSet" >LinkedHashSet</a> e)<br ></br>
--       | <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Unit" >()</a> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/../prelude/PreludeIO.html#STMutable" >STMutable</a> s (<a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/Util#LinkedHashSet" >LinkedHashSet</a> e)<br ></br>
--       | <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/../prelude/PreludeIO.html#STMutable" >STMutable</a> s (<a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/Util#LinkedHashSet" >LinkedHashSet</a> e)<br ></br>

--   <span class="code" ><a name="Locale._new" >new</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#String" >String</a> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/Util#Locale" >Locale</a><br ></br>
--       | <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#String" >String</a> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#String" >String</a> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/Util#Locale" >Locale</a><br ></br>
--       | <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#String" >String</a> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#String" >String</a> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#String" >String</a> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/Util#Locale" >Locale</a><br ></br>
--  <b >pure </b><b >native </b>new</span> 
--   
--   Create a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/Util#Locale" >Locale</a> like so: 
--  <pre>
--  
--   Locale.new &quot;de&quot;
--  </pre> 
--  <pre>
--  
--   Locale.new &quot;de&quot; &quot;AT&quot;   
--  </pre>

-- | An object that maps keys to values. More: <a href="https://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/util/Map.html" >JavaDoc</a> <h3 > Member Functions</h3>

-- | An iterator over a collection. More: <a href="https://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/util/Iterator.html" >JavaDoc</a> <h3 > Member Functions</h3>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Iterator.fold" >fold</a> ∷ (c → a → c) → <b >c</b> → <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/../prelude/PreludeIO.html#Mutable" >Mutable</a> s (<a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/Util#Iterator" >Iterator</a> a)</b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#ST" >ST</a> s c</span> 
--   
--   Fold over a java <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/Util#Iterator" >Iterator</a> 
--   Unlike a fold over the result of <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/Util#Iterator.toList" >Iterator.toList</a>, this doesn't need extra memory.   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Iterator.hasNext" >hasNext</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/../prelude/PreludeIO.html#Mutable" >Mutable</a> s (<a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/Util#Iterator" >Iterator</a> e)</b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#ST" >ST</a> s <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Bool" >Bool</a><br ></br>
--  <b >native </b>hasNext</span> 
--    
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Iterator.next" >next</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/../prelude/PreludeIO.html#Mutable" >Mutable</a> s (<a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/Util#Iterator" >Iterator</a> e)</b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#ST" >ST</a> s e<br ></br>
--  <b >native </b>next</span> 
--    
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Iterator.remove" >remove</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/../prelude/PreludeIO.html#Mutable" >Mutable</a> s (<a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/Util#Iterator" >Iterator</a> e)</b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#ST" >ST</a> s <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Unit" >()</a><br ></br>
--  <b >native </b>remove</span> 
--    
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Iterator.toList" >toList</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/../prelude/PreludeIO.html#Mutable" >Mutable</a> s (<a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/Util#Iterator" >Iterator</a> e) → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#ST" >ST</a> s [e]</span> 
--   
--   Converts the elements of this <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/Util#Iterator" >Iterator</a> to a Frege list. Unfortunately, because the <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/Util#Iterator" >Iterator</a> is mutable, the list is not constructed lazily, but at once. And since it comes out in the wrong order, it must finally be reversed. 
--   This can be deadly when the <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/Util#Iterator" >Iterator</a> has large amounts of data, as there must be <i >2n</i> list nodes created, at least temporarily. 
--   If all you want to do is to reduce (i.e. <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/../prelude/PreludeList.html#fold" >fold</a>) the resulting list, consider <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/Util#Iterator.fold" >Iterator.fold</a>, which doesn't expend any additional memory.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/Util#Iterator
data Iterator e 

-- | Fold over a java <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/Util#Iterator" >Iterator</a> 
--   Unlike a fold over the result of <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/Util#Iterator.toList" >Iterator.toList</a>, this doesn't need extra memory.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/Util#Iterator.fold
fold ∷ (c → a → c) → c → Mutable s (Iterator a) → ST s c

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/Util#Iterator.hasNext
hasNext ∷ Mutable s (Iterator e) → ST s Bool 
native hasNext

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/Util#Iterator.next
next ∷ Mutable s (Iterator e) → ST s e 
native next

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/Util#Iterator.remove
remove ∷ Mutable s (Iterator e) → ST s () 
native remove

-- | Converts the elements of this <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/Util#Iterator" >Iterator</a> to a Frege list. Unfortunately, because the <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/Util#Iterator" >Iterator</a> is mutable, the list is not constructed lazily, but at once. And since it comes out in the wrong order, it must finally be reversed. 
--   This can be deadly when the <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/Util#Iterator" >Iterator</a> has large amounts of data, as there must be <i >2n</i> list nodes created, at least temporarily. 
--   If all you want to do is to reduce (i.e. <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/../prelude/PreludeList.html#fold" >fold</a>) the resulting list, consider <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/Util#Iterator.fold" >Iterator.fold</a>, which doesn't expend any additional memory.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/Util#Iterator.toList
toList ∷ Mutable s (Iterator e) → ST s [e]

-- | An ordered collection (also known as a sequence).

-- | This class implements a vector of bits that grows as needed. 
--   More: <a href="https://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/util/BitSet.html" >JavaDoc</a> <h3 > Member Functions</h3>

-- | The Calendar class is an abstract class that provides methods for converting between a specific instant in time and a set of <a href="https://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/util/Calendar.html#fields" >calendar fields</a> such as YEAR, MONTH, DAY<i >OF</i>MONTH, HOUR, and so on, and for manipulating the calendar fields, such as getting the date of the next week. 
--   More: <a href="https://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/util/Calendar.html" >JavaDoc</a> <h3 > Member Functions</h3>

-- | Mathematical functions from <a href="http://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/lang/Math.html" >java.lang.Math</a>.
--   Functions that are already defined elsewhere, like <span class="code" >abs</span> or <span class="code" >min</span> have been left out.
--   This module is not good for inclusion in user code, because of the overloaded primitive functions.
--   Better use
--  <pre>
--  
--   import Prelude.Math
--  </pre>
--   which also defines the class <a href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../../prelude/Math.html#Floating" >Floating</a> that makes it possibly to use the primitive functions in a type safe way.
module frege.java.lang.Math

-- | The <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Double" >Double</a> value that is closer than any other to e, the base of the natural logarithms.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/Math#e
e ∷ Double 
pure native java.lang.Math.E

-- | The <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Double" >Double</a> value that is closer than any other to pi, the ratio of the circumference of a circle to its diameter.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/Math#pi
pi ∷ Double 
pure native java.lang.Math.PI

-- | Java types needed to run processes. Because the associated classes are in <span class="code" >java.lang</span>, the stuff here would belong into package <span class="code" >frege.java.Lang</span>, however, it does not seem justified to have it imported in each and every program.
module frege.java.lang.Processes

-- | The type <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/Processes#Process" >Process</a> provides methods for performing input from the process, performing output to the process, waiting for the process to complete, checking the exit status of the process, and destroying (killing) the process. 
--   An instance of <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/Processes#Process" >Process</a> can be obtained from the <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/Processes#Process.exec" >Process.exec</a> or <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/Processes#ProcessBuilder.start" >ProcessBuilder.start</a> methods. <h3 > Member Functions</h3>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Process.destroy" >destroy</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/Processes#Process" >Process</a></b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#IO" >IO</a> <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Unit" >()</a><br ></br>
--  <b >native </b>destroy</span> 
--   
--   Kills the subprocess. The subprocess represented by this <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/Processes#Process" >Process</a> object is forcibly terminated.   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Process.exec" >exec</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../../prelude/PreludeArrays.html#ArrayOf" >ArrayOf</a> <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#RealWorld" >RealWorld</a> <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#String" >String</a> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Maybe" >Maybe</a> (<a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../../prelude/PreludeArrays.html#ArrayOf" >ArrayOf</a> <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#RealWorld" >RealWorld</a> <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#String" >String</a>) → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Maybe" >Maybe</a> (<a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../../prelude/PreludeIO.html#MutableIO" >MutableIO</a> <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../IO.html#File" >File</a>) → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#IO" >IO</a> <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/Processes#Process" >Process</a><br ></br>
--            <b >throws </b><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../Lang.html#IOException" >IOException</a><br ></br>
--        | <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#String" >String</a> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#IO" >IO</a> <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/Processes#Process" >Process</a><br ></br>
--            <b >throws </b><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../Lang.html#IOException" >IOException</a><br ></br>
--  <b >native </b>java.lang.Runtime.getRuntime().exec</span> 
--   
--  <pre>
--  
--   Process.exec cmdarray envp dir
--   Process.exec &quot;command&quot;
--  </pre> 
--   Executes the specified command and arguments in a separate process with the specified environment and working directory. 
--   Given an array of strings <i >cmdarray</i>, representing the tokens of a command line, and an array of strings <i >envp</i>, representing "environment" variable settings, this method creates a new process in which to execute the specified command. 
--   This method checks that <i >cmdarray</i> is a valid operating system command. Which commands are valid is system-dependent, but at the very least the command must be a non-empty list of non-null strings. 
--   If <i >envp</i> is <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Maybe.Nothing" >Maybe.Nothing</a>, the subprocess inherits the environment settings of the current process. 
--   A minimal set of system dependent environment variables may be required to start a process on some operating systems. As a result, the subprocess may inherit additional environment variable settings beyond those in the specified environment. 
--   The working directory of the new subprocess is specified by <i >dir</i>. If <i >dir</i> is <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Maybe.Nothing" >Maybe.Nothing</a>, the subprocess inherits the current working directory of the current process. 
--   If a security manager exists, its <span class="code" >checkExec</span> method is invoked with the first component of the array cmdarray as its argument. This may result in a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../Lang.html#SecurityException" >SecurityException</a> being thrown. 
--   Starting an operating system process is highly system-dependent. Among the many things that can go wrong are: <ul > <li > The operating system program file was not found. </li> <li > Access to the program file was denied. </li> <li > The working directory does not exist. </li> </ul> 
--   In such cases an exception will be thrown. The exact nature of the exception is system-dependent, but it will always be a subclass of <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../Lang.html#IOException" >IOException</a>.  
--   Returns: 
--   <div > A new Process object for managing the subprocess </div>  
--   Throws: 
--   <div > </div>   <ul > <li > <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../Lang.html#SecurityException" >SecurityException</a> - If a security manager exists and its checkExec method doesn't allow creation of the subprocess </li> <li > <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../Lang.html#IOException" >IOException</a> - If an I/O error occurs </li> <li > <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../Lang.html#NullPointerException" >NullPointerException</a> - If one of the elements of the passed arrays is null </li> <li > <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../Lang.html#IndexOutOfBoundsException" >IndexOutOfBoundsException</a> - If <i >cmdarray</i> is an empty array (has length 0) </li> </ul>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Process.execα" >execα</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../../prelude/PreludeArrays.html#ArrayOf" >ArrayOf</a> <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#RealWorld" >RealWorld</a> <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#String" >String</a></b> → <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Maybe" >Maybe</a> (<a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../../prelude/PreludeArrays.html#ArrayOf" >ArrayOf</a> <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#RealWorld" >RealWorld</a> <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#String" >String</a>)</b> → <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Maybe" >Maybe</a> (<a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../../prelude/PreludeIO.html#MutableIO" >MutableIO</a> <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../IO.html#File" >File</a>)</b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#IO" >IO</a> <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/Processes#Process" >Process</a><br ></br>
--  <b >native </b>java.lang.Runtime.getRuntime().exec  <b >throws </b><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../Lang.html#IOException" >IOException</a>  <b >overloads </b><a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/Processes#Process.exec" >exec</a></span> 
--   
--  <pre>
--  
--   Process.exec cmdarray envp dir
--   Process.exec &quot;command&quot;
--  </pre> 
--   Executes the specified command and arguments in a separate process with the specified environment and working directory. 
--   Given an array of strings <i >cmdarray</i>, representing the tokens of a command line, and an array of strings <i >envp</i>, representing "environment" variable settings, this method creates a new process in which to execute the specified command. 
--   This method checks that <i >cmdarray</i> is a valid operating system command. Which commands are valid is system-dependent, but at the very least the command must be a non-empty list of non-null strings. 
--   If <i >envp</i> is <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Maybe.Nothing" >Maybe.Nothing</a>, the subprocess inherits the environment settings of the current process. 
--   A minimal set of system dependent environment variables may be required to start a process on some operating systems. As a result, the subprocess may inherit additional environment variable settings beyond those in the specified environment. 
--   The working directory of the new subprocess is specified by <i >dir</i>. If <i >dir</i> is <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Maybe.Nothing" >Maybe.Nothing</a>, the subprocess inherits the current working directory of the current process. 
--   If a security manager exists, its <span class="code" >checkExec</span> method is invoked with the first component of the array cmdarray as its argument. This may result in a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../Lang.html#SecurityException" >SecurityException</a> being thrown. 
--   Starting an operating system process is highly system-dependent. Among the many things that can go wrong are: <ul > <li > The operating system program file was not found. </li> <li > Access to the program file was denied. </li> <li > The working directory does not exist. </li> </ul> 
--   In such cases an exception will be thrown. The exact nature of the exception is system-dependent, but it will always be a subclass of <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../Lang.html#IOException" >IOException</a>.  
--   Returns: 
--   <div > A new Process object for managing the subprocess </div>  
--   Throws: 
--   <div > </div>   <ul > <li > <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../Lang.html#SecurityException" >SecurityException</a> - If a security manager exists and its checkExec method doesn't allow creation of the subprocess </li> <li > <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../Lang.html#IOException" >IOException</a> - If an I/O error occurs </li> <li > <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../Lang.html#NullPointerException" >NullPointerException</a> - If one of the elements of the passed arrays is null </li> <li > <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../Lang.html#IndexOutOfBoundsException" >IndexOutOfBoundsException</a> - If <i >cmdarray</i> is an empty array (has length 0) </li> </ul>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Process.execβ" >execβ</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#String" >String</a></b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#IO" >IO</a> <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/Processes#Process" >Process</a><br ></br>
--  <b >native </b>java.lang.Runtime.getRuntime().exec  <b >throws </b><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../Lang.html#IOException" >IOException</a>  <b >overloads </b><a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/Processes#Process.exec" >exec</a></span> 
--   
--  <pre>
--  
--   Process.exec cmdarray envp dir
--   Process.exec &quot;command&quot;
--  </pre> 
--   Executes the specified command and arguments in a separate process with the specified environment and working directory. 
--   Given an array of strings <i >cmdarray</i>, representing the tokens of a command line, and an array of strings <i >envp</i>, representing "environment" variable settings, this method creates a new process in which to execute the specified command. 
--   This method checks that <i >cmdarray</i> is a valid operating system command. Which commands are valid is system-dependent, but at the very least the command must be a non-empty list of non-null strings. 
--   If <i >envp</i> is <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Maybe.Nothing" >Maybe.Nothing</a>, the subprocess inherits the environment settings of the current process. 
--   A minimal set of system dependent environment variables may be required to start a process on some operating systems. As a result, the subprocess may inherit additional environment variable settings beyond those in the specified environment. 
--   The working directory of the new subprocess is specified by <i >dir</i>. If <i >dir</i> is <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Maybe.Nothing" >Maybe.Nothing</a>, the subprocess inherits the current working directory of the current process. 
--   If a security manager exists, its <span class="code" >checkExec</span> method is invoked with the first component of the array cmdarray as its argument. This may result in a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../Lang.html#SecurityException" >SecurityException</a> being thrown. 
--   Starting an operating system process is highly system-dependent. Among the many things that can go wrong are: <ul > <li > The operating system program file was not found. </li> <li > Access to the program file was denied. </li> <li > The working directory does not exist. </li> </ul> 
--   In such cases an exception will be thrown. The exact nature of the exception is system-dependent, but it will always be a subclass of <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../Lang.html#IOException" >IOException</a>.  
--   Returns: 
--   <div > A new Process object for managing the subprocess </div>  
--   Throws: 
--   <div > </div>   <ul > <li > <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../Lang.html#SecurityException" >SecurityException</a> - If a security manager exists and its checkExec method doesn't allow creation of the subprocess </li> <li > <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../Lang.html#IOException" >IOException</a> - If an I/O error occurs </li> <li > <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../Lang.html#NullPointerException" >NullPointerException</a> - If one of the elements of the passed arrays is null </li> <li > <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../Lang.html#IndexOutOfBoundsException" >IndexOutOfBoundsException</a> - If <i >cmdarray</i> is an empty array (has length 0) </li> </ul>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Process.exitValue" >exitValue</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/Processes#Process" >Process</a></b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#IO" >IO</a> <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a><br ></br>
--  <b >native </b>exitValue  <b >throws </b><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../Lang.html#IllegalThreadStateException" >IllegalThreadStateException</a></span> 
--   
--   Returns the exit value for the subprocess represented by this Process object. 
--   By convention, the value 0 indicates normal termination.   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Process.getErrorStream" >getErrorStream</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/Processes#Process" >Process</a></b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#IO" >IO</a> <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../IO.html#InputStream" >InputStream</a><br ></br>
--  <b >native </b>getErrorStream</span> 
--   
--   Returns the input stream connected to the standard error output of the subprocess. The stream obtains data piped from the error output of the process represented by this <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/Processes#Process" >Process</a> object. 
--   If the standard error of the subprocess has been redirected using <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/Processes#ProcessBuilder.redirectError" >ProcessBuilder.redirectError</a> or <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/Processes#ProcessBuilder.redirectErrorStream" >ProcessBuilder.redirectErrorStream</a> then this method will return an input stream, for which the <span class="unknown" >InputStream.read</span> method always returns <span class="code" >-1</span>, the <span class="unknown" >InputStream.available</span> method returns always <span class="code" >0</span> and the <span class="unknown" >InputStream.close</span> method does nothing.  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Process.getInputStream" >getInputStream</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/Processes#Process" >Process</a></b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#IO" >IO</a> <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../IO.html#InputStream" >InputStream</a><br ></br>
--  <b >native </b>getInputStream</span> 
--   
--   Returns the input stream connected to the standard output of the subprocess. The stream obtains data piped from the standard output of the process represented by this <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/Processes#Process" >Process</a> object. 
--   If the standard output of the subprocess has been redirected using <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/Processes#ProcessBuilder.redirectOutput" >ProcessBuilder.redirectOutput</a> then this method will return an input stream, for which the <span class="unknown" >InputStream.read</span> method always returns <span class="code" >-1</span>, the <span class="unknown" >InputStream.available</span> method returns always <span class="code" >0</span> and the <span class="unknown" >InputStream.close</span> method does nothing. 
--   Otherwise, if the standard error of the subprocess has been redirected using <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/Processes#ProcessBuilder.redirectErrorStream" >ProcessBuilder.redirectErrorStream</a> then the input stream returned by this method will receive the merged standard output and the standard error of the subprocess.  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Process.getOutputStream" >getOutputStream</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/Processes#Process" >Process</a></b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#IO" >IO</a> <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../IO.html#OutputStream" >OutputStream</a><br ></br>
--  <b >native </b>getOutputStream</span> 
--   
--   Returns the output stream connected to the standard input of the subprocess. Output to the stream is piped into the standard input of the process represented by this <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/Processes#Process" >Process</a> object. 
--   If the standard input of the subprocess has been redirected using <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/Processes#ProcessBuilder.redirectInput" >ProcessBuilder.redirectInput</a> then this method will return an output stream for which the <span class="unknown" >OutputStream.write</span> method always throws <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../Lang.html#IOException" >IOException</a> and the <span class="unknown" >OutputStream.close</span> method does nothing.  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Process.waitFor" >waitFor</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/Processes#Process" >Process</a></b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#IO" >IO</a> <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a><br ></br>
--  <b >native </b>waitFor  <b >throws </b><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#InterruptedException" >InterruptedException</a></span> 
--   
--   Causes the current thread to wait, if necessary, until the process represented by this <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/Processes#Process" >Process</a> object has terminated. This method returns immediately if the subprocess has already terminated. If the subprocess has not yet terminated, the calling thread will be blocked until the subprocess exits.  
--   Returns: 
--   <div > the exit value of the subprocess represented by this <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/Processes#Process" >Process</a> object. By convention, the value 0 indicates normal termination.</div>  
--   Throws: 
--   <div > <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#InterruptedException" >InterruptedException</a> if the current <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../Lang.html#Thread" >Thread</a> is interrupted by another <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../Lang.html#Thread" >Thread</a> while it is waiting.</div>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/Processes#Process
data Process 

-- | Kills the subprocess. The subprocess represented by this <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/Processes#Process" >Process</a> object is forcibly terminated.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/Processes#Process.destroy

native java.lang.Runtime.getRuntime().exec  throws IOException  overloads exec

If <i >dir</i> is <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Maybe.Nothing" >Maybe.Nothing</a>, the subprocess inherits the current working directory of the current process. 
--   If a security manager exists, its <span class="code" >checkExec</span> method is invoked with the first component of the array cmdarray as its argument. This may result in a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../Lang.html#SecurityException" >SecurityException</a> being thrown. 
--   Starting an operating system process is highly system-dependent. Among the many things that can go wrong are: <ul > <li > The operating system program file was not found. </li> <li > Access to the program file was denied. </li> <li > The working directory does not exist. </li> </ul> 
--   In such cases an exception will be thrown. The exact nature of the exception is system-dependent, but it will always be a subclass of <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../Lang.html#IOException" >IOException</a>.  
--   Returns: 
--   <div > A new Process object for managing the subprocess </div>  
--   Throws: 
--   <div > </div>   <ul > <li > <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../Lang.html#SecurityException" >SecurityException</a> - If a security manager exists and its checkExec method doesn't allow creation of the subprocess </li> <li > <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../Lang.html#IOException" >IOException</a> - If an I/O error occurs </li> <li > <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../Lang.html#NullPointerException" >NullPointerException</a> - If one of the elements of the passed arrays is null </li> <li > <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../Lang.html#IndexOutOfBoundsException" >IndexOutOfBoundsException</a> - If <i >cmdarray</i> is an empty array (has length 0) </li> </ul>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/Processes#Process.execβ
execβ ∷ String → IO Process 
native java.lang.Runtime.getRuntime().exec  throws IOException  overloads exec

-- | Returns the input stream connected to the standard error output of the subprocess. The stream obtains data piped from the error output of the process represented by this <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/Processes#Process" >Process</a> object. 
--   If the standard error of the subprocess has been redirected using <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/Processes#ProcessBuilder.redirectError" >ProcessBuilder.redirectError</a> or <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/Processes#ProcessBuilder.redirectErrorStream" >ProcessBuilder.redirectErrorStream</a> then this method will return an input stream, for which the <span class="unknown" >InputStream.read</span> method always returns <span class="code" >-1</span>, the <span class="unknown" >InputStream.available</span> method returns always <span class="code" >0</span> and the <span class="unknown" >InputStream.close</span> method does nothing.

-- | Returns the input stream connected to the standard output of the subprocess. The stream obtains data piped from the standard output of the process represented by this <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/Processes#Process" >Process</a> object. 
--   If the standard output of the subprocess has been redirected using <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/Processes#ProcessBuilder.redirectOutput" >ProcessBuilder.redirectOutput</a> then this method will return an input stream, for which the <span class="unknown" >InputStream.read</span> method always returns <span class="code" >-1</span>, the <span class="unknown" >InputStream.available</span> method returns always <span class="code" >0</span> and the <span class="unknown" >InputStream.close</span> method does nothing. 
--   Otherwise, if the standard error of the subprocess has been redirected using <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/Processes#ProcessBuilder.redirectErrorStream" >ProcessBuilder.redirectErrorStream</a> then the input stream returned by this method will receive the merged standard output and the standard error of the subprocess.

-- | Causes the current thread to wait, if necessary, until the process represented by this <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/Processes#Process" >Process</a> object has terminated. -- | Represents a source of subprocess input or a destination of subprocess output. Each <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/Processes#Redirect" >Redirect</a> is one of the following: <ul > <li > the special value <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/Processes#Redirect.pipe" >Redirect.pipe</a> </li> <li > the special value <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/Processes#Redirect.inherit" >Redirect.inherit</a> </li> <li > a redirection to read from a file, created by an invocation of <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/Processes#Redirect.from" >Redirect.from</a> </li> <li > a redirection to write to a file, created by an invocation of <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/Processes#Redirect.to" >Redirect.to</a> </li> <li > a redirection to append to a file, created by an invocation of <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/Processes#Redirect.appendTo" >Redirect.appendTo</a> </li> </ul> <h3 > Member Functions</h3>

-- | The <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/Processes#ProcessBuilder" >ProcessBuilder</a> type is used to create operating system processes. 
--   Each <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/Processes#ProcessBuilder" >ProcessBuilder</a> manages a collection of process attributes. The <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/Processes#ProcessBuilder.start" >ProcessBuilder.start</a> method creates a new <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/Processes#Process" >Process</a> instance with those attributes. The <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/Processes#ProcessBuilder.start" >ProcessBuilder.start</a> method can be invoked repeatedly from the same instance to create new subprocesses with identical or related attributes. 
--   The following attributes are being managed: <ul > <li > a <i >command</i>, a list of strings which signifies the external program file to be invoked and its arguments, if any. Which string lists represent a valid operating system command is system-dependent. For example, it is common for each conceptual argument to be an element in this list, but there are operating systems where programs are expected to tokenize command line strings themselves - on such a system a Java implementation might require commands to contain exactly two elements.</li> <li > an <i >environment</i>, which is a system-dependent mapping from variables to values. The initial value is a copy of the environment of the current process (see <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../Lang.html#System.getenv" >System.getenv</a>).</li> <li > a <i >working directory</i>. The default value is the current working directory of the current process, usually the directory named by the system property <span class="code" >user.dir</span>.</li> <li > a source of <i >standard input</i>. By default, the subprocess reads input from a pipe. Frege code can access this pipe via the output stream returned by <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/Processes#Process.getOutputStream" >Process.getOutputStream</a>. However, standard input may be redirected to another source using <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/Processes#ProcessBuilder.redirectInput" >ProcessBuilder.redirectInput</a>. In this case, <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/Processes#Process.getOutputStream" >Process.getOutputStream</a> will return an output stream, for which the <span class="code" >write</span> methods always throws <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../Lang.html#IOException" >IOException</a> and the <span class="code" >close</span> method does nothing.</li> <li > a destination for <i >standard output</i> and <i >standard error</i>. By default, the subprocess writes standard output and standard error to pipes. Frege code can access these pipes via the input streams returned by <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/Processes#Process.getInputStream" >Process.getInputStream</a> and <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/Processes#Process.getErrorStream" >Process.getErrorStream</a>. However, standard output and standard error may be redirected to other destinations using <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/Processes#ProcessBuilder.redirectOutput" >ProcessBuilder.redirectOutput</a> and <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/Processes#ProcessBuilder.redirectError" >ProcessBuilder.redirectError</a>. In this case, <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/Processes#Process.getInputStream" >Process.getInputStream</a> and/or <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/Processes#Process.getErrorStream" >Process.getErrorStream</a> will return an input stream, for which the <span class="code" >read</span> methods always return <span class="code" >-1</span>, the <span class="code" >available</span> method always returns <span class="code" >0</span> and the <span class="code" >close</span> method does nothing.</li> <li > a <i >redirectErrorStream</i> property. Initially, this property is false, meaning that the standard output and error output of a subprocess are sent to two separate streams, which can be accessed using the <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/Processes#Process.getInputStream" >Process.getInputStream</a> and <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/Processes#Process.getErrorStream" >Process.getErrorStream</a> methods. If the value is set to true, then standard error is merged with the standard output and always sent to the same destination (this makes it easier to correlate error messages with the corresponding output); the common destination of standard error and standard output can be redirected using <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/Processes#ProcessBuilder.redirectOutput" >ProcessBuilder.redirectOutput</a>; and any redirection set by the <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/Processes#ProcessBuilder.redirectError" >ProcessBuilder.redirectError</a> method is ignored when creating a subprocess.</li> </ul> 
--   Modifying a process builder's attributes will affect processes subsequently started by that object's start() method, but will never affect previously started processes or the Java process itself. 
--   Most error checking is performed by the start() method. It is possible to modify the state of an object so that start() will fail. For example, setting the command attribute to an empty list will not throw an exception unless start() is invoked. 
--   Note that this type is not synchronized. If multiple threads access a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/Processes#ProcessBuilder" >ProcessBuilder</a> instance concurrently, and at least one of the threads modifies one of the attributes structurally, it must be synchronized externally. <h3 > Member Functions</h3>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="ProcessBuilder.directory" >directory</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/Processes#ProcessBuilder" >ProcessBuilder</a></b> → <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../../prelude/PreludeIO.html#MutableIO" >MutableIO</a> <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../IO.html#File" >File</a></b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#IO" >IO</a> <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/Processes#ProcessBuilder" >ProcessBuilder</a><br ></br>

--   set the working directory

--  <b >native </b>inheritIO</span>

--   inherit the standard input, output and error from the current process

--   
--   create a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/Processes#ProcessBuilder" >ProcessBuilder</a> passing the command line as list.   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="ProcessBuilder.newFromArray" >newFromArray</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../../prelude/PreludeArrays.html#ArrayOf" >ArrayOf</a> <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#RealWorld" >RealWorld</a> <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#String" >String</a></b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#IO" >IO</a> <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/lang/Processes#ProcessBuilder" >ProcessBuilder</a><br ></br>
--  <b >native </b>new</span> 
--

--   
--   Creates an ArrayBlockingQueue with the given (fixed) capacity and the specified access policy. 
--   If the <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Bool" >Bool</a> argument is missing, the default access policy is used. If it is <span class="code" >true</span> then queue accesses for threads blocked on insertion or removal, are processed in FIFO order; otherwise the access order is unspecified.

--   <span class="code" ><a name="JarEntry._new" >new</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/./Zip.html#ZipEntry" >ZipEntry</a> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#IO" >IO</a> <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Jar#JarEntry" >JarEntry</a><br ></br>

-- | Support for working with regular expressions.
--   This exposes <span class="code" >java.util.regex.Pattern</span> as <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#Regex" >Regex</a> and <span class="code" >java.util.regex.MatchResult</span> as <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#MatchResult" >MatchResult</a>.
--   This module must have been imported during compilation or certain language features can not be used (see below).<h2 > Frege language support</h2><h3 > Regex literals</h3>
--   Regular expression literals have type <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#Regex" >Regex</a> and are written:
--  <pre>
--  
--   &acute;\b(foo|bar)\b&acute;       -- string enclosed in grave accents
--   '\w+'                 -- string with length &gt; 1 enclosed in apostrophes
--  </pre>
--   The notation with the apostrophes has been introduced because many have a hard time entering a grave accent mark on their terminal. However, it is not possible to write a regular expressions with length 1 this way, because then the literal gets interpreted as <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Char" >Char</a> literal. (One can write something like <span class="code" >'(?:X)'</span> for a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#Regex" >Regex</a> that matches a single <span class="code" >'X'</span>).
--   The advantage of using literals rather than compiling string constants to patterns at runtime is
--   1) they are checked by the Frege compiler, and illegal ones cause compilation to fail
--   2) at runtime, literals are available as immutable values of type <span class="code" >java.util.regex.Pattern</span>, not as strings, as can be seen so often in human written Java code. Thus the cost of repeated regex compilation is avoided.
--   3) The regular expression can be written directly, like in Perl or other languages, without taking String escape rules into account. That is, to match a $ sign, one writes
--  <pre>
--  
--   &acute;\$&acute;
--  </pre>
--   and not
--  <pre>
--  
--   &quot;\\$&quot;
--  </pre>
--   like in Java.
--   The <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#Regex" >Regex</a> values created from the literals have the following flags enabled: <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#Regex.canon_eq" >Regex.canon_eq</a>, <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#Regex.unicode_case" >Regex.unicode_case</a> and <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#Regex.unicode_character_class" >Regex.unicode_character_class</a>. That is, they do their best - as far as Java supports it - to get processing of Unicode strings right.<h3 > <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#Regex" >Regex</a> literals in pattern matching</h3>
--   A <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#Regex" >Regex</a> literal is a valid pattern, like any literal:
--  <pre>
--  
--   case expr1 of
--     &acute;\w+&acute;  &rarr;  expr2
--  </pre>
--   This is equivalent to:
--  <pre>
--  
--   case expr1 of
--     s | s ~ &acute;\w+&acute; &rarr;  expr2
--  </pre>
--   where <i >s</i> is some fresh variable that doesn't appear in <i >expr2</i>.
--   The match succeeds if the <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#String" >String</a> value resulting from evaluation of <i >expr1</i> matches the regular expression given. The match diverges when <i >expr1</i> diverges. In all other cases, the match fails.
--   Note that in this simple form, the value of <i >expr1</i> is not available in <i >expr2</i>. One can use an "at" pattern for this:
--  <pre>
--  
--   case expr1 of
--      string@'\w+'  &rarr;  expr2
--  </pre>
--   which gets desugared to
--  <pre>
--  
--   case expr1 of
--     string | string ~ '\w+'  &rarr;  expr2
--  </pre>
--   leaving <i >string</i> bound to the value of <i >expr1</i>.
--   The following syntax not only checks if the regular expression matches but also binds the <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#MatchResult" >MatchResult</a>:
--  <pre>
--  
--   case expr1 of
--     m~'\w+'  &rarr;  expr2
--  </pre>
--   It is equivalent to
--  <pre>
--  
--   case expr1 of
--     s | Just m &larr; s =~ '\w+'  &rarr;  expr2
--  </pre>
--   where <i >s</i> is again a fresh variable not known in <i >expr2</i>, but when the match succeeds <i >m</i> is bound to the <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#MatchResult" >MatchResult</a> and can be inspected further in <i >expr2</i>.
--   And finally, a pattern like
--  <pre>
--  
--   s@m~'\w+'
--  </pre>
--   works like the previous one but in addition binds <i >s</i> to the string value in question.
module frege.java.util.Regex

-- | <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#Regex" >Regex</a> values are based on Java's <span class="code" >java.util.regex.Pattern</span> objects, which are compiled representations of regular expressions. 
--   We call them <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#Regex" >Regex</a> and not <span class="code" >Pattern</span> in Frege, because the word "pattern" and the phrase "pattern matching" have a quite different meaning in deconstruction of algebraic data types. 
--   There are 2 ways to obtain a compiled regular expression: <ol > <li > Use a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#Regex" >Regex</a> literal, see the language reference section 2.7.3. All regular expression literals are values of type <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#Regex" >Regex</a>. It is not possible to run a program which contains a syntactically invalid <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#Regex" >Regex</a> literal - the compiler will flag it already at compile time. Hence, with <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#Regex" >Regex</a> literals one is immune against <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#PatternSyntaxException" >PatternSyntaxException</a>s.</li> <li > Compile a String with <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#Regex.compile" >Regex.compile</a> or <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#regforce" >regforce</a> at run-time. Illegal regular expression will cause <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#PatternSyntaxException" >PatternSyntaxException</a> to be thrown, which, when not handled appropriately, may crash the program.</li> </ol> 
--   <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#Regex" >Regex</a> values are immutable. <h3 > Member Functions</h3>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Regex.canon_eq" >canon_eq</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a><br ></br>
--  <b >pure </b><b >native </b>java.util.regex.Pattern.CANON_EQ</span> 
--   
--   Enables canonical equivalence. 
--   When this flag is specified then two characters will be considered to match if, and only if, their full canonical decompositions match. The expression <span class="code" >´a\u030A´</span>, for example, will match the string <span class="code" >"\u00E5"</span> when this flag is specified. 
--   There is no embedded flag character for enabling canonical equivalence. 
--   Specifying this flag may impose a performance penalty. 
--   Frege <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#Regex" >Regex</a> literals will always be parsed with this flag.  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Regex.case_insensitive" >case_insensitive</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a><br ></br>
--  <b >pure </b><b >native </b>java.util.regex.Pattern.CASE_INSENSITIVE</span> 
--   
--   Enables case-insensitive matching. 
--   By default, case-insensitive matching assumes that only characters in the US-ASCII charset are being matched. Unicode-aware case-insensitive matching can be enabled by specifying the <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#Regex.unicode_case" >Regex.unicode_case</a> flag in conjunction with this flag. 
--   Case-insensitive matching can also be enabled via the embedded flag expression (?i). 
--   Specifying this flag may impose a slight performance penalty.  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Regex.comments" >comments</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a><br ></br>
--  <b >pure </b><b >native </b>java.util.regex.Pattern.COMMENTS</span> 
--   
--   Permits whitespace and comments in pattern. 
--   In this mode, whitespace is ignored, and embedded comments starting with <span class="code" >#</span> are ignored until the end of a line. 
--   Comments mode can also be enabled via the embedded flag expression <span class="code" >(?x)</span>.  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Regex.compile" >compile</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#String" >String</a> → (<a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#PatternSyntaxException" >PatternSyntaxException</a> | <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#Regex" >Regex</a>)<br ></br>
--           | <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#String" >String</a> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a> → (<a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#PatternSyntaxException" >PatternSyntaxException</a> | <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#Regex" >Regex</a>)<br ></br>

--   compile a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#String" >String</a> to a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#Regex" >Regex</a> 
--   Returns <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#either" >either</a> a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#PatternSyntaxException" >PatternSyntaxException</a> in <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Either.Left" >Either.Left</a> or a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#Regex" >Regex</a> in <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Either.Right" >Either.Right</a>. 
--   The overloaded form has an additional <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a> argument which is a set of flags. Such a set can be constructed by adding up the individual flag values, for example: 
--  <pre>
--  
--    Regex.compile &quot;foo|bar&quot; (Regex.canon_eq + Regex.case_insensitive)
--  </pre>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Regex.compileα" >compileα</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#String" >String</a></b> → (<a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#PatternSyntaxException" >PatternSyntaxException</a> | <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#Regex" >Regex</a>)<br ></br>

--   compile a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#String" >String</a> to a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#Regex" >Regex</a>

--  <pre>
