--  </pre>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Regex.dotall" >dotall</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a><br ></br>
--  <b >pure </b><b >native </b>java.util.regex.Pattern.DOTALL</span> 
--   
--   Enables dotall mode. 
--   In dotall mode, the expression <span class="code" >.</span> matches any character, including a line terminator. By default this expression does not match line terminators. 
--   Dotall mode can also be enabled via the embedded flag expression <span class="code" >(?s)</span>. (The <span class="code" >s</span> is a mnemonic for "single-line" mode, which is what this is called in Perl.)  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Regex.flags" >flags</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#Regex" >Regex</a></b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a><br ></br>
--  <b >pure </b><b >native </b>flags</span> 
--   
--   return the flags this pattern was compiled with   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Regex.literal" >literal</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a><br ></br>
--  <b >pure </b><b >native </b>java.util.regex.Pattern.LITERAL</span> 
--   
--   Enables literal parsing of the pattern. 
--   When this flag is specified then the input string that specifies the pattern is treated as a sequence of literal characters. Metacharacters or escape sequences in the input sequence will be given no special meaning. 
--   The flags <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#Regex.case_insensitive" >Regex.case_insensitive</a> and <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#Regex.unicode_case" >Regex.unicode_case</a> retain their impact on matching when used in conjunction with this flag. The other flags become superfluous. 
--   There is no embedded flag character for enabling literal parsing.  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Regex.multiline" >multiline</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a><br ></br>
--  <b >pure </b><b >native </b>java.util.regex.Pattern.MULTILINE</span> 
--   
--   Enables multiline mode. 
--   In multiline mode the expressions <span class="code" >^</span> and <span class="code" >$</span> match just after or just before, respectively, a line terminator or the end of the input sequence. By default these expressions only match at the beginning and the end of the entire input sequence. 
--   Multiline mode can also be enabled via the embedded flag expression <span class="code" >(?m)</span>.  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Regex.pattern" >pattern</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#Regex" >Regex</a></b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#String" >String</a><br ></br>
--  <b >pure </b><b >native </b>pattern</span> 
--   
--   return the source of this <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#Regex" >Regex</a>   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Regex.split" >split</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#Regex" >Regex</a></b> → <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#String" >String</a></b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/../../prelude/PreludeArrays.html#JArray" >JArray</a> <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#String" >String</a><br ></br>
--  <b >pure </b><b >native </b>split</span> 
--   
--   <span class="code" >java.util.regex.Pattern.split</span> method 
--   As this returns a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#String" >String</a> array, one usually uses <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#Regex.splitted" >Regex.splitted</a>   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Regex.splitted" >splitted</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#Regex" >Regex</a></b> → <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#String" >String</a></b> → [<a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#String" >String</a>]</span> 
--   
--   Split a string around matches of a regular expression and return the result as list of strings. 
--   Empty strings on the start of the string are preserved, but not those on the end of the string, e.g.: 
--  <pre>
--  
--    &acute;,&acute;.splitted &quot;,,a,b,c,,&quot; == [&quot;&quot;, &quot;&quot;, &quot;a&quot;, &quot;b&quot;, &quot;c&quot;]
--  </pre>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Regex.toString" >toString</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#Regex" >Regex</a></b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#String" >String</a><br ></br>
--  <b >pure </b><b >native </b>toString</span> 
--   
--   Returns the string representation of this pattern. 
--   This is the regular expression from which this pattern was <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#Regex.compile" >Regex.compile</a>d.   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Regex.unicode_case" >unicode_case</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a><br ></br>
--  <b >pure </b><b >native </b>java.util.regex.Pattern.UNICODE_CASE</span> 
--   
--   Enables Unicode-aware case folding. 
--   When this flag is specified then case-insensitive matching, when enabled by the <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#Regex.case_insensitive" >Regex.case_insensitive</a> flag, is done in a manner consistent with the Unicode Standard. By default, case-insensitive matching assumes that only characters in the US-ASCII charset are being matched. 
--   Unicode-aware case folding can also be enabled via the embedded flag expression <span class="code" >(?u)</span>. 
--   Specifying this flag may impose a performance penalty. 
--   Because Frege <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#Regex" >Regex</a> literals will always be parsed with the <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#Regex.unicode_character_class" >Regex.unicode_character_class</a> flag, this flag is also implicitly enabled by default. 
--   It can be disabled with the embedded flag expression <span class="code" >(?-u)</span>.  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Regex.unicode_character_class" >unicode_character_class</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a><br ></br>
--  <b >pure </b><b >native </b>java.util.regex.Pattern.UNICODE_CHARACTER_CLASS</span> 
--   
--   Enables the Unicode version of Predefined character classes and POSIX character classes. 
--   When this flag is specified then the (US-ASCII only) Predefined character classes and POSIX character classes are in conformance with <a href="http://www.unicode.org/reports/tr18/" >Unicode Technical Standard #18: Unicode Regular Expression</a> Annex C: Compatibility Properties. 
--   The <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#Regex.unicode_character_class" >Regex.unicode_character_class</a> mode can also be enabled via the embedded flag expression <span class="code" >(?U)</span>. 
--   The flag implies <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#Regex.unicode_case" >Regex.unicode_case</a>, that is, it enables Unicode-aware case folding. 
--   Specifying this flag may impose a performance penalty. 
--   Frege <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#Regex" >Regex</a> literals will always be parsed with this flag. It can be disabled with the embedded flag expression <span class="code" >(?-U)</span>.  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Regex.unix_lines" >unix_lines</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a><br ></br>
--  <b >pure </b><b >native </b>java.util.regex.Pattern.UNIX_LINES</span> 
--   
--   Enables UNIX lines mode. 
--   In this mode, only the <span class="code" >\n</span> line terminator is recognized in the behavior of <span class="code" >.</span>, <span class="code" >^</span>, and <span class="code" >$</span>. 
--   Unix lines mode can also be enabled via the embedded flag expression <span class="code" >(?d)</span>.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#Regex
data Regex 

-- | Enables canonical equivalence. 
--   When this flag is specified then two characters will be considered to match if, and only if, their full canonical decompositions match. The expression <span class="code" >´a\u030A´</span>, for example, will match the string <span class="code" >"\u00E5"</span> when this flag is specified. 
--   There is no embedded flag character for enabling canonical equivalence. 
--   Specifying this flag may impose a performance penalty. 
--   Frege <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#Regex" >Regex</a> literals will always be parsed with this flag.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#Regex.canon_eq
canon_eq ∷ Int 
pure native java.util.regex.Pattern.CANON_EQ

-- | Enables case-insensitive matching. 
--   By default, case-insensitive matching assumes that only characters in the US-ASCII charset are being matched. Unicode-aware case-insensitive matching can be enabled by specifying the <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#Regex.unicode_case" >Regex.unicode_case</a> flag in conjunction with this flag. 
--   Case-insensitive matching can also be enabled via the embedded flag expression (?i). 
--   Specifying this flag may impose a slight performance penalty.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#Regex.case_insensitive
case_insensitive ∷ Int 
pure native java.util.regex.Pattern.CASE_INSENSITIVE

-- | Permits whitespace and comments in pattern. 
--   In this mode, whitespace is ignored, and embedded comments starting with <span class="code" >#</span> are ignored until the end of a line. 
--   Comments mode can also be enabled via the embedded flag expression <span class="code" >(?x)</span>.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#Regex.comments
comments ∷ Int 
pure native java.util.regex.Pattern.COMMENTS

-- | compile a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#String" >String</a> to a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#Regex" >Regex</a> 
--   Returns <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#either" >either</a> a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#PatternSyntaxException" >PatternSyntaxException</a> in <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Either.Left" >Either.Left</a> or a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#Regex" >Regex</a> in <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Either.Right" >Either.Right</a>. 
--   The overloaded form has an additional <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a> argument which is a set of flags. Such a set can be constructed by adding up the individual flag values, for example: 
--  <pre>
--  
--    Regex.compile &quot;foo|bar&quot; (Regex.canon_eq + Regex.case_insensitive)
--  </pre>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#Regex.compile

-- | Enables dotall mode. 
--   In dotall mode, the expression <span class="code" >.</span> matches any character, including a line terminator. By default this expression does not match line terminators. 
--   Dotall mode can also be enabled via the embedded flag expression <span class="code" >(?s)</span>. (The <span class="code" >s</span> is a mnemonic for "single-line" mode, which is what this is called in Perl.)

-- | Enables literal parsing of the pattern. 
--   When this flag is specified then the input string that specifies the pattern is treated as a sequence of literal characters. Metacharacters or escape sequences in the input sequence will be given no special meaning. 
--   The flags <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#Regex.case_insensitive" >Regex.case_insensitive</a> and <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#Regex.unicode_case" >Regex.unicode_case</a> retain their impact on matching when used in conjunction with this flag. The other flags become superfluous. 
--   There is no embedded flag character for enabling literal parsing.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#Regex.literal
literal ∷ Int 
pure native java.util.regex.Pattern.LITERAL

-- | Enables multiline mode. 
--   In multiline mode the expressions <span class="code" >^</span> and <span class="code" >$</span> match just after or just before, respectively, a line terminator or the end of the input sequence. By default these expressions only match at the beginning and the end of the entire input sequence. 
--   Multiline mode can also be enabled via the embedded flag expression <span class="code" >(?m)</span>.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#Regex.multiline
multiline ∷ Int 
pure native java.util.regex.Pattern.MULTILINE

-- | return the source of this <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#Regex" >Regex</a>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#Regex.pattern
pattern ∷ Regex → String 
pure native pattern

-- | <span class="code" >java.util.regex.Pattern.split</span> method 
--   As this returns a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#String" >String</a> array, one usually uses <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#Regex.splitted" >Regex.splitted</a>

-- | Split a string around matches of a regular expression and return the result as list of strings. 
--   Empty strings on the start of the string are preserved, but not those on the end of the string, e.g.: 
--  <pre>
--  
--    &acute;,&acute;.splitted &quot;,,a,b,c,,&quot; == [&quot;&quot;, &quot;&quot;, &quot;a&quot;, &quot;b&quot;, &quot;c&quot;]
--  </pre>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#Regex.splitted

-- | Returns the string representation of this pattern.

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#Regex.toString
toString ∷ Regex → String

-- | Enables Unicode-aware case folding. 
--   When this flag is specified then case-insensitive matching, when enabled by the <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#Regex.case_insensitive" >Regex.case_insensitive</a> flag, is done in a manner consistent with the Unicode Standard. By default, case-insensitive matching assumes that only characters in the US-ASCII charset are being matched. 
--   Unicode-aware case folding can also be enabled via the embedded flag expression <span class="code" >(?u)</span>. 
--   Specifying this flag may impose a performance penalty. 
--   Because Frege <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#Regex" >Regex</a> literals will always be parsed with the <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#Regex.unicode_character_class" >Regex.unicode_character_class</a> flag, this flag is also implicitly enabled by default. 
--   It can be disabled with the embedded flag expression <span class="code" >(?-u)</span>.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#Regex.unicode_case
unicode_case ∷ Int 
pure native java.util.regex.Pattern.UNICODE_CASE

-- | Enables the Unicode version of Predefined character classes and POSIX character classes. 
--   When this flag is specified then the (US-ASCII only) Predefined character classes and POSIX character classes are in conformance with <a href="http://www.unicode.org/reports/tr18/" >Unicode Technical Standard #18: Unicode Regular Expression</a> Annex C: Compatibility Properties. 
--   The <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#Regex.unicode_character_class" >Regex.unicode_character_class</a> mode can also be enabled via the embedded flag expression <span class="code" >(?U)</span>. 
--   The flag implies <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#Regex.unicode_case" >Regex.unicode_case</a>, that is, it enables Unicode-aware case folding. 
--   Specifying this flag may impose a performance penalty. 
--   Frege <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#Regex" >Regex</a> literals will always be parsed with this flag. It can be disabled with the embedded flag expression <span class="code" >(?-U)</span>.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#Regex.unicode_character_class
unicode_character_class ∷ Int 
pure native java.util.regex.Pattern.UNICODE_CHARACTER_CLASS

-- | Enables UNIX lines mode. 
--   In this mode, only the <span class="code" >\n</span> line terminator is recognized in the behavior of <span class="code" >.</span>, <span class="code" >^</span>, and <span class="code" >$</span>. 
--   Unix lines mode can also be enabled via the embedded flag expression <span class="code" >(?d)</span>.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#Regex.unix_lines
unix_lines ∷ Int 
pure native java.util.regex.Pattern.UNIX_LINES

-- | Will be thrown when one compiles a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#String" >String</a> to a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#Regex" >Regex</a> using <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#Regex.compile" >Regex.compile</a> or <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#regforce" >regforce</a>

-- | this is only used to inject the replace functions into <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#String" >String</a>  <h3 > Known Instances</h3> 
--   <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#Replace_String" >StringJ</a> <h3 > Member Functions</h3>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Replace.replaceAll" >replaceAll</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#Replace" >Replace</a> s ⇒ s → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#Regex" >Regex</a> → s → s</span> 
--   
--   Like <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#Replace.replaceFirst" >Replace.replaceFirst</a>, but replaces <b >all</b> substrings that match the pattern.  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Replace.replaceFirst" >replaceFirst</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#Replace" >Replace</a> s ⇒ s → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#Regex" >Regex</a> → s → s</span> 
--   
--   Replaces the first subsequence of the input sequence that matches the pattern with the given replacement string. 
--   This method scans the input sequence from the start looking for a match of the pattern. Characters that are not part of the match are appended directly to the result string; the match is replaced in the result by the replacement string. The replacement string may contain references to captured subsequences. 
--   Note that backslashes (\\) and dollar signs ($) in the replacement string may cause the results to be different than if it were being treated as a literal replacement string. Dollar signs may be treated as references to captured subsequences as described above, and backslashes are used to escape literal characters in the replacement string. 
--   For example 
--  <pre>
--  
--   replaceFirst &quot;zzzdogzzzdogzzz&quot; &acute;dog&acute; &quot;cat&quot; == &quot;zzzcatzzzdogzzz&quot;
--  </pre>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#Replace
class Replace s

-- | Like <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#Replace.replaceFirst" >Replace.replaceFirst</a>, but replaces <b >all</b> substrings that match the pattern.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#Replace.replaceAll
replaceAll ∷ Replace s ⇒ s → Regex → s → s

-- | Replaces the first subsequence of the input sequence that matches the pattern with the given replacement string. 
--   This method scans the input sequence from the start looking for a match of the pattern. Characters that are not part of the match are appended directly to the result string; the match is replaced in the result by the replacement string. The replacement string may contain references to captured subsequences. 
--   Note that backslashes (\\) and dollar signs ($) in the replacement string may cause the results to be different than if it were being treated as a literal replacement string. Dollar signs may be treated as references to captured subsequences as described above, and backslashes are used to escape literal characters in the replacement string. 
--   For example 
--  <pre>
--  
--   replaceFirst &quot;zzzdogzzzdogzzz&quot; &acute;dog&acute; &quot;cat&quot; == &quot;zzzcatzzzdogzzz&quot;
--  </pre>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#Replace.replaceFirst
replaceFirst ∷ Replace s ⇒ s → Regex → s → s

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#substituteFirst

-- | This interface contains query methods used to determine the results of a match against a regular expression. 
--   More: <a href="https://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/util/regex/MatchResult.html" >JavaDoc</a> <h3 > Member Functions</h3>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="MatchResult.end" >end</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#MatchResult" >MatchResult</a></b> → <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a></b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a><br ></br>
--  <b >pure </b><b >native </b>end</span> 
--   
--   Returns the offset after the last character of the subsequence captured by the given group during the previous match operation where group 0 denotes the entire pattern. 
--   If the specified capturing group failed to match, the return value will be -1. 
--   The following property holds: 
--  <pre>
--  
--   (m.group n == Nothing) ==&gt; (m.end n &lt; 0)
--  </pre>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="MatchResult.group" >group</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#MatchResult" >MatchResult</a></b> → <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a></b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Maybe" >Maybe</a> <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#String" >String</a></span> 
--   
--  <pre>
--  
--   group m n
--  </pre> 
--   retrieves the input subsequence captured by the given group index during the previous match operation. 
--   Capturing groups are indexed from left to right, starting at one. Group zero denotes the entire pattern, so the expression <span class="code" >(m.group 0)</span> retrieves that portion of the input string that was matched by the pattern. 
--   If the match was successful but the group specified failed to match any part of the input sequence, then <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Maybe.Nothing" >Maybe.Nothing</a> is returned. 
--   Note that some groups, for example <span class="code" >(a?)</span>, match the empty string. This function will return <span class="code" >Just ""</span> when such a group successfully matches the empty string in the input. 
--   The result will also be <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Maybe.Nothing" >Maybe.Nothing</a> when the specified group does not exist, that is, when the <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a> argument is outside the range <span class="code" >[0..</span><a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#MatchResult.groupCount" >MatchResult.groupCount</a> <span class="code" >m]</span> 
--   The following property holds for a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#MatchResult" >MatchResult</a> <i >m</i> with input sequence <i >s</i> and valid group index <i >g</i>: 
--  <pre>
--  
--   isJust (m.group g) ==&gt; (m.group g) == Just (s.substr (m.start g) (m.end g))
--  </pre>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="MatchResult.groupCount" >groupCount</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#MatchResult" >MatchResult</a></b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a><br ></br>
--  <b >pure </b><b >native </b>groupCount</span> 
--   
--   Returns the number of capturing groups in this matcher's pattern. 
--   Group zero denotes the entire pattern by convention. It is not included in this count. 
--   Any non-negative integer smaller than or equal to the value returned by this method is guaranteed to be a valid group index for this matcher.  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="MatchResult.groupPrim" >groupPrim</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#MatchResult" >MatchResult</a></b> → <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a></b> → (<a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/../Lang.html#IndexOutOfBoundsException" >IndexOutOfBoundsException</a> | <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Maybe" >Maybe</a> <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#String" >String</a>)<br ></br>
--  <b >pure </b><b >native </b>group</span> 
--    
--   <span class="code" ><a name="MatchResult.groups" >groups</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Maybe" >Maybe</a> <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#MatchResult" >MatchResult</a></b> → [<a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Maybe" >Maybe</a> <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#String" >String</a>]</span> 
--   
--   The list of subsequences captured during the previous match operation, or the empty list if there was no match. 
--   To be used like: 
--  <pre>
--  
--   groups $ s =~ regex
--  </pre> 
--   See also <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#_eq_tilde_tilde" >=~~</a>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="MatchResult.match" >match</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#MatchResult" >MatchResult</a></b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#String" >String</a><br ></br>
--  <b >pure </b><b >native </b>group</span> 
--   
--   <span class="code" >MatchResult.match m</span> returns the input subsequence matched by the previous match. The result is <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#undefined" >undefined</a> if the last match was not successful. 
--   For a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#MatchResult" >MatchResult</a> <span class="code" >m</span> with input sequence <span class="code" >s</span>, the following holds: 
--  <pre>
--  
--   isJust (m.group 0) ==&gt; unJust (m.group 0) == m.match
--  </pre> 
--   Note that some patterns, for example <span class="code" >a?</span>, match the empty string. This method will return the empty string when the pattern successfully matches the empty string in the input.  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="MatchResult.start" >start</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#MatchResult" >MatchResult</a></b> → <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a></b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a><br ></br>
--  <b >pure </b><b >native </b>start</span> 
--   
--   Returns the start index of the subsequence captured by the given group during the previous match operation where group 0 denotes the entire pattern. 
--   If the specified capturing group failed to match, the return value will be -1. 
--   The following property holds: 
--  <pre>
--  
--   (m.group n == Nothing) ==&gt; (m.start n &lt; 0)
--  </pre>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#MatchResult
data MatchResult 

-- | Returns the offset after the last character of the subsequence captured by the given group during the previous match operation where group 0 denotes the entire pattern. 
--   If the specified capturing group failed to match, the return value will be -1. 
--   The following property holds: 
--  <pre>
--  
--   (m.group n == Nothing) ==&gt; (m.end n &lt; 0)
--  </pre>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#MatchResult.end
end ∷ MatchResult → Int → Int 
pure native end

-- | <pre>
--  
--   group m n
--  </pre> 
--   retrieves the input subsequence captured by the given group index during the previous match operation. 
--   Capturing groups are indexed from left to right, starting at one. Group zero denotes the entire pattern, so the expression <span class="code" >(m.group 0)</span> retrieves that portion of the input string that was matched by the pattern. 
--   If the match was successful but the group specified failed to match any part of the input sequence, then <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Maybe.Nothing" >Maybe.Nothing</a> is returned. 
--   Note that some groups, for example <span class="code" >(a?)</span>, match the empty string. This function will return <span class="code" >Just ""</span> when such a group successfully matches the empty string in the input. 
--   The result will also be <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Maybe.Nothing" >Maybe.Nothing</a> when the specified group does not exist, that is, when the <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a> argument is outside the range <span class="code" >[0..</span><a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#MatchResult.groupCount" >MatchResult.groupCount</a> <span class="code" >m]</span> 
--   The following property holds for a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#MatchResult" >MatchResult</a> <i >m</i> with input sequence <i >s</i> and valid group index <i >g</i>: 
--  <pre>
--  
--   isJust (m.group g) ==&gt; (m.group g) == Just (s.substr (m.start g) (m.end g))
--  </pre>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#MatchResult.group
group ∷ MatchResult → Int → Maybe String

-- | Returns the number of capturing groups in this matcher's pattern. 
--   Group zero denotes the entire pattern by convention. It is not included in this count. 
--   Any non-negative integer smaller than or equal to the value returned by this method is guaranteed to be a valid group index for this matcher.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#MatchResult.groupCount
groupCount ∷ MatchResult → Int 
pure native groupCount

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#MatchResult.groupPrim
groupPrim ∷ MatchResult → Int → (IndexOutOfBoundsException | Maybe String) 
pure native group

-- | The list of subsequences captured during the previous match operation, or the empty list if there was no match. 
--   To be used like: 
--  <pre>
--  
--   groups $ s =~ regex
--  </pre> 
--   See also <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#_eq_tilde_tilde" >=~~</a>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#MatchResult.groups
groups ∷ Maybe MatchResult → [Maybe String]

-- | <span class="code" >MatchResult.match m</span> returns the input subsequence matched by the previous match. The result is <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#undefined" >undefined</a> if the last match was not successful. 
--   For a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#MatchResult" >MatchResult</a> <span class="code" >m</span> with input sequence <span class="code" >s</span>, the following holds: 
--  <pre>
--  
--   isJust (m.group 0) ==&gt; unJust (m.group 0) == m.match
--  </pre> 
--   Note that some patterns, for example <span class="code" >a?</span>, match the empty string. This method will return the empty string when the pattern successfully matches the empty string in the input.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#MatchResult.match
match ∷ MatchResult → String 
pure native group

-- | Returns the start index of the subsequence captured by the given group during the previous match operation where group 0 denotes the entire pattern. 
--   If the specified capturing group failed to match, the return value will be -1. 
--   The following property holds: 
--  <pre>
--  
--   (m.group n == Nothing) ==&gt; (m.start n &lt; 0)
--  </pre>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#MatchResult.start
start ∷ MatchResult → Int → Int 
pure native start

-- | <pre>
--  
--   string =~ regex
--  </pre> 
--   tries to match <i >string</i> against <i >regex</i> and returns <span class="code" >Just matcher</span> if it succeeds, <span class="code" >Nothing</span> otherwise.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#_eq_tilde
(=~) ∷  String → Regex → Maybe MatchResult 
pure native frege.runtime.Regex9.findResult 
infix  15

-- | <pre>
--  
--   findAt string regex offset
--  </pre> 
--   Like <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#_eq_tilde" >=~</a>, but matches only the substring of <i >string</i> that starts at <i >offset</i> against <i >regex</i>. 
--   If <i >offset</i> is negative or not smaller than the length of <i >string</i>, the result is <i >Nothing</i>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#findAt
findAt ∷ String → Regex → Int → Maybe MatchResult 
pure native frege.runtime.Regex9.findResult

-- | <pre>
--  
--   string =~~ regex
--  </pre> 
--   tries to match <i >string</i> against <i >regex</i> and returns a list of all captured substrings, see <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#MatchResult.groups" >MatchResult.groups</a>. 
--   Example: 
--  <pre>
--  
--   case &quot;today is 2014-02-18&quot; =~~ &acute;(\d\d\d\d)-(0[1-9]|1[012])-(\d\d)&acute; of
--      [Just date, Just year, Just month, Just day] -&gt; ...
--      baddate -&gt; ....
--  </pre>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#_eq_tilde_tilde
(=~~) ∷  String → Regex → [Maybe String] 
infix  15

-- | <pre>
--  
--  string ~ regex
--  </pre> 
--   <span class="code" >true</span> if <i >string</i> matches <i >regex</i>, <span class="code" >false</span> otherwise
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#_tilde
(~) ∷  String → Regex → Bool 
pure native frege.runtime.Regex9.find 
infix  15

-- | <pre>
--  
--   s !~ p == !(s ~ p)
--  </pre>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#_excl_tilde
(!~) ∷  String → Regex → Bool 
infix  15

-- | <pre>
--  
--   (&quot;string&quot; ~~ &acute;r..&acute;) == Just &quot;rin&quot;
--  </pre> 
--   Tries a match and returns <span class="code" >Just x</span> where <i >x</i> is the matched substring or <span class="code" >Nothing</span> if there was no match.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#_tilde_tilde
(~~) ∷  String → Regex → Maybe String 
infix  15

-- | <pre>
--  
--   string ~~~ regex
--  </pre> 
--   Matches <i >string</i> with <i >regex</i> and returns a function that can be used to extract the matched part of the string and the captured substrings. 
--  <pre>
--  
--     let f = &quot;frege&quot; ~~~ &acute;(..).(..)&acute;
--     in [ f i | i &lt;- 0..3 ]
--  </pre> 
--   yields 
--  <pre>
--  
--  [Just &quot;frege&quot;, Just &quot;fr&quot;, Just &quot;ge&quot;, Nothing]
--  </pre>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#_tilde_tilde_tilde
(~~~) ∷  String → Regex → Int → Maybe String 
infix  15

-- | <pre>
--  
--   &quot;cats and dogs are not concatenated.&quot; ~~* &acute;cat|dog&acute;
--  </pre> 
--   Matches the string with the regex and returns a list of all matches. The example gives: 
--  <pre>
--  
--   [&quot;cat&quot;, &quot;dog&quot;, &quot;cat&quot;]
--  </pre>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/java/util/Regex#_tilde_tilde_star
(~~*) ∷  String → Regex → [String] 
infix  15

-- | Support for ad hoc parallelism in Frege through java's ForkJoin mechanism
module frege.lib.ForkJoin

-- | usage 
--   <div > <span class="code" >a `par` b</span> </div>   
--   Fork evaluation of <span class="code" >a</span> and return <span class="code" >b</span>.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/lib/ForkJoin#par
par ∷ β → α → α 
infixr  2

-- | usage 
--   <div > <span class="code" >f $| a</span> </div>   
--   Equivalent to <span class="code" >a `par` f a</span>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/lib/ForkJoin#$_bar
($|) ∷  (β→α) → β → α 
infixr  1

-- | usage 
--   <div > <span class="code" >parOp f a b</span> </div>   
--   Equivalent to <span class="code" >a `par` b `par` f a b</span>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/lib/ForkJoin#parOp
parOp ∷ (β→γ→α) → β → γ → α

-- | usage 
--   <div > <span class="code" >a :| as</span> </div>   
--   Equivalent to <span class="code" >parOp (:) a as</span>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/lib/ForkJoin#_colon_bar
(:|) ∷  α → [α] → [α] 
infixr  4

-- | usage 
--   <div > <span class="code" >mapP f xs</span> </div>   
--   Like <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/lib/../prelude/PreludeList.html#map" >map</a>, but applies the function parallel to mapping the rest of the list. It does therefore not work with infinite lists.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/lib/ForkJoin#mapP
mapP ∷ (β→α) → [β] → [α]

-- | Find frege modules
module frege.lib.Modules

-- | Walk a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/lib/../java/util/Zip.html#ZipFile" >ZipFile</a> and find Frege modules. 
--   The classes inside the ZIP/JAR must be loadable with the given <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/lib/../java/Lang.html#ClassLoader" >ClassLoader</a> 
--   Ignores <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/lib/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#ClassNotFoundException" >ClassNotFoundException</a>s and the strange <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/lib/../java/Lang.html#Error" >Error</a>s that can happen during class loading.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/lib/Modules#zipWalk
zipWalk ∷ ClassLoader → ZipFile → IO [(String, FregePackage)]

-- | load a package and return maybe a tuple of package name and <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/lib/../compiler/Classtools.html#FregePackage" >FregePackage</a>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/lib/Modules#getX
getX ∷ ClassLoader → String → IO (Maybe (String, FregePackage))

-- | the path separator used here
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/lib/Modules#pathSep
pathSep ∷ String

-- | a pattern that can be used to <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/lib/../java/util/Regex.html#Regex.split" >Regex.split</a> a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/lib/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#String" >String</a> by the path separator
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/lib/Modules#pathRE
pathRE ∷ Regex

-- | the class path this JVM started with, as [<a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/lib/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#String" >String</a>]
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/lib/Modules#classPath
classPath ∷ [String]

-- | Walk a directory and find Frege modules. 
--   The classes in the directory must be loadable with the given <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/lib/../java/Lang.html#ClassLoader" >ClassLoader</a> 
--   Ignores <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/lib/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#ClassNotFoundException" >ClassNotFoundException</a>s and the strange <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/lib/../java/Lang.html#Error" >Error</a>s that can happen during class loading.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/lib/Modules#dirWalk
dirWalk ∷ ClassLoader → String → MutableIO File → IO [(String, FregePackage)]

-- | Walk a directory or a zip file and search for Frege packages. 
--   If the argument is neither a directory nor a ZIP/JAR file, an empty list is returned.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/lib/Modules#walkThing

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/lib/Modules#_main
main ∷ [String] → IO ()

-- | Math functions from <a href="http://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/lang/Math.html" >java.lang.Math</a>. Many of those functions are overloaded for <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Float" >Float</a> and <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Double" >Double</a>, so we introduce a type class <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/Math#Floating" >Floating</a> to avoid overloading issues.
--   For example
--  <pre>
--  
--   f x = 2 * sqrt x
--  </pre>
--   would give a type error, because the compiler wouldn't know whether to use
--  <pre>
--  
--   sqrt :: Float  -&gt; Double
--  </pre>
--   or
--  <pre>
--  
--   sqrt :: Double -&gt; Double
--  </pre>
--   Note that many functions return <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Double" >Double</a>, no matter if the argument was <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Double" >Double</a> or <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Float" >Float</a>.
module frege.prelude.Math

-- | Returns a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Double" >Double</a> with a positive sign, greater than or equal to 0.0 and less than 1.0.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/Math#random
random ∷ () → IO Double 
native java.lang.Math.random

-- | square
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/Math#sqr
sqr ∷ Num a ⇒ a → a
