--   
--   Returns the closest <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Long" >Long</a> to the argument, with ties rounding up.   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Floating.scalb" >scalb</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/Math#Floating" >Floating</a> r ⇒ r → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a> → r</span> 
--   
--  <pre>
--  
--   scalb d scaleFactor
--  </pre> 
--   Return <span class="code" >d * 2^scaleFactor</span> rounded as if performed by a single correctly rounded floating-point multiply.   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Floating.signum" >signum</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/Math#Floating" >Floating</a> r ⇒ r → r</span> 
--   
--   Returns the signum function of the argument; zero if the argument is zero, 1.0 if the argument is greater than zero, -1.0 if the argument is less than zero.   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Floating.sin" >sin</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/Math#Floating" >Floating</a> r ⇒ r → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Double" >Double</a></span> 
--   
--   Returns the trigonometric sine of an angle.   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Floating.sinh" >sinh</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/Math#Floating" >Floating</a> r ⇒ r → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Double" >Double</a></span> 
--   
--   Returns the hyperbolic sine of a value.   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Floating.sqrt" >sqrt</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/Math#Floating" >Floating</a> r ⇒ r → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Double" >Double</a></span> 
--   
--   Returns the correctly rounded positive square root of a value.   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Floating.tan" >tan</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/Math#Floating" >Floating</a> r ⇒ r → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Double" >Double</a></span> 
--   
--   Returns the trigonometric tangent of an angle.   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Floating.tanh" >tanh</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/Math#Floating" >Floating</a> r ⇒ r → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Double" >Double</a></span> 
--   
--   Returns the hyperbolic tangent of a floating point value.   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Floating.toDegrees" >toDegrees</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/Math#Floating" >Floating</a> r ⇒ r → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Double" >Double</a></span> 
--   
--   Converts an angle measured in radians to an approximately equivalent angle measured in degrees.   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Floating.toRadians" >toRadians</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/Math#Floating" >Floating</a> r ⇒ r → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Double" >Double</a></span> 
--   
--   Converts an angle measured in degrees to an approximately equivalent angle measured in radians.   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Floating.ulp" >ulp</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/Math#Floating" >Floating</a> r ⇒ r → r</span> 
--   
--   Returns the size of an ulp of the argument.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/Math#Floating
class (Eq r, Ord r, Num r, Real r) ⇒ Floating r

-- | Returns the arc cosine of a value; the returned angle is in the range 0.0 through <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/Math#Floating.pi" >Floating.pi</a>.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/Math#Floating.acos
acos ∷ Floating r ⇒ r → Double

-- | Inverse hyperbolic function for <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/Math#Floating.cosh" >Floating.cosh</a>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/Math#Floating.acosh
acosh ∷ Floating r ⇒ r → Double

-- | Returns the arc sine of a value; the returned angle is in the range -<a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/Math#Floating.pi" >Floating.pi</a>/2 through <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/Math#Floating.pi" >Floating.pi</a>/2.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/Math#Floating.asin
asin ∷ Floating r ⇒ r → Double

-- | Inverse hyperbolic function for <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/Math#Floating.sinh" >Floating.sinh</a>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/Math#Floating.asinh
asinh ∷ Floating r ⇒ r → Double

-- | Returns the arc tangent of a value; the returned angle is in the range -<a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/Math#Floating.pi" >Floating.pi</a>/2 through <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/Math#Floating.pi" >Floating.pi</a>/2.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/Math#Floating.atan
atan ∷ Floating r ⇒ r → Double

-- | Returns the angle theta from the conversion of rectangular coordinates (x, y) to polar coordinates (r, theta).
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/Math#Floating.atan2
atan2 ∷ Floating r ⇒ r → r → Double

-- | Inverse hyperbolic function for <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/Math#Floating.tanh" >Floating.tanh</a>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/Math#Floating.atanh
atanh ∷ Floating r ⇒ r → Double

-- | Returns the cube root of a value.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/Math#Floating.cbrt
cbrt ∷ Floating r ⇒ r → Double

-- | Returns the smallest (closest to negative infinity) value that is greater than or equal to the argument and is equal to a mathematical integer.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/Math#Floating.ceil
ceil ∷ Floating r ⇒ r → Double

-- | Returns the first argument with the sign of the second argument.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/Math#Floating.copySign
copySign ∷ Floating r ⇒ r → r → r

-- | Returns the trigonometric cosine of an angle.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/Math#Floating.cos
cos ∷ Floating r ⇒ r → Double

-- | Returns the hyperbolic cosine of a floating point value.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/Math#Floating.cosh
cosh ∷ Floating r ⇒ r → Double

-- | The value that is closer than any other to <span class="code" >e</span>, the base of the natural logarithms.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/Math#Floating.e
e ∷ Floating r ⇒ r

-- | Returns Euler's number <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/Math#Floating.e" >Floating.e</a> raised to the power of a floating-point value.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/Math#Floating.exp
exp ∷ Floating r ⇒ r → Double

-- | Returns <span class="code" >e^x -1</span>.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/Math#Floating.expm1
expm1 ∷ Floating r ⇒ r → Double

-- | Returns the largest (closest to positive infinity) value that is less than or equal to the argument and is equal to a mathematical integer. 
--   Special cases: <ul > <li > If the argument value is already equal to a mathematical integer, then the result is the same as the argument.</li> <li > If the argument is NaN or an infinity or positive zero or negative zero, then the result is the same as the argument.</li> </ul>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/Math#Floating.floor
floor ∷ Floating r ⇒ r → Double

-- | Returns the unbiased exponent used in the representation of a floating point number.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/Math#Floating.getExponent
getExponent ∷ Floating r ⇒ r → Int

-- | Returns <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/Math#Floating.sqrt" >Floating.sqrt</a> <span class="code" >(x² + y²)</span> without intermediate overflow or underflow.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/Math#Floating.hypot
hypot ∷ Floating r ⇒ r → r → Double

-- | Computes the remainder operation on two arguments as prescribed by the IEEE 754 standard.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/Math#Floating.ieeeRemainder
ieeeRemainder ∷ Floating r ⇒ r → r → Double

-- | Returns the natural logarithm (base <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/Math#Floating.e" >Floating.e</a>) of a value.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/Math#Floating.log
log ∷ Floating r ⇒ r → Double

-- | Returns the base 10 logarithm of a value.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/Math#Floating.log10
log10 ∷ Floating r ⇒ r → Double

-- | Returns the natural logarithm of the sum of the argument and 1.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/Math#Floating.log1p
log1p ∷ Floating r ⇒ r → Double

-- | Returns the logarithm of the second argument to the base given by the first argument.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/Math#Floating.logBase
logBase ∷ Floating r ⇒ r → r → Double

-- | Returns the floating-point number adjacent to the first argument in the direction of the second argument.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/Math#Floating.nextAfter
nextAfter ∷ Floating r ⇒ r → r → Double

-- | Returns the floating-point value adjacent to the argument in the direction of positive infinity.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/Math#Floating.nextUp
nextUp ∷ Floating r ⇒ r → r

-- | The value that is closer than any other to <span class="code" >pi</span>, the ratio of the circumference of a circle to its diameter.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/Math#Floating.pi
pi ∷ Floating r ⇒ r

-- | Returns the value of the first argument raised to the power of the second argument.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/Math#Floating.pow
pow ∷ Floating r ⇒ r → r → Double 
infixr  15

-- | Returns the double value that is closest in value to the argument and is equal to a mathematical integer.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/Math#Floating.rint
rint ∷ Floating r ⇒ r → Double

-- | Returns the closest <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Long" >Long</a> to the argument, with ties rounding up.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/Math#Floating.round
round ∷ Floating r ⇒ r → Long

-- | <pre>
--  
--   scalb d scaleFactor
--  </pre> 
--   Return <span class="code" >d * 2^scaleFactor</span> rounded as if performed by a single correctly rounded floating-point multiply.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/Math#Floating.scalb
scalb ∷ Floating r ⇒ r → Int → r

-- | Returns the signum function of the argument; zero if the argument is zero, 1.0 if the argument is greater than zero, -1.0 if the argument is less than zero.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/Math#Floating.signum
signum ∷ Floating r ⇒ r → r

-- | Returns the trigonometric sine of an angle.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/Math#Floating.sin
sin ∷ Floating r ⇒ r → Double

-- | Returns the hyperbolic sine of a value.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/Math#Floating.sinh
sinh ∷ Floating r ⇒ r → Double

-- | Returns the correctly rounded positive square root of a value.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/Math#Floating.sqrt
sqrt ∷ Floating r ⇒ r → Double

-- | Returns the trigonometric tangent of an angle.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/Math#Floating.tan
tan ∷ Floating r ⇒ r → Double

-- | Returns the hyperbolic tangent of a floating point value.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/Math#Floating.tanh
tanh ∷ Floating r ⇒ r → Double

-- | Converts an angle measured in radians to an approximately equivalent angle measured in degrees.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/Math#Floating.toDegrees
toDegrees ∷ Floating r ⇒ r → Double

-- | Converts an angle measured in degrees to an approximately equivalent angle measured in radians.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/Math#Floating.toRadians
toRadians ∷ Floating r ⇒ r → Double

-- | Returns the size of an ulp of the argument.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/Math#Floating.ulp
ulp ∷ Floating r ⇒ r → r

-- | Provides functions and instances for the <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Maybe" >Maybe</a> type.
--   Compatible with the Haskell 2010 <i >Data.Maybe</i> module.
module frege.prelude.Maybe

-- | <span class="code" >true</span> if and only if the argument is a <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Maybe.Just" >Maybe.Just</a> value
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/Maybe#isJust
isJust ∷ Maybe α → Bool

-- | <span class="code" >true</span> if and only if the argument is <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Maybe.Nothing" >Maybe.Nothing</a> 
--   This function is preferable over <span class="code" >v == Nothing</span> because no <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Eq" >Eq</a> constraint is needed.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/Maybe#isNothing
isNothing ∷ Maybe α → Bool

-- | <span class="code" >fromMaybe d (Just a)</span> returns <span class="code" >a</span> and <span class="code" >fromMaybe d Nothing</span> returns <span class="code" >d</span>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/Maybe#fromMaybe
fromMaybe ∷ α → Maybe α → α

-- | <span class="code" >unJust Nothing</span> is <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#undefined" >undefined</a> whereas <span class="code" >unJust (Just a)</span> is <span class="code" >a</span>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/Maybe#unJust
unJust ∷ Maybe α → α

-- | The <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/Maybe#catMaybes" >catMaybes</a> function takes a list of <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Maybe" >Maybe</a>s and returns a list of all the <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Maybe.Just" >Maybe.Just</a> values.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/Maybe#catMaybes
catMaybes ∷ ListSource β ⇒ β (Maybe α) → [α]

-- | The <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/Maybe#mapMaybe" >mapMaybe</a> function is a version of <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeList.html#map" >map</a> which can throw out elements. In particular, the functional argument returns something of type <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Maybe" >Maybe</a> <i >b</i>. If this is <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Maybe.Nothing" >Maybe.Nothing</a>, no element is added on to the result list. If it just <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Maybe.Just" >Maybe.Just</a> <i >b</i>, then <i >b</i> is included in the result list.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/Maybe#mapMaybe
mapMaybe ∷ (β→Maybe α) → [β] → [α]

-- | give the first element of a list or <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Maybe.Nothing" >Maybe.Nothing</a>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/Maybe#listToMaybe
listToMaybe ∷ ListSource α ⇒ α β → Maybe β

-- | convert a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Maybe" >Maybe</a> to a single element list or an empty list
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/Maybe#maybeToList
maybeToList ∷ Maybe a → [a]

-- | Support for Java reflective arrays.
module frege.prelude.PreludeArrays

-- | short hand for <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeIO.html#Mutable" >Mutable</a> <span class="code" >s</span> (<a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#JArray" >JArray</a> <span class="code" >a</span>)
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#ArrayOf
type ArrayOf s a = Mutable s (JArray a)

-- | The type <span class="code" >JArray X</span> corresponds to Java's <span class="code" >J[]</span> for any type <span class="code" >X</span> where <span class="code" >J</span> is the corresponding java type of <span class="code" >X</span>, but note that Java does not really have generic arrays. 
--   We can use arrays generically inside Frege, but native code that expects or returns arrays will not be generic. 
--   The native interface will take every occurrence of 
--  <pre>
--  
--   JArray X
--  </pre> 
--   or 
--  <pre>
--  
--   Mutable s (JArray X)
--  </pre> 
--   in native declarations to denote the corresponding Java array type. But when the type argument is variable, it will be just <span class="code" >Object</span>. This corresponds to the usage in <a href="http://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/index.html?java/lang/reflect/Array.html" >the array reflection API</a>. 
--   Multi-dimensional arrays are not very well supported out of the box. If one needs more than 1 dimensions, the type will get quite complex, as of course arrays are mutable and so one will have multiple levels of <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#JArray" >JArray</a> nested in <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeIO.html#Mutable" >Mutable</a> nested in <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#JArray" >JArray</a> and so forth. Moreover, multi-dimensional arrays cannot be generic at all. 
--   Note that there are really 2 different APIs: <ol > <li > With the <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#JArray.getElemAt" >JArray.getElemAt</a>, <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#JArray.getAt" >JArray.getAt</a>, <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#JArray.setAt" >JArray.setAt</a>, <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#JArray.setElemAt" >JArray.setElemAt</a>, <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#JArray.itemAt" >JArray.itemAt</a> and <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#JArray.elemAt" >JArray.elemAt</a> it is possible to work on Java objects with java compile time type <span class="code" >java.lang.Object</span> <b >or</b> <span class="code" >X[]</span> for some java type <span class="code" >X</span> <b >or</b> <span class="code" >java.lang.Object[]</span>, but the run time type is always <span class="code" >java.lang.Object[]</span>.</li> <li > With the <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#ArrayElem.newArray" >ArrayElem.newArray</a>, <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#ArrayElem.getElemAt" >ArrayElem.getElemAt</a>, <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#ArrayElem.getAt" >ArrayElem.getAt</a>, <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#ArrayElem.setAt" >ArrayElem.setAt</a>, <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#ArrayElem.setElemAt" >ArrayElem.setElemAt</a>, <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#ArrayElem.itemAt" >ArrayElem.itemAt</a> and <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#ArrayElem.elemAt" >ArrayElem.elemAt</a> functions of the <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#ArrayElem" >ArrayElem</a> class for some type <span class="code" >F</span> that is an instance of <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#ArrayElem" >ArrayElem</a>, we can work on Java objects with Java compile time type <span class="code" >X[]</span>, where <span class="code" >X</span> is the Java type corresponding to <span class="code" >F</span>, but the run time type is always <span class="code" >X[]</span>.</li> </ol> 
--   The former ones are usable only in polymorphic functions where the type argument for <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#JArray" >JArray</a> is a variable and we don't (want to) have <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#ArrayElem" >ArrayElem</a> constraints. They are not good for interfacing native methods that take or return arrays of a certain type. Run time type errors are possible because native methods could put anything there. However, when used in Frege only, the typing is safe. 
--   The latter ones are truly type safe, because their Frege type corresponds to the expected Java compile time type, which is also the actual run time type. 
--   Here is a cheat sheet for the different array get and set methods: 
--  <pre>
--  
--               Array type            Argument/    Description
--                                     Result
--  </pre> 
--  <pre>
--  
--   setAt       Mutable (JArray s X)  Maybe X     set null or data element
--   setElemAt   Mutable (JArray s X)  X           set data element
--   getAt       Mutable (JArray s X)  Maybe X     get null or data element
--   getElemAt   Mutable (JArray s X)  X           get data element (unsafe)
--   itemAt      JArray s X            Maybe X     get null or data element (pure)
--   elemAt      JArray s X            X           get data element (pure, unsafe)
--  </pre> 
--   "unsafe" in this context applies only to non-primitive types and means that the function will fail with a <span class="code" >NullPointerException</span> if the value accessed is a Java <span class="code" >null</span>. <h3 > Member Functions</h3>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="JArray.cache" >cache</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#ArrayElem" >ArrayElem</a> β ⇒ (<a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a>→<a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#JArray" >JArray</a> β→β) → <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a></b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeIO.html#STMutable" >STMutable</a> α (<a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#JArray" >JArray</a> β)</span> 
--   
--   Create a mutable array of a given size and compute the values of its elements by some function. The function gets the current index and the already computed values in the form of an immutable array, where it can access elements with a <b >smaller</b> index than the current one. 
--   The restriction to smaller indexes is because array elements are strict in Frege. For example, we can't store unevaluated values in an <span class="code" >int[]</span> array, because the Java type of unevaluated values is not <span class="code" >int</span>. 
--   To create an array of 1000 fibonacci numbers, one could write: 
--  <pre>
--  
--   cache fib 1000 where
--     fib 0 _ = 1n
--     fib 1 _ = 1n
--     fib n a = a.[n-1] + a.[n-2]
--  </pre>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="JArray.elemAt" >elemAt</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#JArray" >JArray</a> a</b> → <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a></b> → a<br ></br>
--  <b >pure </b><b >native </b>java.lang.reflect.Array.get</span> 
--   
--   Like <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#JArray.itemAt" >JArray.itemAt</a> but the result is not wrapped in <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Maybe" >Maybe</a>. 
--   This is appropriate for arrays of primitive values. For all other arrays, the user is expected to prove that the element cannot be <span class="code" >null</span> or else risk a <span class="code" >NullPointerException</span>.  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="JArray.fold" >fold</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#ArrayElem" >ArrayElem</a> α ⇒ (β → α → β) → β → <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#ArrayOf" >ArrayOf</a> γ α</b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#ST" >ST</a> γ β</span> 
--   
--   Equivalent of <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeList.html#fold" >fold</a> for mutable arrays.   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="JArray.fromIndexList" >fromIndexList</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#ArrayElem" >ArrayElem</a> α ⇒ <b >[(<a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a>, α)]</b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeIO.html#STMutable" >STMutable</a> β (<a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#JArray" >JArray</a> α)</span> 
--   
--   Create a mutable array from a finite index/value list. 
--   Indexes not mentioned in the list remain <span class="code" >null</span> for non primitive array elements and 0 otherwise.  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="JArray.fromList" >fromList</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#ArrayElem" >ArrayElem</a> α ⇒ [α] → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeIO.html#STMutable" >STMutable</a> β (<a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#JArray" >JArray</a> α)</span> 
--   
--   Create a mutable array from a finite list.  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="JArray.fromMaybeList" >fromMaybeList</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#ArrayElem" >ArrayElem</a> α ⇒ [<a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Maybe" >Maybe</a> α] → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeIO.html#STMutable" >STMutable</a> β (<a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#JArray" >JArray</a> α)</span> 
--   
--   Create a mutable array from a finite list of <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Maybe" >Maybe</a> values.  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="JArray.genericFromIndexList" >genericFromIndexList</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeIO.html#JavaType" >JavaType</a> α ⇒ <b >[(<a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a>, α)]</b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeIO.html#STMutable" >STMutable</a> β (<a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#JArray" >JArray</a> α)</span> 
--   
--   Create a mutable generic array from a finite index/value list. 
--   Indexes not mentioned in the list remain <span class="code" >null</span> for non primitive array elements and 0 otherwise.  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="JArray.getAt" >getAt</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#ArrayOf" >ArrayOf</a> s a</b> → <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a></b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#ST" >ST</a> s (<a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Maybe" >Maybe</a> a)<br ></br>
--  <b >native </b>java.lang.reflect.Array.get</span> 
--   
--   Get the array element at a certain index of a mutable array and return it in the <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#ST" >ST</a> monad. 
--   This will throw an <span class="unknown" >IndexOutOfBoundsException</span> if the index is lower than 0 or greater or equal to the length of the array. 
--   Because in general, array elements may be <span class="code" >null</span>, the return value is wrapped in <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Maybe" >Maybe</a>, as usual.  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="JArray.getElemAt" >getElemAt</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#ArrayOf" >ArrayOf</a> s a</b> → <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a></b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#ST" >ST</a> s a<br ></br>
--  <b >native </b>java.lang.reflect.Array.get</span> 
--   
--   Get the array element at a certain index of a mutable array and return it in the <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#ST" >ST</a> monad. 
--   This will throw an <span class="unknown" >IndexOutOfBoundsException</span> if the index is lower than 0 or greater or equal to the length of the array. 
--   Unlike with <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#JArray.getAt" >JArray.getAt</a> the element <b >must not be <span class="code" >null</span></b>. 
--   This is appropriate for arrays of primitive values. For all other arrays, the user is expected to prove that the element cannot be <span class="code" >null</span> or else risk a <span class="code" >NullPointerException</span>.  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="JArray.getLength" >getLength</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#ArrayOf" >ArrayOf</a> α β</b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#ST" >ST</a> α <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a></span> 
--   
--   Return the length of a mutable array in the <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#ST" >ST</a> monad.   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="JArray.itemAt" >itemAt</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#JArray" >JArray</a> a</b> → <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a></b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Maybe" >Maybe</a> a<br ></br>
--  <b >pure </b><b >native </b>java.lang.reflect.Array.get</span> 
--   
--   Get the array element at a given index. This will throw an <span class="unknown" >IndexOutOfBoundsException</span> if the index is lower than 0 or greater or equal to the length of the array. 
--   Because in general, array elements may be <span class="code" >null</span>, the return value is wrapped in <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Maybe" >Maybe</a>, as usual.  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="JArray.length" >length</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#JArray" >JArray</a> a</b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a><br ></br>
--  <b >pure </b><b >native </b>java.lang.reflect.Array.getLength</span> 
--   
--   Tell the length of an immutable Java array. 
--   Because the length of an array cannot change, it is safe to use this function with <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeIO.html#Mutable.readonly" >Mutable.readonly</a>.  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="JArray.map" >map</a> ∷ (<a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#ArrayElem" >ArrayElem</a> α, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#ArrayElem" >ArrayElem</a> β) ⇒ (α → β) → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#JArray" >JArray</a> α → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeIO.html#STMutable" >STMutable</a> γ (<a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#JArray" >JArray</a> β)</span> 
--   
--   Map a function over the elements of an immutable array. 
--   The results will be collected in a new mutable array of the same length. 
--   If the target element type is a primitive one, no <b >null</b> elements are allowed in the source array.   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="JArray.mapElem" >mapElem</a> ∷ (<a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#ArrayElem" >ArrayElem</a> γ, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#ArrayElem" >ArrayElem</a> α) ⇒ (γ → α) → <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#JArray" >JArray</a> γ</b> → <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#ArrayOf" >ArrayOf</a> β α</b> → <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a></b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#ST" >ST</a> β <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Unit" >()</a></span> 
--   
--   Apply a function to an array element and write the result to another array at the same index. 
--   If the target array is a primitive one, there must be no null elements in the source array.  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="JArray.modify" >modify</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#ArrayElem" >ArrayElem</a> α ⇒ (α → α) → <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#ArrayOf" >ArrayOf</a> β α</b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#ST" >ST</a> β <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Unit" >()</a></span> 
--   
--   Modify a mutable array by applying a function to all its elements.   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="JArray._new" >new</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Class" >Class</a> a</b> → <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a></b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeIO.html#STMutable" >STMutable</a> s (<a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#JArray" >JArray</a> a)<br ></br>
--  <b >native </b>java.lang.reflect.Array.newInstance</span> 
--   
--   create a one dimensional Java array   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="JArray.newM" >newM</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Class" >Class</a> a</b> → <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a></b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeIO.html#STMutable" >STMutable</a> s (<a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#JArray" >JArray</a> (<a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeIO.html#Mutable" >Mutable</a> s a))<br ></br>
--  <b >native </b>java.lang.reflect.Array.newInstance</span> 
--   
--   create a one dimensional Java array that holds <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeIO.html#Mutable" >Mutable</a> data   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="JArray.setAt" >setAt</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#ArrayOf" >ArrayOf</a> s a</b> → <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a></b> → <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Maybe" >Maybe</a> a</b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#ST" >ST</a> s <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Unit" >()</a><br ></br>
--  <b >native </b>java.lang.reflect.Array.set</span> 
--   
--   Set the element at a certain index of a mutable array to a value that is wrapped in <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Maybe" >Maybe</a>. This won't work for primitive element types. 
--   This will throw an <span class="unknown" >IndexOutOfBoundsException</span> if the index is lower than 0 or greater or equal to the length of the array. 
--   To set the corresponding array element to <span class="code" >null</span>, pass <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Maybe.Nothing" >Maybe.Nothing</a>, otherwise pass a <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Maybe.Just" >Maybe.Just</a> value.  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="JArray.setElemAt" >setElemAt</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#ArrayOf" >ArrayOf</a> s a</b> → <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a></b> → <b >a</b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#ST" >ST</a> s <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Unit" >()</a><br ></br>
--  <b >native </b>java.lang.reflect.Array.set</span> 
--   
--   Set the element at a certain index of a mutable array. 
--   This will throw an <span class="unknown" >IndexOutOfBoundsException</span> if the index is lower than 0 or greater or equal to the length of the array.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#JArray
data JArray a 

-- | Create a mutable array of a given size and compute the values of its elements by some function. The function gets the current index and the already computed values in the form of an immutable array, where it can access elements with a <b >smaller</b> index than the current one. 
--   The restriction to smaller indexes is because array elements are strict in Frege. For example, we can't store unevaluated values in an <span class="code" >int[]</span> array, because the Java type of unevaluated values is not <span class="code" >int</span>. 
--   To create an array of 1000 fibonacci numbers, one could write: 
--  <pre>
--  
--   cache fib 1000 where
--     fib 0 _ = 1n
--     fib 1 _ = 1n
--     fib n a = a.[n-1] + a.[n-2]
--  </pre>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#JArray.cache
cache ∷ ArrayElem β ⇒ (Int→JArray β→β) → Int → STMutable α (JArray β)

-- | Like <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#JArray.itemAt" >JArray.itemAt</a> but the result is not wrapped in <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Maybe" >Maybe</a>. 
--   This is appropriate for arrays of primitive values. For all other arrays, the user is expected to prove that the element cannot be <span class="code" >null</span> or else risk a <span class="code" >NullPointerException</span>.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#JArray.elemAt
elemAt ∷ JArray a → Int → a 
pure native java.lang.reflect.Array.get

-- | Equivalent of <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeList.html#fold" >fold</a> for mutable arrays.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#JArray.fold
fold ∷ ArrayElem α ⇒ (β → α → β) → β → ArrayOf γ α → ST γ β

-- | Create a mutable array from a finite index/value list. 
--   Indexes not mentioned in the list remain <span class="code" >null</span> for non primitive array elements and 0 otherwise.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#JArray.fromIndexList
fromIndexList ∷ ArrayElem α ⇒ [(Int, α)] → STMutable β (JArray α)

-- | Create a mutable array from a finite list.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#JArray.fromList
fromList ∷ ArrayElem α ⇒ [α] → STMutable β (JArray α)

-- | Create a mutable array from a finite list of <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Maybe" >Maybe</a> values.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#JArray.fromMaybeList
fromMaybeList ∷ ArrayElem α ⇒ [Maybe α] → STMutable β (JArray α)

-- | Create a mutable generic array from a finite index/value list. 
--   Indexes not mentioned in the list remain <span class="code" >null</span> for non primitive array elements and 0 otherwise.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#JArray.genericFromIndexList
genericFromIndexList ∷ JavaType α ⇒ [(Int, α)] → STMutable β (JArray α)

-- | Get the array element at a certain index of a mutable array and return it in the <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#ST" >ST</a> monad. 
--   This will throw an <span class="unknown" >IndexOutOfBoundsException</span> if the index is lower than 0 or greater or equal to the length of the array. 
--   Because in general, array elements may be <span class="code" >null</span>, the return value is wrapped in <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Maybe" >Maybe</a>, as usual.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#JArray.getAt
getAt ∷ ArrayOf s a → Int → ST s (Maybe a) 
native java.lang.reflect.Array.get

-- | Get the array element at a certain index of a mutable array and return it in the <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#ST" >ST</a> monad. 
--   This will throw an <span class="unknown" >IndexOutOfBoundsException</span> if the index is lower than 0 or greater or equal to the length of the array. 
--   Unlike with <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#JArray.getAt" >JArray.getAt</a> the element <b >must not be <span class="code" >null</span></b>. 
--   This is appropriate for arrays of primitive values. For all other arrays, the user is expected to prove that the element cannot be <span class="code" >null</span> or else risk a <span class="code" >NullPointerException</span>.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#JArray.getElemAt
getElemAt ∷ ArrayOf s a → Int → ST s a 
native java.lang.reflect.Array.get

-- | Return the length of a mutable array in the <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#ST" >ST</a> monad.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#JArray.getLength
getLength ∷ ArrayOf α β → ST α Int

-- | Get the array element at a given index. This will throw an <span class="unknown" >IndexOutOfBoundsException</span> if the index is lower than 0 or greater or equal to the length of the array. 
--   Because in general, array elements may be <span class="code" >null</span>, the return value is wrapped in <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Maybe" >Maybe</a>, as usual.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#JArray.itemAt
itemAt ∷ JArray a → Int → Maybe a 
pure native java.lang.reflect.Array.get

-- | Tell the length of an immutable Java array. 
--   Because the length of an array cannot change, it is safe to use this function with <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeIO.html#Mutable.readonly" >Mutable.readonly</a>.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#JArray.length
length ∷ JArray a → Int 
pure native java.lang.reflect.Array.getLength

-- | Map a function over the elements of an immutable array. 
--   The results will be collected in a new mutable array of the same length. 
--   If the target element type is a primitive one, no <b >null</b> elements are allowed in the source array.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#JArray.map
map ∷ (ArrayElem α, ArrayElem β) ⇒ (α → β) → JArray α → STMutable γ (JArray β)

-- | Apply a function to an array element and write the result to another array at the same index. 
--   If the target array is a primitive one, there must be no null elements in the source array.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#JArray.mapElem
mapElem ∷ (ArrayElem γ, ArrayElem α) ⇒ (γ → α) → JArray γ → ArrayOf β α → Int → ST β ()

-- | Modify a mutable array by applying a function to all its elements.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#JArray.modify
modify ∷ ArrayElem α ⇒ (α → α) → ArrayOf β α → ST β ()

-- | create a one dimensional Java array
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#JArray._new
new ∷ Class a → Int → STMutable s (JArray a) 
native java.lang.reflect.Array.newInstance

-- | create a one dimensional Java array that holds <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeIO.html#Mutable" >Mutable</a> data
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#JArray.newM
newM ∷ Class a → Int → STMutable s (JArray (Mutable s a)) 
native java.lang.reflect.Array.newInstance

-- | Set the element at a certain index of a mutable array to a value that is wrapped in <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Maybe" >Maybe</a>. This won't work for primitive element types. 
--   This will throw an <span class="unknown" >IndexOutOfBoundsException</span> if the index is lower than 0 or greater or equal to the length of the array. 
--   To set the corresponding array element to <span class="code" >null</span>, pass <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Maybe.Nothing" >Maybe.Nothing</a>, otherwise pass a <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Maybe.Just" >Maybe.Just</a> value.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#JArray.setAt
setAt ∷ ArrayOf s a → Int → Maybe a → ST s () 
native java.lang.reflect.Array.set

-- | Set the element at a certain index of a mutable array. 
--   This will throw an <span class="unknown" >IndexOutOfBoundsException</span> if the index is lower than 0 or greater or equal to the length of the array.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#JArray.setElemAt
setElemAt ∷ ArrayOf s a → Int → a → ST s () 
native java.lang.reflect.Array.set

-- | Unload an immutable array to a list. 
--   The non-null elements become <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Maybe.Just" >Maybe.Just</a> values, the <span class="code" >null</span>s translate to <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Maybe.Nothing" >Maybe.Nothing</a>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#toMaybeList
toMaybeList ∷ JArray α → [Maybe α]

-- | Create an immutable array from a finite list whose elements are <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Maybe" >Maybe</a> values. 
--   Uses <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#JArray.fromMaybeList" >JArray.fromMaybeList</a> and freezes the resulting array. 
--   Note that 
--  <pre>
--  
--   arrayFromList . toList
--  </pre> 
--   does not guarantee reconstruction of the original array, because <span class="code" >null</span>s get lost, whereas 
--  <pre>
--  
--   arrayFromMaybeList . toMaybeList
--  </pre> 
--   does.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#arrayFromMaybeList
arrayFromMaybeList ∷ ArrayElem a ⇒ [Maybe a] → JArray a

-- | Create an immutable array from a finite list whose elements are 'ArrayElem` 
--   Uses <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#JArray.fromList" >JArray.fromList</a> and freezes the resulting array.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#arrayFromList
arrayFromList ∷ ArrayElem α ⇒ [α] → JArray α

-- | Create an immutable array from a finite index/value list. 
--   Uses <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#JArray.fromIndexList" >JArray.fromIndexList</a> and freezes the resulting array.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#arrayFromIndexList
arrayFromIndexList ∷ ArrayElem α ⇒ [(Int, α)] → JArray α

-- | Create an immutable generic array from a finite index/value list. 
--   Uses <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#JArray.genericFromIndexList" >JArray.genericFromIndexList</a> and freezes the resulting array.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#genericArrayFromIndexList
genericArrayFromIndexList ∷ JavaType α ⇒ [(Int, α)] → JArray α

-- | Map a function over the elements of an immutable array, and collect the results in another immutable array. 
--   Uses <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#JArray.map" >JArray.map</a> and makes result read-only.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#arrayMap
arrayMap ∷ (ArrayElem α, ArrayElem β) ⇒ (α → β) → JArray α → JArray β

-- | Left fold an immutable array
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#arrayFold
arrayFold ∷ (α → β → α) → α → JArray β → α

-- | Memoize a number of results from a function that maps <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a> to the array element. 
--   Uses <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#JArray.cache" >JArray.cache</a> and makes it immutable
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#arrayCache
arrayCache ∷ ArrayElem α ⇒ (Int→JArray α→α) → Int → JArray α

-- | Type class for basic <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#JArray" >JArray</a> operations. The <b >element type</b> must be an instance of this class to support arrays of that type. 
--   <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#ArrayElem" >ArrayElem</a> is not derivable, derive sub-class <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#ArrayElement" >ArrayElement</a> instead. 
--   The operations are mostly overloaded on return type and provide the appropriate <span class="code" >java.lang.Class</span> object when needed. 
--   This supports one dimensional arrays, though more dimensions would be possible with some extra effort. 
--   Note that <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#JArray" >JArray</a> cannot be an instance of <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#ArrayElem" >ArrayElem</a> itself, because it has no fixed <span class="code" >java.lang.Class</span> instance. <h3 > Known Instances</h3> 
--   <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#ArrayElement_String" >StringJ</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#ArrayElement__minus_gt" >-></a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#ArrayElement_l_c_r" >(,)</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#ArrayElement_l_cc_r" >(,,)</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#ArrayElement_Integer" >Integer</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#ArrayElement__lbrack_rbrack" >[]</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#PrimitiveArrayElement_Int" >Int</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#PrimitiveArrayElement_Char" >Char</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#PrimitiveArrayElement_Bool" >Bool</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#PrimitiveArrayElement_Float" >Float</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#PrimitiveArrayElement_Double" >Double</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#PrimitiveArrayElement_Long" >Long</a> <h3 > Member Functions</h3>

-- | Type class for array elements of primitive type. 
--   Not thought for public use, as all instances are pre-defined. 
--   The default implementation of <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#PrimitiveArrayElement.setAt" >PrimitiveArrayElement.setAt</a> does not support passing <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Maybe.Nothing" >Maybe.Nothing</a>, because there can be no <span class="code" >null</span> in primitive arrays. <h3 > Known Instances</h3> 
--   <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#PrimitiveArrayElement_Int" >Int</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#PrimitiveArrayElement_Char" >Char</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#PrimitiveArrayElement_Bool" >Bool</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#PrimitiveArrayElement_Float" >Float</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#PrimitiveArrayElement_Double" >Double</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#PrimitiveArrayElement_Long" >Long</a> <h3 > Member Functions</h3>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="PrimitiveArrayElement.getAt" >getAt</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#PrimitiveArrayElement" >PrimitiveArrayElement</a> a ⇒ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#ArrayOf" >ArrayOf</a> s a</b> → <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a></b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#ST" >ST</a> s (<a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Maybe" >Maybe</a> a)</span> 
--   
--   Default implementation suitable for primitive types, wraps result with <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Maybe.Just" >Maybe.Just</a>   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="PrimitiveArrayElement.itemAt" >itemAt</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#PrimitiveArrayElement" >PrimitiveArrayElement</a> a ⇒ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#JArray" >JArray</a> a → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Maybe" >Maybe</a> a</span> 
--   
--   Default implementation suitable for primitive types, wraps result with <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Maybe.Just" >Maybe.Just</a>   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="PrimitiveArrayElement.setAt" >setAt</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#PrimitiveArrayElement" >PrimitiveArrayElement</a> a ⇒ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#ArrayOf" >ArrayOf</a> s a</b> → <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a></b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Maybe" >Maybe</a> a → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#ST" >ST</a> s <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Unit" >()</a></span> 
--   
--   Default implementation suitable for primitive types. 
--   It is an error to put <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Maybe.Nothing" >Maybe.Nothing</a> in a primitive array.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#PrimitiveArrayElement
class (JavaType a, ArrayElem a) ⇒ PrimitiveArrayElement a

-- | Default implementation suitable for primitive types, wraps result with <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Maybe.Just" >Maybe.Just</a>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#PrimitiveArrayElement.getAt
getAt ∷ PrimitiveArrayElement a ⇒ ArrayOf s a → Int → ST s (Maybe a)

-- | Default implementation suitable for primitive types, wraps result with <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Maybe.Just" >Maybe.Just</a>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#PrimitiveArrayElement.itemAt
itemAt ∷ PrimitiveArrayElement a ⇒ JArray a → Int → Maybe a

-- | Default implementation suitable for primitive types. 
--   It is an error to put <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Maybe.Nothing" >Maybe.Nothing</a> in a primitive array.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#PrimitiveArrayElement.setAt
setAt ∷ PrimitiveArrayElement a ⇒ ArrayOf s a → Int → Maybe a → ST s ()

-- | <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#ArrayElement" >ArrayElement</a> is the class one derives for array elements. 
--   In addition to the base class <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#ArrayElem" >ArrayElem</a> it also supports mutable array elements.  <h3 > Known Instances</h3> 
--   <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#ArrayElement_String" >StringJ</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#ArrayElement__minus_gt" >-></a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#ArrayElement_l_c_r" >(,)</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#ArrayElement_l_cc_r" >(,,)</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#ArrayElement_Integer" >Integer</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#ArrayElement__lbrack_rbrack" >[]</a> <h3 > Member Functions</h3>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="ArrayElement.newArrayM" >newArrayM</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#ArrayElement" >ArrayElement</a> a ⇒ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a></b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeIO.html#STMutable" >STMutable</a> s (<a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#JArray" >JArray</a> (<a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeIO.html#Mutable" >Mutable</a> s a))</span> 
--   
--   Create an array of mutable items. 
--   Such an array may never be immutable itself.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#ArrayElement
class (JavaType a, ArrayElem a) ⇒ ArrayElement a

-- | Create an array of mutable items. 
--   Such an array may never be immutable itself.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeArrays#ArrayElement.newArrayM
newArrayM ∷ ArrayElement a ⇒ Int → STMutable s (JArray (Mutable s a))

--   This package provides basic definitions for the Frege language.
--   The <i >Prelude</i> packages are imported explicitly or implicitly during compilation of any other package. They define basic data structures, classes and functions.
--   The types and constructors for lists, unit type and tuple types are not defined here: They are provided programmatically by the compiler when it compiles a package with the name <span class="code" >frege.prelude.PreludeBase</span>. Nevertheless, they are considered part of the <i >Prelude</i>, thus qualified names like <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Tuple2" >(,)</a> are okay.
--   The packages are <i >implementation specific</i> insofar as the compiler may assume that certain items are defined here in a certain way. Changes may thus lead to compiler crashes or java code that will be rejected by the java compiler.
module frege.prelude.PreludeBase

-- | Unit type <h3 > Constructors</h3>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Unit.Unit" >()</a> </span> 
--   
--   Unit value
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Unit
data ()

-- | Unit value
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Unit.Unit
()

-- | 2-tuple <h3 > Constructors</h3>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Tuple2.Tuple2" >(,)</a> a   b</span> 
--   
--   2-tuple constructor
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Tuple2
data (a, b)

-- | 2-tuple constructor
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Tuple2.Tuple2
(,) a   b

-- | 3-tuple <h3 > Constructors</h3>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Tuple3.Tuple3" >(,,)</a> a   b   c</span>

--   3-tuple constructor
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Tuple3

-- | 3-tuple constructor
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Tuple3.Tuple3
(,,) a   b   c

-- | The type class <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Eq" >Eq</a> provides operators <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Eq._eq_eq" >Eq.==</a>, <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Eq._excl_eq" >Eq.!=</a> and <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Eq.hashCode" >Eq.hashCode</a>. 
--   All types whose values can be compared for equality should be instances of this class. For algebraic data types instances can be automatically derived if all components are themselves instances of <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Eq" >Eq</a>. <h3 > Known Instances</h3> 
--   <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Ord_Integer" >Integer</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Eq_Long" >Long</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Eq_Char" >Char</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Eq_Bool" >Bool</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Eq_l__r" >()</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Eq_Float" >Float</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Eq_Double" >Double</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Eq_Int" >Int</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Eq__lbrack_rbrack" >[]</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Eq_String" >StringJ</a> <h3 > Member Functions</h3>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Eq._excl_eq" >!=</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Eq" >Eq</a> eq ⇒ eq → eq → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Bool" >Bool</a><br ></br>
--  <b >infix</b>  7</span> 
--   
--   Check for inequality. The default implementation obeys the laws 
--  <pre>
--  
--   !(a != a)
--  </pre> 
--  <pre>
--  
--   (a != b) == !(a == b)
--  </pre> 
--  <pre>
--  
--   (a == b) != (a != b)
--  </pre> 
--   These laws shall also be obeyed in all implementations.   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Eq._eq_eq" >==</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Eq" >Eq</a> eq ⇒ eq → eq → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Bool" >Bool</a><br ></br>
--  <b >infix</b>  7</span> 
--   
--   Check for equality. This function is required in all instances. 
--   The basic law of philosophy 
--  <pre>
--  
--   a == a
--  </pre> 
--   shall be obeyed by all implementations.   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Eq.hashCode" >hashCode</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Eq" >Eq</a> eq ⇒ eq → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Int" >Int</a></span> 
--   
--   Compute a hash code. 
--   The following rules shall hold in all instances: 
--  <pre>
--  
--   a == b ==&gt; hashCode a == hashCode b
--  </pre> 
--  <pre>
--  
--   hashCode a != hashCode b ==&gt; a != b
--  </pre> 
--   In addition, unequal values should produce unequal hash codes more likely than not. 
--   The hash code in derived instances for algebraic data types is computed as follows: 
--  <pre>
--  
--   hashCode v = case v of
--      Con_1 f_1 ... f_k -&gt; fold mkhash 1 [1, hashCode f_1, ..., hashCode f_k ]
--      ...
--      Con_n f_1 ... f_k -&gt; fold mkhash 1 [n, hashCode f_1, ..., hashCode f_k ]
--     where mkhash a b = (31 * a) + b
--  </pre> 
--   Here, the <span class="code" >Con_i</span> with <span class="code" >i>0</span> are the constructors, and in each clause the <span class="code" >f_j</span> with <span class="code" >j >= 0</span> are bound to the fields of the constructor under consideration.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Eq
class Eq eq

-- | Check for inequality. The default implementation obeys the laws 
--  <pre>
--  
--   !(a != a)
--  </pre> 
--  <pre>
--  
--   (a != b) == !(a == b)
--  </pre> 
--  <pre>
--  
--   (a == b) != (a != b)
--  </pre> 
--   These laws shall also be obeyed in all implementations.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Eq._excl_eq
(!=) ∷  Eq eq ⇒ eq → eq → Bool 
infix  7

-- | Check for equality. This function is required in all instances. 
--   The basic law of philosophy 
--  <pre>
--  
--   a == a
--  </pre> 
--   shall be obeyed by all implementations.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Eq._eq_eq
(==) ∷  Eq eq ⇒ eq → eq → Bool 
infix  7

-- | Compute a hash code. 
--   The following rules shall hold in all instances: 
--  <pre>
--  
--   a == b ==&gt; hashCode a == hashCode b
--  </pre> 
--  <pre>
--  
--   hashCode a != hashCode b ==&gt; a != b
--  </pre> 
--   In addition, unequal values should produce unequal hash codes more likely than not. 
--   The hash code in derived instances for algebraic data types is computed as follows: 
--  <pre>
--  
--   hashCode v = case v of
--      Con_1 f_1 ... f_k -&gt; fold mkhash 1 [1, hashCode f_1, ..., hashCode f_k ]
--      ...
--      Con_n f_1 ... f_k -&gt; fold mkhash 1 [n, hashCode f_1, ..., hashCode f_k ]
--     where mkhash a b = (31 * a) + b
--  </pre> 
--   Here, the <span class="code" >Con_i</span> with <span class="code" >i>0</span> are the constructors, and in each clause the <span class="code" >f_j</span> with <span class="code" >j >= 0</span> are bound to the fields of the constructor under consideration.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Eq.hashCode
hashCode ∷ Eq eq ⇒ eq → Int

-- | Determines the constructor of a value. This is used like 
--  <pre>
--  
--  constructor arg
--  </pre> 
--   where <span class="code" >arg</span> is any frege value. 
--   Returns 0 for function types, product types and native types or the <i >constructor number</i> for constructed types. The <i >constructor number</i> is a small integer associated with every constructed value. It indicates the data constructor a value was constructed with. 
--   The compiler assigns constructor numbers starting from 0 to the constructors defined in a <span class="code" >data</span> definition in the order of their appearance. 
--   Examples 
--  <pre>
--  
--  constructor [] == 0
--  constructor (a:as) == 1
--  constructor &quot;string&quot;  == 0    // native value
--  </pre> 
--   This function is strict in its argument, i.e. 
--  <pre>
--  
--  constructor undefined == undefined
--  </pre> 
--   <b >Implementation specific:</b> This function is used in derived instances of <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Eq" >Eq</a> and <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Ord" >Ord</a>.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#constructor
constructor ∷ a → Int 
pure native frege.runtime.Runtime.constructor

-- | <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Bool" >Bool</a> values are based on Java's primitive <span class="code" >boolean</span> values. Note that <span class="code" >true</span> and <span class="code" >false</span> are literals, not constructors.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Bool
data Bool 

-- | For compatibility with Haskell, the <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#HaskellBool" >HaskellBool</a> type defines constructors <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#HaskellBool.True" >HaskellBool.True</a> and <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#HaskellBool.False" >HaskellBool.False</a>. 
--   When the identifiers <span class="code" >True</span> or <span class="code" >False</span> are used in patterns or expressions, qualified or unqualified, and name resolution detects that they resolve to <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#HaskellBool.True" >HaskellBool.True</a> or <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#HaskellBool.False" >HaskellBool.False</a> they will be replaced by literals <span class="code" >true</span> or <span class="code" >false</span>. 
--   This is, of course, a hack, but I see no other way to bridge the gap between redefinable constructor ids and literals. For example, we couldn't simply define <span class="code" >True</span> as another literal keyword, because some Haskell code might use <span class="code" >Prelude.True</span> or could have code like. 
--  <pre>
--  
--   import Prelude hiding(True, False)
--   data TriBool = False | Perhaps | True
--  </pre> <h3 > Constructors</h3>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="HaskellBool.False" >False</a> </span> 
--   
--   will be replaced by literal <span class="code" >false</span>   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="HaskellBool.True" >True</a> </span> 
--   
--   will be replaced by literal <span class="code" >true</span>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#HaskellBool
data HaskellBool

-- | will be replaced by literal <span class="code" >false</span>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#HaskellBool.False
False

-- | will be replaced by literal <span class="code" >true</span>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#HaskellBool.True
True

-- | This is a constant with the value <span class="code" >true</span>. It is most often used as the last alternative in pattern guards: 
--  <pre>
--  
--   foo n | n &gt;= 0    = ...
--         | otherwise = ...
--  </pre>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#otherwise
otherwise ∷ Bool

-- | warning: will soon be replaced with bool This is used by code generation when a conditional expression appears in a lazy context, i.e. 
--  <pre>
--  
--   (42, if foo then bar else baz)
--  </pre> 
--   <span class="code" >lazyif a b c</span> evaluates to <span class="code" >b</span> if <span class="code" >a</span> is <span class="code" >true</span>, otherwise to <span class="code" >c</span>.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#lazyif
lazyif ∷ Bool → α → α → α

-- | This is used by code generation when a conditional expression appears in a lazy context, i.e. 
--  <pre>
--  
--   (42, if foo then bar else baz)
--  </pre> 
--   <span class="code" >bool a b c</span> evaluates to <span class="code" >a</span> if <span class="code" >c</span> is <span class="code" >true</span>, otherwise to <span class="code" >b</span>.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#bool
bool ∷ α → α → Bool → α

-- | <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Int" >Int</a> values are based on Java's primitive <span class="code" >int</span> values. 
--   The existence of this type is assumed in numerous places in the compiler. 
--   Like with all <span class="code" >native</span> Java types, be they primitive or reference types, Frege holds the raw <span class="code" >int</span> in boxed form. However, in certain cases the compiler will optimize the boxing away: <ul > <li > Strict variables or function arguments work with the unboxed value directly. </li> <li > Functions with a <span class="code" >native</span> return type generally return the unboxed value. Polymorphic data structures or functions always work with boxed values. Thus, for example, the function</li> </ul> 
--  <pre>
--  
--   sum a b c = a + b + c
--  </pre> 
--   can compute the sum of 3 <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Int" >Int</a>s, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Long" >Long</a>s, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Double" >Double</a>s or any other values of a type that is an instance of type class <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Num" >Num</a>, but it may be somewhat slower than functions specialized for a given type. 
--   According to the Java Language Specification, <span class="code" >int</span> values are 32 bit wide signed two's complement integers (§4.2). Java operations on <span class="code" >int</span> do not indicate overflow or underflow in any way (§4.2.2). Instead, just the low 32 bits of every result are retained. <h3 > Member Functions</h3>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Int._dot_amp_dot" >.&.</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Int" >Int</a></b> → <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Int" >Int</a></b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Int" >Int</a><br ></br>
--  <b >pure </b><b >native </b>&<br ></br>
--  <b >infixl</b>  11</span> 
--   
--   Computes binary /and/ of two integers. Uses the java <span class="code" >&</span>-operator.   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Int._dot_caret_dot" >.^.</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Int" >Int</a></b> → <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Int" >Int</a></b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Int" >Int</a><br ></br>
--  <b >pure </b><b >native </b>^<br ></br>
--  <b >infixl</b>  10</span> 
--   
--   Computes binary /exclusive or/ of two integers. Uses the java <span class="code" >^</span>-operator.   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Int._dot_bar_dot" >.|.</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Int" >Int</a></b> → <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Int" >Int</a></b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Int" >Int</a><br ></br>
--  <b >pure </b><b >native </b>|<br ></br>
--  <b >infixl</b>  10</span> 
--   
--   Computes binary /or/ of two integers. Uses the java <span class="code" >|</span>-operator.   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Int._char" >char</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Int" >Int</a></b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Char" >Char</a><br ></br>
--  <b >pure </b><b >native </b>(char)</span> 
--   
--   <span class="code" >i.char</span> returns the <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Char" >Char</a> value whose ordinal number is <span class="code" >i</span> 
--   Result is only valid for integers in the range 0..65535   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Int.complement" >complement</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Int" >Int</a></b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Int" >Int</a><br ></br>
--  <b >pure </b><b >native </b>~</span> 
--    
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Int._double" >double</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Int" >Int</a></b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Double" >Double</a><br ></br>
--  <b >pure </b><b >native </b>java.lang.Double.valueOf</span> 
--   
--   convert an <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Int" >Int</a> to a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Double" >Double</a>, i.e. <span class="code" >2.double == 2.0</span>.   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Int._float" >float</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Int" >Int</a></b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Float" >Float</a><br ></br>
--  <b >pure </b><b >native </b>java.lang.Float.valueOf</span> 
--   
--   convert an <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Int" >Int</a> to a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Float" >Float</a>, i.e. <span class="code" >2.float == 2.0f</span>. 
--   For large integers, the result may have been be rounded.   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Int._long" >long</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Int" >Int</a></b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Long" >Long</a><br ></br>
--  <b >pure </b><b >native </b>java.lang.Long.valueOf</span> 
--

-- | construction from a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Long" >Long</a>, see also <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#StringJ.aton" >StringJ.aton</a> and <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#StringJ.integer" >StringJ.integer</a>
