-- | This is the standard undefined value.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#undefined
undefined ∷ u

-- | Construct an undefined value with an informative message. 
--   When evaluated, an <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Undefined" >Undefined</a> exception will be thrown.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#error
error ∷ String → u

-- | Constructs an undefined value from a java exception and throws it.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#_throw
throw ∷ Throwable → α

-- | The Java <span class="code" >!</span> operator on booleans
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#_excl
(!) ∷  Bool → Bool 
pure native !

-- | The Java <span class="code" >&&</span> operator on booleans. Note that since this is a native function, the second argument appears strict to the compiler when in fact it is lazy at the Java level. This can lead to inconsistent results in some cases. For example, the following program correctly prints <span class="code" >false</span> in the first line of the output, but then aborts: 
--  <pre>
--  
--   main _ = do
--      stdout &lt;&lt; (false &amp;&amp; undefined) &lt;&lt; &quot;\n&quot;
--      stdout &lt;&lt; conj false undefined &lt;&lt; &quot;\n&quot;
--    where
--      conj a b = a &amp;&amp; b
--  </pre> 
--   Note that the very same behaviour is seen in the following java program 
--  <pre>
--  
--   public class And {
--      static boolean undef() {
--          if (true) throw new Error(&quot;undefined&quot;);
--          return false;
--      }
--      static boolean conj(boolean a, boolean b) { return a&amp;&amp;b; }
--      public static void main(String[] args) {
--          System.out.println(false &amp;&amp; undef());
--          System.out.println(conj(false, undef()));
--      }
--   }
--  </pre> 
--   One could thus say that <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#_amp_amp" >&&</a> behaves exactly like the Java operator including the fact that it cannot be replaced by a function without changing the semantics of a program. 
--   For an alternative see <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#und" >und</a>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#_amp_amp
(&&) ∷  Bool → Bool → Bool 
pure native && 
infixr  6

-- | The Java <span class="code" >||</span> operator on booleans. 
--   Note that since this is a native function, the second argument appears strict to the compiler when in fact it is lazy at the Java level. 
--   This can lead to inconsistent results in cases where the wrong strictness of the second argument propagates to arguments of the function that contains an application of <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#_bar_bar" >||</a>. (The documentation for <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#_amp_amp" >&&</a> has an example.) 
--   See <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#oder" >oder</a> for an alternative
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#_bar_bar
(||) ∷  Bool → Bool → Bool 
pure native || 
infixr  5

-- | Like <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#_amp_amp" >&&</a>, but second argument is lazy. The <span class="code" >`und`</span> operator has the same precedence and arity as <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#_amp_amp" >&&</a>. The definition is 
--  <pre>
--  
--   a `und` b = if a then b     else false
--  </pre> 
--   This should really be named <i >and</i>, but Haskell 2010 uses this already for lists. Hence we use the german word <i >und</i>.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#und
und ∷ Bool → Bool → Bool 
infixr  6

-- | Like <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#_bar_bar" >||</a>, but second argument is lazy. The <span class="code" >`oder`</span> operator has the same precedence and arity as <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#_bar_bar" >||</a>. The definition is 
--  <pre>
--  
--   a `oder`  b = if a then true  else b
--  </pre> 
--   This should really be named <i >or</i>, but Haskell 2010 uses this already for lists. Hence we use the german word <i >oder</i>.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#oder
oder ∷ Bool → Bool → Bool 
infixr  5

-- | <span class="code" >not b</span> is true if <i >b</i> is false, otherwise true. Uses java's <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#_excl" >!</a> operator.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#not
not ∷ Bool → Bool 
pure native !

-- | <span class="code" >a ^^ b</span> is true if either <i >a</i> or <i >b</i> is true, but not both. 
--  <pre>
--  
--   a ^^ b = if a then not b else b
--  </pre>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#_caret_caret
(^^) ∷  Bool → Bool → Bool 
infixr  5

-- | This checks for object identity or equality of primitive values using Java's <span class="code" >==</span> operator. It evaluates its arguments, so undefined values cannot be compared.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#_eq_eq_eq
(===) ∷  a → a → Bool 
pure native == 
infix  7

-- | This checks for object identity or inequality of primitive values using Java's <span class="code" >!=</span> operator. It evaluates its arguments, so undefined values cannot be compared.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#_excl_eq_eq
(!==) ∷  a → a → Bool 
pure native != 
infix  7

-- | <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Ordering" >Ordering</a> encodes the results of comparisons, see also <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Ord._lt_eq_gt" >Ord.<=></a>  <h3 > Constructors</h3>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Ordering.Eq" >Eq</a> </span> 
--    
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Ordering.Gt" >Gt</a> </span> 
--    
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Ordering.Lt" >Lt</a> </span>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Ordering
data Ordering

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Ordering.Eq
Eq

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Ordering.Gt
Gt

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Ordering.Lt
Lt

-- | The <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Ord" >Ord</a> class provides relational operators as well as the functions <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Ord.max" >Ord.max</a> and <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Ord.min" >Ord.min</a>. The default implementation defines them all in terms of the <i >compare</i> operator <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Ord._lt_eq_gt" >Ord.<=></a>. 
--   Making some type an instance of <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Ord" >Ord</a> makes it automatically an instance of <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Eq" >Eq</a> if it is not one already and if it has an implementation for <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Eq.hashCode" >Eq.hashCode</a>. The operators <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Eq._eq_eq" >Eq.==</a> and <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Eq._excl_eq" >Eq.!=</a> will be defined in terms of <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Ord._lt_eq_gt" >Ord.<=></a>. 
--   Instances of <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Ord" >Ord</a> can be derived automatically for algebraic data types when all elements of the type are themselves instances of <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Ord" >Ord</a> and when the type is an instance of <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Eq" >Eq</a>. <h3 > Known Instances</h3> 
--   <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Ord_Integer" >Integer</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Ord_Char" >Char</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Ord_Bool" >Bool</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Ord_Float" >Float</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Ord_Double" >Double</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Ord_Int" >Int</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Ord_String" >StringJ</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Ord_Long" >Long</a> <h3 > Member Functions</h3>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Ord._excl_eq" >!=</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Ord" >Ord</a> ord ⇒ ord → ord → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Bool" >Bool</a><br ></br>
--  <b >infix</b>  7</span> 
--   
--   This implementation for the (<a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Eq._excl_eq" >Eq.!=</a>) operator is being used in instances of <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Ord" >Ord</a> when the instantiated type is not already an instance of <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Eq" >Eq</a>.  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Ord._lt" ><</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Ord" >Ord</a> ord ⇒ ord → ord → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Bool" >Bool</a><br ></br>
--  <b >infix</b>  9</span> 
--   
--   Relational <span class="code" ><</span> operator. Obeys the following laws: 
--  <pre>
--  
--   if a &lt; b &amp;&amp; b &lt; c then a &lt; c
--   a &lt; b == b &gt; a
--  </pre>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Ord._lt_eq" ><=</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Ord" >Ord</a> ord ⇒ ord → ord → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Bool" >Bool</a><br ></br>
--  <b >infix</b>  9</span> 
--   
--   Relational <span class="code" ><=</span> operator. Obeys the following laws: 
--  <pre>
--  
--   if a &lt;= b &amp;&amp; b &lt;= c then a &lt;= c
--   a &lt;= b == b &gt;= a
--   a &lt;= b == !(a &gt; b)
--  </pre>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Ord._lt_eq_gt" ><=></a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Ord" >Ord</a> ord ⇒ ord → ord → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Ordering" >Ordering</a><br ></br>
--  <b >infix</b>  8</span> 
--   
--   This operator must be defined in all instances. It compares its operands and returns <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Ordering.Lt" >Ordering.Lt</a> if the first is lower than the second, <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Ordering.Gt" >Ordering.Gt</a> if the first is greater than the second and <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Ordering.Eq" >Ordering.Eq</a> otherwise. 
--   The following shall be invariantly true: 
--  <pre>
--  
--   case a &lt;=&gt; b of { Eq -&gt; a == b; _ -&gt; a != b }
--  </pre>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Ord._eq_eq" >==</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Ord" >Ord</a> ord ⇒ ord → ord → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Bool" >Bool</a><br ></br>
--  <b >infix</b>  7</span> 
--   
--   This implementation for the (<a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Eq._eq_eq" >Eq.==</a>) operator is being used in instances of <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Ord" >Ord</a> when the instantiated type is not already an instance of <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Eq" >Eq</a>.  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Ord._gt" >></a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Ord" >Ord</a> ord ⇒ ord → ord → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Bool" >Bool</a><br ></br>
--  <b >infix</b>  9</span> 
--   
--   Relational <span class="code" >></span> operator. Obeys the following laws: 
--  <pre>
--  
--   if a &gt; b &amp;&amp; b &gt; c then a &gt; c
--   a &gt; b == b &lt; a
--  </pre>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Ord._gt_eq" >>=</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Ord" >Ord</a> ord ⇒ ord → ord → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Bool" >Bool</a><br ></br>
--  <b >infix</b>  9</span> 
--   
--   Relational <span class="code" >>=</span> operator. Obeys the following laws: 
--  <pre>
--  
--   if a &gt;= b &amp;&amp; b &gt;= c then a &gt;= c
--   a &gt;= b == b &lt;= a
--   a &gt;= b == !(a &lt; b)
--  </pre>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Ord.compare" >compare</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Ord" >Ord</a> ord ⇒ ord → ord → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Ordering" >Ordering</a><br ></br>
--  <b >infix</b>  8</span> 
--    
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Ord.max" >max</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Ord" >Ord</a> ord ⇒ ord → ord → ord</span> 
--   
--  <pre>
--  
--   max a b = if a &gt; b then a else b   
--  </pre>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Ord.min" >min</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Ord" >Ord</a> ord ⇒ ord → ord → ord</span> 
--   
--  <pre>
--  
--   min a b = if a &lt; b then a else b   
--  </pre>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Ord
class Eq ord ⇒ Ord ord

-- | This implementation for the (<a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Eq._excl_eq" >Eq.!=</a>) operator is being used in instances of <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Ord" >Ord</a> when the instantiated type is not already an instance of <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Eq" >Eq</a>.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Ord._excl_eq
(!=) ∷  Ord ord ⇒ ord → ord → Bool 
infix  7

-- | Relational <span class="code" ><</span> operator. Obeys the following laws: 
--  <pre>
--  
--   if a &lt; b &amp;&amp; b &lt; c then a &lt; c
--   a &lt; b == b &gt; a
--  </pre>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Ord._lt
(<) ∷  Ord ord ⇒ ord → ord → Bool 
infix  9

-- | Relational <span class="code" ><=</span> operator. Obeys the following laws: 
--  <pre>
--  
--   if a &lt;= b &amp;&amp; b &lt;= c then a &lt;= c
--   a &lt;= b == b &gt;= a
--   a &lt;= b == !(a &gt; b)
--  </pre>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Ord._lt_eq
(<=) ∷  Ord ord ⇒ ord → ord → Bool 
infix  9

-- | This operator must be defined in all instances. It compares its operands and returns <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Ordering.Lt" >Ordering.Lt</a> if the first is lower than the second, <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Ordering.Gt" >Ordering.Gt</a> if the first is greater than the second and <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Ordering.Eq" >Ordering.Eq</a> otherwise. 
--   The following shall be invariantly true: 
--  <pre>
--  
--   case a &lt;=&gt; b of { Eq -&gt; a == b; _ -&gt; a != b }
--  </pre>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Ord._lt_eq_gt
(<=>) ∷  Ord ord ⇒ ord → ord → Ordering 
infix  8

-- | This implementation for the (<a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Eq._eq_eq" >Eq.==</a>) operator is being used in instances of <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Ord" >Ord</a> when the instantiated type is not already an instance of <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Eq" >Eq</a>.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Ord._eq_eq
(==) ∷  Ord ord ⇒ ord → ord → Bool 
infix  7

-- | Relational <span class="code" >></span> operator. Obeys the following laws: 
--  <pre>
--  
--   if a &gt; b &amp;&amp; b &gt; c then a &gt; c
--   a &gt; b == b &lt; a
--  </pre>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Ord._gt
(>) ∷  Ord ord ⇒ ord → ord → Bool 
infix  9

-- | Relational <span class="code" >>=</span> operator. Obeys the following laws: 
--  <pre>
--  
--   if a &gt;= b &amp;&amp; b &gt;= c then a &gt;= c
--   a &gt;= b == b &lt;= a
--   a &gt;= b == !(a &lt; b)
--  </pre>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Ord._gt_eq
(>=) ∷  Ord ord ⇒ ord → ord → Bool 
infix  9

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Ord.compare
compare ∷ Ord ord ⇒ ord → ord → Ordering 
infix  8

-- | <pre>
--  
--   max a b = if a &gt; b then a else b   
--  </pre>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Ord.max
max ∷ Ord ord ⇒ ord → ord → ord

-- | <pre>
--  
--   min a b = if a &lt; b then a else b   
--  </pre>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Ord.min
min ∷ Ord ord ⇒ ord → ord → ord

-- | Class <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Enum" >Enum</a> defines operations on sequentially ordered types. 
--   A type that is an instance of <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Enum" >Enum</a> is also an instance of <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Ord" >Ord</a> (and, in turn, of <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Eq" >Eq</a>). 
--   Instances of <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Enum" >Enum</a> may be derived for any enumeration type (types whose constructors have no fields). If there is no <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Eq.hashCode" >Eq.hashCode</a> provided, it will be the same as <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Enum.ord" >Enum.ord</a>. 
--   Enumeration types have special syntactic support with the range list: 
--  <pre>
--  
--   [a .. b]
--   [a ..]
--   [a,b .. c]
--   [a,b ..]
--  </pre> <h3 > Known Instances</h3> 
--   <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Enum_Int" >Int</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Enum_Bool" >Bool</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Enum_Char" >Char</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Enum_Integer" >Integer</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Enum_Long" >Long</a> <h3 > Member Functions</h3>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Enum._lt_eq_gt" ><=></a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Enum" >Enum</a> e ⇒ e → e → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Ordering" >Ordering</a><br ></br>
--  <b >infix</b>  8</span> 
--   
--   This is the default implementation of the compare operator, that makes each <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Enum" >Enum</a> type an <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Ord" >Ord</a> type automatically. 
--  <pre>
--  
--   a &lt;=&gt; b  =  (ord a).&lt;=&gt;  (ord b)
--  </pre>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Enum.enumFrom" >enumFrom</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Enum" >Enum</a> e ⇒ e → [e]</span> 
--   
--   used in translating @[n..]   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Enum.enumFromThen" >enumFromThen</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Enum" >Enum</a> e ⇒ e → e → [e]</span> 
--   
--   used in translating @[n,n'..]   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Enum.enumFromThenTo" >enumFromThenTo</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Enum" >Enum</a> e ⇒ e → e → e → [e]</span> 
--   
--   used in translating @[n,n'..m]   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Enum.enumFromTo" >enumFromTo</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Enum" >Enum</a> e ⇒ e → e → [e]</span> 
--   
--   used in translating @[n..m]   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Enum.from" >from</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Enum" >Enum</a> e ⇒ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Int" >Int</a> → e</span> 
--   
--   <span class="code" >T.from i</span> maps the <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Int" >Int</a> value <span class="code" >i</span> to a value of <span class="code" >T</span>, such that 
--  <pre>
--  
--     ord (T.from i) == i
--  </pre> 
--   unless there is no value <span class="code" >e</span> of <span class="code" >T</span> so that <span class="code" >ord e == i</span>. In the latter case, the result is <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#undefined" >undefined</a>.  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Enum.hashCode" >hashCode</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Enum" >Enum</a> e ⇒ e → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Int" >Int</a></span> 
--   
--   default implementation for <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Eq.hashCode" >Eq.hashCode</a> is same as <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Enum.ord" >Enum.ord</a>   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Enum.ord" >ord</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Enum" >Enum</a> e ⇒ e → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Int" >Int</a></span> 
--   
--   <span class="code" >ord e</span> returns the ordinal number associated with the value <span class="code" >e</span>. For enumeration types, <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Enum.ord" >Enum.ord</a> is the same as <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#constructor" >constructor</a>, for <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Int" >Int</a>, it is the identity function. Some types, like <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Long" >Long</a>, cannot map all their values to <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Int" >Int</a>, in such cases the result of applying <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Enum.ord" >Enum.ord</a> may be meaningless.  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Enum.pred" >pred</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Enum" >Enum</a> e ⇒ e → e</span> 
--   
--   <span class="code" >pred e</span> is the predecessor of <span class="code" >e</span> or <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#undefined" >undefined</a> if there is no predecessor.   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Enum.succ" >succ</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Enum" >Enum</a> e ⇒ e → e</span> 
--   
--   <span class="code" >succ e</span> is the successor of <span class="code" >e</span> or <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#undefined" >undefined</a> if there is no such successor.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Enum
class (Eq e, Ord e) ⇒ Enum e

-- | This is the default implementation of the compare operator, that makes each <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Enum" >Enum</a> type an <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Ord" >Ord</a> type automatically. 
--  <pre>
--  
--   a &lt;=&gt; b  =  (ord a).&lt;=&gt;  (ord b)
--  </pre>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Enum._lt_eq_gt
(<=>) ∷  Enum e ⇒ e → e → Ordering 
infix  8

-- | used in translating @[n..]
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Enum.enumFrom
enumFrom ∷ Enum e ⇒ e → [e]

-- | used in translating @[n,n'..]
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Enum.enumFromThen
enumFromThen ∷ Enum e ⇒ e → e → [e]

-- | used in translating @[n,n'..m]
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Enum.enumFromThenTo
enumFromThenTo ∷ Enum e ⇒ e → e → e → [e]

-- | used in translating @[n..m]
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Enum.enumFromTo
enumFromTo ∷ Enum e ⇒ e → e → [e]

-- | <span class="code" >T.from i</span> maps the <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Int" >Int</a> value <span class="code" >i</span> to a value of <span class="code" >T</span>, such that 
--  <pre>
--  
--     ord (T.from i) == i
--  </pre> 
--   unless there is no value <span class="code" >e</span> of <span class="code" >T</span> so that <span class="code" >ord e == i</span>. In the latter case, the result is <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#undefined" >undefined</a>.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Enum.from
from ∷ Enum e ⇒ Int → e

-- | default implementation for <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Eq.hashCode" >Eq.hashCode</a> is same as <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Enum.ord" >Enum.ord</a>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Enum.hashCode
hashCode ∷ Enum e ⇒ e → Int

-- | <span class="code" >ord e</span> returns the ordinal number associated with the value <span class="code" >e</span>. For enumeration types, <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Enum.ord" >Enum.ord</a> is the same as <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#constructor" >constructor</a>, for <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Int" >Int</a>, it is the identity function. Some types, like <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Long" >Long</a>, cannot map all their values to <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Int" >Int</a>, in such cases the result of applying <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Enum.ord" >Enum.ord</a> may be meaningless.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Enum.ord
ord ∷ Enum e ⇒ e → Int

-- | <span class="code" >pred e</span> is the predecessor of <span class="code" >e</span> or <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#undefined" >undefined</a> if there is no predecessor.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Enum.pred
pred ∷ Enum e ⇒ e → e

-- | <span class="code" >succ e</span> is the successor of <span class="code" >e</span> or <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#undefined" >undefined</a> if there is no such successor.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Enum.succ
succ ∷ Enum e ⇒ e → e

-- | The <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Num" >Num</a> class provides the operators (<a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Num._plus" >Num.+</a>), (<a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Num._minus" >Num.-</a>) and (<a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Num._star" >Num.*</a>) as well as some functions that are common for all numeric types. <h3 > Known Instances</h3> 
--   <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Integral_Integer" >Integer</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Real_Float" >Float</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Real_Double" >Double</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Num_Int" >Int</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Num_Long" >Long</a> <h3 > Member Functions</h3>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Num._star" >*</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Num" >Num</a> n ⇒ n → n → n<br ></br>
--  <b >infixl</b>  14</span> 
--   
--   Computes the product of two numbers   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Num._plus" >+</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Num" >Num</a> n ⇒ n → n → n<br ></br>
--  <b >infixl</b>  13</span> 
--   
--   Computes the sum of two numbers   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Num._minus" >-</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Num" >Num</a> n ⇒ n → n → n<br ></br>
--  <b >infixl</b>  13</span> 
--   
--   Computes the difference of two numbers   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Num.abs" >abs</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Num" >Num</a> n ⇒ n → n</span> 
--   
--   Computes the absolute value   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Num.fromInt" >fromInt</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Num" >Num</a> n ⇒ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Int" >Int</a> → n</span> 
--   
--   converts an <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Int" >Int</a> value to the instantiated type   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Num.fromInteger" >fromInteger</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Num" >Num</a> n ⇒ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Integer" >Integer</a> → n</span> 
--   
--   converts an <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Integer" >Integer</a> value to the instantiated type   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Num.isInfinite" >isInfinite</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Num" >Num</a> n ⇒ n → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Bool" >Bool</a></span> 
--   
--   Floating point number types may have special values for <i >infinity</i> and <i >negative infinity</i>. <span class="code" >isFinite n</span> yields <span class="code" >true</span> if <span class="code" >n</span> is an infinite value and <span class="code" >false</span> in all other cases. 
--   The default implementation always returns <span class="code" >false</span> so that implementors of instances for types without special values for infinity need not care. 
--   See also <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Num.isNumber" >Num.isNumber</a>.  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Num.isNaN" >isNaN</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Num" >Num</a> n ⇒ n → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Bool" >Bool</a></span> 
--   
--   Floating point number types may have a special values for <i >not a number</i> (NaN). For example, <span class="code" >0d / 0d</span> is NaN. <span class="code" >isNaN n</span> yields <span class="code" >true</span> if <span class="code" >n</span> is the special value that indicates that <span class="code" >n</span> is not a number and <span class="code" >false</span> in all other cases. 
--   The default implementation always returns <span class="code" >false</span> so that implementors of instances for types without such a special values need not care. 
--   See also <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Num.isNumber" >Num.isNumber</a>.  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Num.isNumber" >isNumber</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Num" >Num</a> n ⇒ n → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Bool" >Bool</a></span> 
--   
--   Returns <span class="code" >true</span> if <span class="code" >n</span> is neither infinite (see <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Num.isInfinite" >Num.isInfinite</a>) nor NaN (see <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Num.isNaN" >Num.isNaN</a>). 
--   Note that certain properties for functions on numbers are true only under the assumption that the argument values are numbers. 
--   The default implementation is 
--  <pre>
--  
--   isNumber n = !(isInfinite n) &amp;&amp; !(isNaN n)
--  </pre> 
--   so that the function should always compute the right answer as long as <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Num.isInfinite" >Num.isInfinite</a> and <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Num.isNaN" >Num.isNaN</a> do.  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Num.negate" >negate</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Num" >Num</a> n ⇒ n → n</span> 
--   
--   Negates a number n such that if n is a number 
--  <pre>
--  
--   n + negate n == 0   
--  </pre>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Num.one" >one</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Num" >Num</a> n ⇒ n</span> 
--   
--   the number 1 in the instantiated type   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Num.sign" >sign</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Num" >Num</a> n ⇒ n → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Int" >Int</a></span> 
--   
--   <span class="code" >sign n</span> is -1 if n<0, 1 if n>0 and 0 otherwise   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Num.subtract" >subtract</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Num" >Num</a> n ⇒ n → n → n</span> 
--   
--   use <span class="code" >(subtract a)</span> instead of <span class="code" >\\b -> b-a</span> in sections   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Num.zero" >zero</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Num" >Num</a> n ⇒ n</span> 
--   
--   the number 0 in the instantiated type
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Num
class (Eq n, Ord n) ⇒ Num n

-- | Computes the product of two numbers
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Num._star
(*) ∷  Num n ⇒ n → n → n 
infixl  14

-- | Computes the sum of two numbers
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Num._plus
(+) ∷  Num n ⇒ n → n → n 
infixl  13

-- | Computes the difference of two numbers
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Num._minus
(-) ∷  Num n ⇒ n → n → n 
infixl  13

-- | Computes the absolute value
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Num.abs
abs ∷ Num n ⇒ n → n

-- | converts an <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Int" >Int</a> value to the instantiated type
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Num.fromInt
fromInt ∷ Num n ⇒ Int → n

-- | converts an <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Integer" >Integer</a> value to the instantiated type
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Num.fromInteger
fromInteger ∷ Num n ⇒ Integer → n

-- | Floating point number types may have special values for <i >infinity</i> and <i >negative infinity</i>. <span class="code" >isFinite n</span> yields <span class="code" >true</span> if <span class="code" >n</span> is an infinite value and <span class="code" >false</span> in all other cases. 
--   The default implementation always returns <span class="code" >false</span> so that implementors of instances for types without special values for infinity need not care. 
--   See also <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Num.isNumber" >Num.isNumber</a>.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Num.isInfinite
isInfinite ∷ Num n ⇒ n → Bool

-- | Floating point number types may have a special values for <i >not a number</i> (NaN). For example, <span class="code" >0d / 0d</span> is NaN. <span class="code" >isNaN n</span> yields <span class="code" >true</span> if <span class="code" >n</span> is the special value that indicates that <span class="code" >n</span> is not a number and <span class="code" >false</span> in all other cases. 
--   The default implementation always returns <span class="code" >false</span> so that implementors of instances for types without such a special values need not care. 
--   See also <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Num.isNumber" >Num.isNumber</a>.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Num.isNaN
isNaN ∷ Num n ⇒ n → Bool

-- | Returns <span class="code" >true</span> if <span class="code" >n</span> is neither infinite (see <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Num.isInfinite" >Num.isInfinite</a>) nor NaN (see <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Num.isNaN" >Num.isNaN</a>). 
--   Note that certain properties for functions on numbers are true only under the assumption that the argument values are numbers. 
--   The default implementation is 
--  <pre>
--  
--   isNumber n = !(isInfinite n) &amp;&amp; !(isNaN n)
--  </pre> 
--   so that the function should always compute the right answer as long as <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Num.isInfinite" >Num.isInfinite</a> and <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Num.isNaN" >Num.isNaN</a> do.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Num.isNumber
isNumber ∷ Num n ⇒ n → Bool

-- | Negates a number n such that if n is a number 
--  <pre>
--  
--   n + negate n == 0   
--  </pre>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Num.negate
negate ∷ Num n ⇒ n → n

-- | the number 1 in the instantiated type
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Num.one
one ∷ Num n ⇒ n

-- | <span class="code" >sign n</span> is -1 if n<0, 1 if n>0 and 0 otherwise
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Num.sign
sign ∷ Num n ⇒ n → Int

-- | use <span class="code" >(subtract a)</span> instead of <span class="code" >\\b -> b-a</span> in sections
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Num.subtract
subtract ∷ Num n ⇒ n → n → n

-- | the number 0 in the instantiated type
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Num.zero
zero ∷ Num n ⇒ n

-- | The <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Real" >Real</a> class provides the division operator (<a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Real._div" >Real./</a>). <h3 > Known Instances</h3>

--   the division operator

--   convert a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Double" >Double</a> to any <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Real" >Real</a> value

--   <span class="code" > x ^ n </span> raise <i >x</i> to the <i >n</i>-th power

--   every <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Num" >Num</a> can be made from an <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Integral" >Integral</a>   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Integral.gcd" >gcd</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Integral" >Integral</a> integ ⇒ integ → integ → integ</span> 
--   
--   <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Integral.gcd" >Integral.gcd</a> <span class="code" >x y</span> is the non-negative factor of both <span class="code" >x</span> and <span class="code" >y</span> of which every common factor of <span class="code" >x</span> and <span class="code" >y</span> is also a factor; for example <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Integral.gcd" >Integral.gcd</a> <span class="code" >4 2 = 2</span>, <span class="code" ><a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Integral.gcd" >Integral.gcd</a> (-4) 6 = 2</span>, <span class="code" ><a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Integral.gcd" >Integral.gcd</a> 0 4</span> = <span class="code" >4</span>. <span class="code" ><a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Integral.gcd" >Integral.gcd</a> 0 0</span> = <span class="code" >0</span>. (That is, the common divisor that is \"greatest\" in the divisibility preordering.) 
--   Note: Since for signed fixed-width integer types, <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Num.abs" >Num.abs</a> <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Bounded.minBound" >Bounded.minBound</a> < <span class="code" >0</span>, the result may be negative if one of the arguments is <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Bounded.minBound" >Bounded.minBound</a> (and necessarily is if the other is <span class="code" >0</span> or <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Bounded.minBound" >Bounded.minBound</a>) for such types.  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Integral.gcdHelper" >gcdHelper</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Integral" >Integral</a> integ ⇒ <b >integ</b> → <b >integ</b> → integ</span> 
--   
--   worker function for <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Integral.gcd" >Integral.gcd</a>, needs not pollute the namespace   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Integral.lcm" >lcm</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Integral" >Integral</a> integ ⇒ integ → integ → integ</span> 
--   
--   <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Integral.lcm" >Integral.lcm</a> <span class="code" >x y</span> is the smallest positive integer that both <span class="code" >x</span> and <span class="code" >y</span> divide.   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Integral.mod" >mod</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Integral" >Integral</a> integ ⇒ integ → integ → integ<br ></br>
--  <b >infixl</b>  14</span> 
--   
--   This modulo operator works so that 
--  <pre>
--  
--   forAll arbitrary (\a -&gt; forAll arbitrary (\b -&gt; (a `div` b) * b + (a `mod` b) = a))
--  </pre> 
--   In addition, it is the case that 
--  <pre>
--  
--   forAll arbitrary (\a -&gt; forAll arbitrary (\b -&gt; @(a `quot` b) == (a `div` b) || (a `quot` b) == (a `div` b)-1))   
--  </pre>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Integral.odd" >odd</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Integral" >Integral</a> integ ⇒ integ → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Bool" >Bool</a></span> 
--    
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Integral.powf" >powf</a> ∷ (<a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Integral" >Integral</a> integ, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Num" >Num</a> a) ⇒ a → integ → a</span> 
--   
--   helper for <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Integral._caret" >Integral.^</a>   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Integral.powg" >powg</a> ∷ (<a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Integral" >Integral</a> integ, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Num" >Num</a> a) ⇒ a → integ → a → a</span> 
--   
--   helper for <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Integral._caret" >Integral.^</a>   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Integral.quot" >quot</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Integral" >Integral</a> integ ⇒ integ → integ → integ<br ></br>
--  <b >infixl</b>  14</span> 
--    
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Integral.quotRem" >quotRem</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Integral" >Integral</a> integ ⇒ integ → integ → (integ, integ)</span> 
--   
--   Haskell compatibility   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Integral.rem" >rem</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Integral" >Integral</a> integ ⇒ integ → integ → integ<br ></br>
--  <b >infixl</b>  14</span> 
--   
--   The remainder á la Java operator <span class="code" >%</span> - <span class="code" >a `rem` b</span> has same sign as <span class="code" >a</span> 
--  <pre>
--  
--   forAll arbitrary (\a -&gt; forAll arbitrary (\b -&gt; (a `quot` b) * b + (a `rem` b) = a
--  </pre> 
--   This behaviour is the same as in Haskell
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Integral
class (Eq integ, Ord integ, Num integ) ⇒ Integral integ

-- | <span class="code" > x ^ n </span> raise <i >x</i> to the <i >n</i>-th power 
--   The exponent must be positive.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Integral._caret
(^) ∷  (Integral integ, Num a) ⇒ a → integ → a 
infixr  15

-- | every integral number can be converted to a big <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Integer" >Integer</a>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Integral.big
big ∷ Integral integ ⇒ integ → Integer

-- | integer division
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Integral.div
div ∷ Integral integ ⇒ integ → integ → integ 
infixl  14

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Integral.divMod
divMod ∷ Integral integ ⇒ integ → integ → (integ, integ)

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Integral.even
even ∷ Integral integ ⇒ integ → Bool

-- | every <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Num" >Num</a> can be made from an <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Integral" >Integral</a>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Integral.fromIntegral
fromIntegral ∷ (Integral integ, Num b) ⇒ integ → b

-- | <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Integral.gcd" >Integral.gcd</a> <span class="code" >x y</span> is the non-negative factor of both <span class="code" >x</span> and <span class="code" >y</span> of which every common factor of <span class="code" >x</span> and <span class="code" >y</span> is also a factor; for example <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Integral.gcd" >Integral.gcd</a> <span class="code" >4 2 = 2</span>, <span class="code" ><a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Integral.gcd" >Integral.gcd</a> (-4) 6 = 2</span>, <span class="code" ><a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Integral.gcd" >Integral.gcd</a> 0 4</span> = <span class="code" >4</span>. <span class="code" ><a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Integral.gcd" >Integral.gcd</a> 0 0</span> = <span class="code" >0</span>. (That is, the common divisor that is \"greatest\" in the divisibility preordering.) 
--   Note: Since for signed fixed-width integer types, <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Num.abs" >Num.abs</a> <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Bounded.minBound" >Bounded.minBound</a> < <span class="code" >0</span>, the result may be negative if one of the arguments is <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Bounded.minBound" >Bounded.minBound</a> (and necessarily is if the other is <span class="code" >0</span> or <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Bounded.minBound" >Bounded.minBound</a>) for such types.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Integral.gcd
gcd ∷ Integral integ ⇒ integ → integ → integ

-- | worker function for <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Integral.gcd" >Integral.gcd</a>, needs not pollute the namespace
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Integral.gcdHelper
gcdHelper ∷ Integral integ ⇒ integ → integ → integ

-- | <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Integral.lcm" >Integral.lcm</a> <span class="code" >x y</span> is the smallest positive integer that both <span class="code" >x</span> and <span class="code" >y</span> divide.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Integral.lcm
lcm ∷ Integral integ ⇒ integ → integ → integ

-- | This modulo operator works so that 
--  <pre>
--  
--   forAll arbitrary (\a -&gt; forAll arbitrary (\b -&gt; (a `div` b) * b + (a `mod` b) = a))
--  </pre> 
--   In addition, it is the case that 
--  <pre>
--  
--   forAll arbitrary (\a -&gt; forAll arbitrary (\b -&gt; @(a `quot` b) == (a `div` b) || (a `quot` b) == (a `div` b)-1))   
--  </pre>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Integral.mod
mod ∷ Integral integ ⇒ integ → integ → integ 
infixl  14

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Integral.odd
odd ∷ Integral integ ⇒ integ → Bool

-- | helper for <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Integral._caret" >Integral.^</a>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Integral.powf
powf ∷ (Integral integ, Num a) ⇒ a → integ → a

-- | helper for <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Integral._caret" >Integral.^</a>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Integral.powg
powg ∷ (Integral integ, Num a) ⇒ a → integ → a → a

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Integral.quot
quot ∷ Integral integ ⇒ integ → integ → integ 
infixl  14

-- | Haskell compatibility
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Integral.quotRem
quotRem ∷ Integral integ ⇒ integ → integ → (integ, integ)

-- | The remainder á la Java operator <span class="code" >%</span> - <span class="code" >a `rem` b</span> has same sign as <span class="code" >a</span> 
--  <pre>
--  
--   forAll arbitrary (\a -&gt; forAll arbitrary (\b -&gt; (a `quot` b) * b + (a `rem` b) = a
--  </pre> 
--   This behaviour is the same as in Haskell
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Integral.rem
rem ∷ Integral integ ⇒ integ → integ → integ 
infixl  14

-- | A class for data types that have a lower and an upper bound. 
--   Instances of <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Bounded" >Bounded</a> can be derived automatically for enumeration types. <h3 > Known Instances</h3> 
--   <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Bounded_Int" >Int</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Bounded_Bool" >Bool</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Bounded_Char" >Char</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Bounded_Long" >Long</a> <h3 > Member Functions</h3>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Bounded.maxBound" >maxBound</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Bounded" >Bounded</a> b ⇒ b</span> 
--   
--   the upper bound   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Bounded.minBound" >minBound</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Bounded" >Bounded</a> b ⇒ b</span> 
--   
--   the lower bound
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Bounded
class Bounded b

-- | the upper bound
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Bounded.maxBound
maxBound ∷ Bounded b ⇒ b

-- | the lower bound
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Bounded.minBound
minBound ∷ Bounded b ⇒ b

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#chr
chr ∷ Int → Char

-- | make a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#String" >String</a> from a single <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Char" >Char</a>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#ctos
ctos ∷ Char → String 
pure native java.lang.Character.toString

-- | <h3 > Constructors</h3>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Maybe.Just" >Just</a> a</span> 
--    
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Maybe.Nothing" >Nothing</a> </span>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Maybe
data Maybe a

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Maybe.Just
Just a

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Maybe.Nothing
Nothing

-- | The <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#maybe" >maybe</a> function takes a default value, a function, and a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Maybe" >Maybe</a> value. If the <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Maybe" >Maybe</a> value is <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Maybe.Nothing" >Maybe.Nothing</a>, the function returns the default value. Otherwise, it applies the function to the value inside the <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Maybe.Just" >Maybe.Just</a> and returns the result.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#maybe
maybe ∷ α → (β→α) → Maybe β → α

-- | <h3 > Constructors</h3>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Either.Left" >Left</a> a</span> 
--    
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Either.Right" >Right</a> b</span>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Either
data (a | b)

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Either.Left
Left a

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Either.Right
Right b

-- | apply first function to value in <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Either.Left" >Either.Left</a> or second function to value in <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Either.Right" >Either.Right</a>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#either
either ∷ (α→γ) → (β→γ) → (α | β) → γ 
infixl  2

-- | return the first element of a 2-tuple
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#fst
fst ∷ (α, β) → α

-- | return the second element of a 2-tuple
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#snd
snd ∷ (β, α) → α

-- | A head strict variant of (:) 
--   This will be used in list comprehensions
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#_excl_colon
(!:) ∷  α → [α] → [α] 
infixr  4

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#id
id ∷ α → α

-- | <span class="code" >a $ b</span> is the same as <span class="code" >a b</span>, but because of <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#$" >$</a>'s low precedence one can write <span class="code" >f $ x+y</span> instead of <span class="code" >f (x+y)</span>. Also, because <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#$" >$</a> is right associative, <span class="code" >f $ g $ h y</span> is <span class="code" >f (g (h y))</span>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#$
($) ∷  (β→α) → β → α 
infixr  1

-- | Same as `$` but argument is strict
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#$_excl
($!) ∷  (β→α) → β → α 
infixr  1

-- | <span class="code" >const a</span> is a function that returns <i >a</i> regardless of its argument.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#_const
const ∷ β → α → β

-- | <span class="code" >asTypeOf a b</span> is <i >a</i> with the type of <i >b</i>. 
--   This is a type restricted version of <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#_const" >const</a>.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#asTypeOf
asTypeOf ∷ a → a → a

-- | Exchange first and second argument of a function, i.e. 
--  <pre>
--  
--   flip f a b = f b a   
--  </pre>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#flip
flip ∷ (α→β→γ) → β → α → γ

-- | Passes the elements of a 2-tuple as arguments to a function.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#uncurry
uncurry ∷ (β→γ→α) → (β, γ) → α

-- | <span class="code" >curry f</span> passes the next two arguments as 2-tuple to <i >f</i>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#curry
curry ∷ ((γ, β)→α) → γ → β → α

-- | In patterns, the @-operator is used to bind a name to a complex pattern 
--  <pre>
--  
--   f (x@a:as) = e
--  </pre> 
--   is the same as 
--  <pre>
--  
--   f arg = case arg of { x -&gt; case x of { a:as -&gt; e }}   
--  </pre>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#_at
(@) ∷  β → α → () 
infixr  2

-- | <span class="code" >using f</span> applies a projection function <i >f</i> on both sides of <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Eq._eq_eq" >Eq.==</a>. Example usage: 
--  <pre>
--  
--   uniqBy (using fst) [(1, 1), (2, 2), (2, 3), (3,4), (2,5)]
--  </pre>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#using
using ∷ Eq α ⇒ (β→α) → β → β → Bool

-- | <span class="code" >comparing f</span> applies a projection function on both sides of <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Ord._lt_eq_gt" >Ord.<=></a>. Example usage: 
--  <pre>
--  
--   sortBy (comparing snd) [(1, &quot;z&quot;), (2, &quot;b&quot;)] == [(2, &quot;b&quot;), (1, &quot;z&quot;)]
--  </pre>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#comparing
comparing ∷ Ord α ⇒ (β→α) → β → β → Ordering

-- | Alias for <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#comparing" >comparing</a>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#ascending
ascending ∷ Ord α ⇒ (β→α) → β → β → Ordering

-- | <span class="code" >descending f</span> applies a projection function on both sides of <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#Ord._lt_eq_gt" >Ord.<=></a>, but flips arguments. Example usage: 
--  <pre>
--  
--   sortBy (descending fst) [(1, &quot;z&quot;), (2, &quot;b&quot;)] == [(2, &quot;b&quot;), (1, &quot;z&quot;)]
--  </pre>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#descending
descending ∷ Ord α ⇒ (β→α) → β → β → Ordering

-- | <pre>
--  
--   g `on` f
--  </pre> 
--   Apply a projection function <span class="code" >f</span> on both operands of <span class="code" >g</span> 
--  <pre>
--  
--   comparing f = (&lt;=&gt;) `on` f   
--  </pre>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#on
on ∷ (α→α→γ) → (β→α) → β → β → γ 
infixl  1

-- | <span class="code" >(ST s a)</span> is an abstract data type and is a computation that encapsulates side effects in state thread <span class="code" >s</span> and returns a value of type <span class="code" >a</span>. 
--   The type <span class="code" >s</span> can be understood as a compiler generated unique index for state threads. Every state thread is independent of each other and keeps track of mutable variables created in it. For detailed information, read the paper <i >Lazy Functional State Threads</i>. 
--   Every mutable native data type shall be wrapped in a <a href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeIO.html#Mutable" >Mutable</a> with phantom type parameter <span class="code" >s</span>. that tells to what state thread the value belongs. For example, the <span class="code" >new</span> method of the java class <span class="code" >java.util.Date</span> could be accessed like this: 
--  <pre>
--  
--   data Date s = native java.util.Date where
--       native new :: Long -&gt; ST s (Mutable s Date)
--  </pre> 
--   Inside ST actions, Date values can be created and manipulated with impure native methods at will. However, such a value can never escape its ST thread. 
--   Because <span class="code" >ST s</span> is an instance of <a href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeMonad.html#Monad" >Monad</a>, ST actions can be combined, which ensures sequenced execution. For example, we could add another method to the Date type that converts the date to a string: 
--  <pre>
--  
--       native toString :: Mutable s Date -&gt; ST s String
--  </pre> 
--   and a computation which yields the current time in string form: 
--  <pre>
--  
--   epoch = do
--      date &lt;- Date.new 0L
--      return date.toString
--  </pre> 
--   This looks almost like java already! <span class="code" >epoch</span> has type <span class="code" >ST s String</span> and we can run the computation with <span class="code" >epoch.run</span> (see <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#ST.run" >ST.run</a> below), which gives us a nice, pure, immutable, functional, correct <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#String" >String</a> value. 
--   The <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#IO" >IO</a> type is just an alias for <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#ST" >ST</a> <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#RealWorld" >RealWorld</a>, and can be thought of as indexing a unique global state thread. Values of type <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#IO" >IO</a> <span class="code" >a</span> are also called <i >IO actions</i>. 
--   Any ST value can also be used in the IO thread. 
--   This guarantees that <ul > <li > any computation with side effect is sequenced through the ST-Monad </li> <li > any function whose return type is not <span class="code" >IO something</span> does not have side effects, as long as no impure native function or value is deliberately declared to be pure.</li> </ul> <h3 > Constructors</h3>  
--   <span class="code" ><b >private</b> <a name="ST.ST" >ST</a> (s → a)</span> 
--     <h3 > Member Functions</h3>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="ST._gt_gt_eq" >>>=</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#ST" >ST</a> γ α</b> → (α→<a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#ST" >ST</a> γ β) → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#ST" >ST</a> γ β<br ></br>
--  <b >infixl</b>  3</span> 
--    
--   <span class="code" ><a name="ST.performUnsafe" >performUnsafe</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#IO" >IO</a> α</b> → α</span> 
--   
--   warning: You are breaking the rules. Expect an arbitrary result and program crashes.   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="ST._return" >return</a> ∷ α → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#ST" >ST</a> β α</span> 
--    
--   <span class="code" ><a name="ST.run" >run</a> ∷ (<b ><b >∀</b> ß.<a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#ST" >ST</a> ß a</b>) → a</span> 
--   
--   Run a stateful action with type <span class="code" >ST r a</span> and return a result of type <i >a</i>. The overall computation <span class="code" >ST.run st</span> is pure, though inside the <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#ST" >ST</a> action local mutable state can be employed. 
--   This is possible only if the result type <span class="code" >a</span> of the state action does <b >not</b> mention <span class="code" >r</span> and if <span class="code" >r</span> is a type variable. Hence, it is not possible to <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#ST.run" >ST.run</a> an <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#IO" >IO</a> action.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#ST
data ST s a

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#ST.ST
private ST (s → a)

-- | This abstract data type identifies the global state (disk, network, you name it). Values of type <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#ST" >ST</a> <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#RealWorld" >RealWorld</a> <span class="code" >a</span> are likely to perform input/output, manipulate global data and so on.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#RealWorld
data RealWorld 

-- | <span class="code" >IO a</span> is an abbreviation for <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#ST" >ST</a> <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#RealWorld" >RealWorld</a> <span class="code" >a</span>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeBase#IO
type IO = ST RealWorld
