-- | This package provides classes and functions that deal with the lesser pure parts of Frege - Exceptions, Threads, mutable data.
--   This package is <i >implementation specific</i> insofar as the compiler may assume that certain items are defined here in a certain way. Changes may thus lead to compiler crashes or java code that will be rejected by the java compiler.
--   In particular, derived <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#Exceptional" >Exceptional</a> instances will reference type class <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#Exceptional" >Exceptional</a>.
module frege.prelude.PreludeIO

-- | Make the <span class="code" >java.lang.Class</span> object corresponding to the instantiated type available. 
--   An instance for this type class is needed for the element type of <a href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeArrays.html#JArray" >JArray</a>s (which are based on <a href="http://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/lang/reflect/Array.html" >reflective true Java arrays</a>) one needs to create. 
--   A subclass of this is <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#Exceptional" >Exceptional</a> which adds no additional functionality and behaves basically just as a marker interface for exceptions. 
--   <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#JavaType" >JavaType</a> instances are derivable for all data types. <h3 > Known Instances</h3> 
--   <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#Exceptional_NoMatch" >NoMatch</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#Exceptional_GuardFailed" >GuardFailed</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#Exceptional_Exception" >Exception</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#Exceptional_Undefined" >Undefined</a> <h3 > Member Functions</h3>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="JavaType.javaClass" >javaClass</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#JavaType" >JavaType</a> e ⇒ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Class" >Class</a> e</span> 
--   
--   The <span class="code" >java.lang.Class</span> object of the instantiated type
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#JavaType
class JavaType e

-- | The <span class="code" >java.lang.Class</span> object of the instantiated type
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#JavaType.javaClass
javaClass ∷ JavaType e ⇒ Class e

-- | Function <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#_catch" >catch</a> requires that the argument of a handler function is an instance of <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#Exceptional" >Exceptional</a>. 
--   This is derivable for <span class="code" >pure</span> <span class="code" >native</span> data types. <h3 > Known Instances</h3> 
--   <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#Exceptional_NoMatch" >NoMatch</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#Exceptional_GuardFailed" >GuardFailed</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#Exceptional_Exception" >Exception</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#Exceptional_Undefined" >Undefined</a>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#Exceptional
class JavaType e ⇒ Exceptional e

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#Exception
data Exception 

-- | nowarn: argument of type (ST s a) 
--   Runtime method for implementation of <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#_catch" >catch</a>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#doCatch
doCatch ∷ Class b → ST s a → (b → ST s a) → ST s a 
native frege.runtime.WrappedCheckedException.doCatch

-- | The construct 
--  <pre>
--  
--   action `catch` handler
--  </pre> 
--   is a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#ST" >ST</a> action with the same type as <i >action</i>. 
--   If <i >action</i> yields a result, this will be the result of the overall action. However, if, during execution of <i >action</i> the JVM raises an exception <i >e</i> with java type <span class="code" >E</span>, and <span class="code" >E</span> is a subtype of java type <span class="code" >H</span>, and <span class="code" >H</span> is the java type associated with the argument of <i >handler</i>, the return value will be: 
--  <pre>
--  
--   handler e
--  </pre> 
--   Otherwise, if the type of <i >e</i> does not allow to pass it to <i >handler</i> it will be propagated upwards and <span class="code" >a `catch` b</span> will not return to its caller. 
--   Because <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#_catch" >catch</a> is left associative, it is possible to catch different exceptions, like in: 
--  <pre>
--  
--   action `catch` handler1 `catch` handler2
--  </pre> 
--   Care must be taken to check for the <b >most specific</b> exception first. In the example above, if the exception handled by <i >handler1</i> is <b >less specific</b> than the one handled by <i >handler2</i>, then <i >handler2</i> will never get a chance to execute. 
--   Another way to put this is to say that if <span class="code" >E1</span> and <span class="code" >E2</span> are distinct exception types handled in a chain of <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#_catch" >catch</a>es, and <span class="code" >E1</span> is (from the point of view of Java!) a subtype of <span class="code" >E2</span>, then the handler for <span class="code" >E1</span> must appear further left than the handler for <span class="code" >E2</span>. If it is a super type of <span class="code" >E2</span>, however, its handler must appear further right. And finally, if the types do not stand in a sub-type relationship, the order of the handlers is immaterial. 
--   <b >Note</b> If <i >action</i> is of the form: 
--  <pre>
--  
--   doSomething arg
--  </pre> 
--   then, depending on the strictness of <i >doSomething</i> the argument <i >arg</i> may be evaluated <b >before</b> the action is returned. Exceptions (i.e. undefined values) that occur in the construction of the action do <b >not</b> count as exceptions thrown during execution of it, and hence cannot be catched. 
--   Example: 
--  <pre>
--  
--   println (head []) `catch`  ....
--  </pre> 
--   will not catch the exception that will be thrown when println evaluates 
--   For a remedy, see <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#_try" >try</a>.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#_catch
catch ∷ JavaType γ ⇒ ST β α → (γ→ST β α) → ST β α 
infixl  2

-- | nowarn: argument of type (ST s a) 
--   The construct 
--  <pre>
--  
--   action `finally` always
--  </pre> 
--   returns the same value as <i >action</i>, when executed. 
--   However, no matter if <i >action</i> produces a value or diverges (for example, by throwing an exception), in any case will <i >always</i> be executed, and its return value dismissed. 
--   Note that <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#_finally" >finally</a> only returns to its caller if <i >action</i> would have done so. 
--   <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#_finally" >finally</a> has the same fixity as <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#_catch" >catch</a>, hence it is possible to have 
--  <pre>
--  
--   action `catch` handler1 `catch` handler2 `finally` always
--  </pre>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#_finally
finally ∷ IO a → IO b → IO a 
native frege.runtime.WrappedCheckedException.doFinally 
infixl  2

-- | Deliberately throw an exception in the <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#ST" >ST</a> monad.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#throwST
throwST ∷ Throwable → ST s a

-- | Deliberately throw an exception in the <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#IO" >IO</a> monad.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#throwIO
throwIO ∷ Throwable → IO a

-- | Make sure that exceptions thrown during construction of an action can be catched. See <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#_catch" >catch</a> for an explanation. 
--   Example: 
--  <pre>
--  
--   try println (head []) `catch` (\u::Undefined -&gt; println u.catched)
--  </pre> 
--   should print: 
--  <pre>
--  
--   frege.runtime.Undefined: Prelude.head []
--  </pre> 
--   <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#_try" >try</a> does work for unary functions only. To be safe with functions taking more actions, use: 
--  <pre>
--  
--   return a &gt;&gt;= (\a -&gt; return b &gt;&gt;= (\b -&gt; f a b))
--  </pre>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#_try
try ∷ Monad γ ⇒ (β→γ α) → β → γ α

-- | The <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#catchAll" >catchAll</a> function runs a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#ST" >ST</a> action and returns either the result or the exception thrown.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#catchAll
catchAll ∷ ST α β → ST α (Exception | β)

-- | <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#Mutable" >Mutable</a> is a wrapper for native data types. A value of type <span class="code" >Mutable s x</span> is really an <span class="code" >x</span>, but it is tied to the <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#ST" >ST</a> thread s, from which it cannot escape. 
--   The compiler will enforce the following rules: <ol > <li > When type checking <span class="code" >x.m</span> and <span class="code" >(x::Mutable s T)</span>, <span class="code" >m</span> will be searched in the namespace <span class="code" >T</span> </li> <li > An impure native method must only take and return <span class="code" >Mutable s T</span>, unless <span class="code" >T</span> is itself <b ><span class="code" >pure</span></b> (of course, all algebraic data types are pure)</li> <li > A pure type <span class="code" >T</span> must not appear as <span class="code" >Mutable s T</span> in native functions. </li> <li > Pure native functions may not return <span class="code" >Mutable s t</span> for any <span class="code" >t</span>. </li> <li > Pure native functions must not normally get arguments of type <span class="code" >Mutable s T</span>. (see below) </li> <li > In a type of the form <span class="code" >ST x (Mutable y d)</span>, it will be enforced that <i >x</i> is the same type as <i >y</i>. Furthermore, all phantom types of all <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#Mutable" >Mutable</a> types must be the same in a type signature.</li> </ol> 
--   To understand the motivation for rule 5, observe that the <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#Mutable.Mutable" >Mutable.Mutable</a> data constructor cannot be applied in Frege code, hence the only possibility to obtain a value of type <span class="code" >Mutable s t</span> is through a native function. But by rule 4 above, this could only happen in the <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#ST" >ST</a> or <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#IO" >IO</a> monad, from whence those values cannot escape. The <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#ST" >ST</a> monad is a context where the sequence of actions matters. If we allowed passing mutable data to pure functions, their results would depend on whether <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#ST" >ST</a> actions modified the value before the result is actually evaluated. 
--   Although in a strict sense, no pure function should get mutable data, rule 5 is only enforced for native pure functions, as normal frege functions couldn't do anything with the native value, except passing them on to native functions eventually. 
--   There will be means to get a read-only copy (<a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#Freezable.freeze" >Freezable.freeze</a>) of a mutable value through class <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#Freezable" >Freezable</a>. 
--   There is also the possibility that, although a value is mutable, there are certain properties that cannot change (such as the length of an array). It will be possible to bypass rule 5 in such cases. 
--   To summarize: <ul > <li > Mutable data live in the <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#ST" >ST</a> or <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#IO" >IO</a> monad, from which they cannot escape. </li> <li > They can be passed only to other <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#ST" >ST</a> actions that operate in the same state thread, as indicated by the phantom type, that is either a type variable or <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#RealWorld" >RealWorld</a>.</li> <li > Read only copies of mutable values and mutable copies of read-only values can be obtained. </li> <li > Rule 5 can be bypassed in exceptional cases. </li> </ul> <h3 > Constructors</h3>  
--   <span class="code" ><b >private</b> <a name="Mutable.Mutable" >Mutable</a> m</span> 
--     <h3 > Member Functions</h3>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Mutable.freeze" >freeze</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#Freezable" >Freezable</a> m ⇒ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#Mutable" >Mutable</a> s m</b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#ST" >ST</a> s m</span> 
--   
--   obtain a read-only copy of a mutable value through cloning or serialization.   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Mutable.readonly" >readonly</a> ∷ (m → b) → <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#Mutable" >Mutable</a> s m</b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#ST" >ST</a> s b</span> 
--   
--   Apply a pure function to a mutable value that pretends to be read-only. 
--   The function must not rely on anything that could change in the mutable data!   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Mutable.thaw" >thaw</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#Freezable" >Freezable</a> m ⇒ m → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#STMutable" >STMutable</a> s m</span> 
--   
--   obtain a mutable copy of a read only value through cloning or serialization.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#Mutable
data Mutable s m

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#Mutable.Mutable
private Mutable m

-- | Alias for <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#Mutable.readonly" >Mutable.readonly</a>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#readonly
readonly ∷ (m → b) → Mutable s m → ST s b

-- | Obtain a read only native value (temporarily) typed as <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#Mutable" >Mutable</a> 
--   For example, this could be needed when running a native <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#ST" >ST</a> method that uses the value as read-only, but we can't declare it, like: 
--  <pre>
--  
--   private native copyOf java.util.Arrays.copyOf
--                 :: ArrayOf s HashMap -&gt; Int -&gt; ST s (ArrayOf s HashMap)
--  </pre>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#mutable
mutable ∷ β → Mutable α β

-- | They type for mostly mutable values that are tied to the <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#IO" >IO</a> monad. 
--   For java types that are <b >mutable only</b> so that they always would occur wrapped into <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#MutableIO" >MutableIO</a>, the convention is to declare them as 
--  <pre>
--  
--   data Thing = mutable native org.mut.impure.Thing
--  </pre> 
--   and just write <span class="code" >Thing</span> everywhere. The type checker will check the rules for native functions <i >as if</i> <span class="code" >Thing</span> was <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#MutableIO" >MutableIO</a> <span class="code" >Thing</span>. 
--   However, normal type unification does not take the mutable status into account, so <span class="code" >Mutable a m</span> will never unify with <span class="code" >Thing</span>.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#MutableIO
type MutableIO = Mutable RealWorld

-- | They type of <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#IO" >IO</a> actions that return a mutable value of type <i >d</i> 
--   This is an abbreviation for <span class="code" >ST RealWorld (Mutable RealWorld d)</span>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#IOMutable
type IOMutable d = ST RealWorld (Mutable RealWorld d)

-- | They type of <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#ST" >ST</a> actions that return a mutable value of type <i >d</i> 
--   This is an abbreviation for <span class="code" >ST s (Mutable s d)</span>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#STMutable
type STMutable s d = ST s (Mutable s d)

-- | Type class for mutable values that support making read-only copies. To be implemented with care. <h3 > Member Functions</h3>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Freezable.freeze" >freeze</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#Freezable" >Freezable</a> f ⇒ f → f</span> 
--   
--   "Freeze" a mutable native value. The result is supposed to be immutable or at least not reachable from other parts of the code, especially from java code. 
--   The most prominent way to freeze a value is by <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#Cloneable.clone" >Cloneable.clone</a>-ing it, if that is supported. But note that sometimes a deep copy would be needed, and that <span class="code" >clone</span> does not do that.  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Freezable.thaw" >thaw</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#Freezable" >Freezable</a> f ⇒ f → f</span> 
--   
--   The inverse of <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#Freezable.freeze" >Freezable.freeze</a> creates a value (an object) which can be passed to impure functions without compromising the frozen object passed as argument. 
--   One possibility to thaw an object is by cloning it. 
--   If <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#Freezable.thaw" >Freezable.thaw</a> is not implemented correctly, bad things may happen.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#Freezable
class Freezable f

-- | "Freeze" a mutable native value. The result is supposed to be immutable or at least not reachable from other parts of the code, especially from java code. 
--   The most prominent way to freeze a value is by <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#Cloneable.clone" >Cloneable.clone</a>-ing it, if that is supported. But note that sometimes a deep copy would be needed, and that <span class="code" >clone</span> does not do that.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#Freezable.freeze
freeze ∷ Freezable f ⇒ f → f

-- | The inverse of <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#Freezable.freeze" >Freezable.freeze</a> creates a value (an object) which can be passed to impure functions without compromising the frozen object passed as argument. 
--   One possibility to thaw an object is by cloning it. 
--   If <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#Freezable.thaw" >Freezable.thaw</a> is not implemented correctly, bad things may happen.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#Freezable.thaw
thaw ∷ Freezable f ⇒ f → f

-- | For a data type declared like 
--  <pre>
--  
--   data D = native Javatype
--  </pre> 
--   where <span class="code" >Javatype</span> implements the <span class="code" >java.lang.Cloneable</span> interface, one can get implementations for <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#Freezable.freeze" >Freezable.freeze</a> and <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#Freezable.thaw" >Freezable.thaw</a> by just stating 
--  <pre>
--  
--   instance Cloneable D
--  </pre> 
--   The <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#Freezable.freeze" >Freezable.freeze</a> and <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#Freezable.thaw" >Freezable.thaw</a> operations are implemented in terms of <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#Cloneable.clone" >Cloneable.clone</a>. 
--   Note: Cloning does <b >not</b> produce safe copies if the cloned object contains references to mutable objects. In such cases, sort of a deep cloning would be required. <h3 > Member Functions</h3>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Cloneable.clone" >clone</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#Cloneable" >Cloneable</a> f ⇒ <b >f</b> → f<br ></br>
--  <b >pure </b><b >native </b>clone</span> 
--   
--   <span class="code" >clone v</span> must be a native method that works like <span class="code" >java.lang.Object#clone</span>.  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Cloneable.freeze" >freeze</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#Cloneable" >Cloneable</a> f ⇒ <b >f</b> → f</span> 
--    
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Cloneable.thaw" >thaw</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#Cloneable" >Cloneable</a> f ⇒ <b >f</b> → f</span>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#Cloneable
class Freezable f ⇒ Cloneable f

-- | <span class="code" >clone v</span> must be a native method that works like <span class="code" >java.lang.Object#clone</span>.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#Cloneable.clone
clone ∷ Cloneable f ⇒ f → f 
pure native clone

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#Cloneable.freeze
freeze ∷ Cloneable f ⇒ f → f

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#Cloneable.thaw
thaw ∷ Cloneable f ⇒ f → f

-- | For a data type declared like 
--  <pre>
--  
--   data D = native Javatype
--  </pre> 
--   where <span class="code" >Javatype</span> implements the <span class="code" >java.io.Serializable</span> interface, one can get implementations for <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#Freezable.freeze" >Freezable.freeze</a> and <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#Freezable.thaw" >Freezable.thaw</a> by just stating 
--  <pre>
--  
--   instance Serializable D
--  </pre> 
--   The <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#Freezable.freeze" >Freezable.freeze</a> and <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#Freezable.thaw" >Freezable.thaw</a> operations are implemented in terms of <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#Serializable.copySerializable" >Serializable.copySerializable</a>, which serializes its argument to a byte array and creates a new copy by deserializing it from the byte array. <h3 > Member Functions</h3>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Serializable.copySerializable" >copySerializable</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#Serializable" >Serializable</a> f ⇒ <b >f</b> → f<br ></br>
--  <b >pure </b><b >native </b>frege.runtime.Runtime.copySerializable</span> 
--   
--   <span class="code" >copySerializable v</span> is supposed to be a native function that is implemented by <span class="code" >frege.runtime.Runtime.copySerializable</span> at the instantiated type.  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Serializable.freeze" >freeze</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#Serializable" >Serializable</a> f ⇒ <b >f</b> → f</span> 
--   
--   make a safe copy through serialization/deserialization   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Serializable.thaw" >thaw</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#Serializable" >Serializable</a> f ⇒ <b >f</b> → f</span> 
--   
--   make a safe copy through serialization/deserialization
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#Serializable
class Freezable f ⇒ Serializable f

-- | <span class="code" >copySerializable v</span> is supposed to be a native function that is implemented by <span class="code" >frege.runtime.Runtime.copySerializable</span> at the instantiated type.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#Serializable.copySerializable
copySerializable ∷ Serializable f ⇒ f → f 
pure native frege.runtime.Runtime.copySerializable

-- | make a safe copy through serialization/deserialization
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#Serializable.freeze
freeze ∷ Serializable f ⇒ f → f

-- | make a safe copy through serialization/deserialization
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#Serializable.thaw
thaw ∷ Serializable f ⇒ f → f

-- | A mutable reference, suitable for use in the <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#ST" >ST</a> monad.  <h3 > Member Functions</h3>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Ref.get" >get</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#Mutable" >Mutable</a> s (<a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#Ref" >Ref</a> a)</b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#ST" >ST</a> s a<br ></br>
--  <b >native </b>get</span> 
--   
--   get the value the reference is pointing to   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Ref.modify" >modify</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#Mutable" >Mutable</a> β (<a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#Ref" >Ref</a> α)</b> → (α→α) → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#ST" >ST</a> β <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Unit" >()</a></span> 
--   
--   modify the referenced value with a function   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Ref._new" >new</a> ∷ <b >a</b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#STMutable" >STMutable</a> s (<a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#Ref" >Ref</a> a)<br ></br>
--  <b >native </b>new</span> 
--   
--   create a reference that is initially set to the argument value   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Ref.put" >put</a> ∷ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#Mutable" >Mutable</a> s (<a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#Ref" >Ref</a> a)</b> → <b >a</b> → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#ST" >ST</a> s <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Unit" >()</a><br ></br>
--  <b >native </b>put</span> 
--   
--   assign another value to the reference
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#Ref
data Ref a 

-- | get the value the reference is pointing to
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#Ref.get
get ∷ Mutable s (Ref a) → ST s a 
native get

-- | modify the referenced value with a function
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#Ref.modify
modify ∷ Mutable β (Ref α) → (α→α) → ST β ()

-- | create a reference that is initially set to the argument value
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#Ref._new
new ∷ a → STMutable s (Ref a) 
native new

-- | assign another value to the reference
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#Ref.put
put ∷ Mutable s (Ref a) → a → ST s () 
native put

-- | Haskell compatibility
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#IORef
type IORef a = Mutable RealWorld (Ref a)

-- | Alias for <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#Ref.get" >Ref.get</a>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#readIORef
readIORef ∷ Mutable s (Ref a) → ST s a 
native get

-- | Alias for <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#Ref.put" >Ref.put</a>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#writeIORef
writeIORef ∷ Mutable s (Ref a) → a → ST s () 
native put

-- | Alias for <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#Ref.modify" >Ref.modify</a>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#modifyIORef
modifyIORef ∷ Mutable β (Ref α) → (α→α) → ST β ()

-- | Alias for <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#Ref._new" >Ref.new</a>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeIO#newIORef
newIORef ∷ a → STMutable s (Ref a) 
native new

-- | This package provides common list functions for the Frege language.
--   It contains all functions described in section 9.1 of the <i >Haskell 2010 Language Report</i>, except for <a href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/../data/List.html#lookup" >lookup</a> and <a href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/../data/List.html#!!" >!!</a>. These functions have been moved to <span class="code" >frege.data.List</span> (the equivalent of Haskell's <span class="code" >Data.List</span>).
--   In addition to the common list functions, three type classes capture common properties of types that are like ordinary lists: 
--   <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#ListEmpty" >ListEmpty</a> 
--   <div > provides <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#ListEmpty._null" >ListEmpty.null</a> to test for empty containers and <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#ListEmpty.empty" >ListEmpty.empty</a> to create one. </div>  
--   <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#ListSemigroup" >ListSemigroup</a> 
--   <div > introduces the <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#ListSemigroup._plus_plus" >ListSemigroup.++</a> operator. </div>  
--   <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#ListMonoid" >ListMonoid</a> 
--   <div > is the union of the previous two. </div>  
--   <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#ListView" >ListView</a> 
--   <div > provides <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#ListView.length" >ListView.length</a>, and introduces <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#ListView.uncons" >ListView.uncons</a>, a safe operation to split a list-view into <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#ListView.head" >ListView.head</a> and <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#ListView.tail" >ListView.tail</a>.</div>  
--   <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#ListSource" >ListSource</a> 
--   <div > is the type class for types that can be converted to lists (<a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#ListSource.toList" >ListSource.toList</a>). There are instances for <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#String" >String</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Maybe" >Maybe</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Either" >Either</a> and arrays.</div>  
--   This module is <i >implementation specific</i> insofar as the compiler may assume that certain items are defined here in a certain way. Changes may thus lead to compiler crashes or java code that will be rejected by the java compiler.
--   In particular, desugared list comprehensions will reference <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#ListSource.toList" >ListSource.toList</a>.
--   This package is implicitly imported.
module frege.prelude.PreludeList

-- | A class for containers/collections that have an empty value. <h3 > Known Instances</h3> 
--   <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#ListView_StringJ" >StringJ</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#ListView__lbrack_rbrack" >[]</a> <h3 > Member Functions</h3>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="ListEmpty.empty" >empty</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#ListEmpty" >ListEmpty</a> α ⇒ α β</span> 
--   
--   the empty container   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="ListEmpty._null" >null</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#ListEmpty" >ListEmpty</a> α ⇒ α β → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Bool" >Bool</a></span> 
--   
--   <b >true</b> if and only if the container is <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#ListEmpty.empty" >ListEmpty.empty</a>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#ListEmpty
class ListEmpty α

-- | the empty container
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#ListEmpty.empty
empty ∷ ListEmpty α ⇒ α β

-- | <b >true</b> if and only if the container is <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#ListEmpty.empty" >ListEmpty.empty</a>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#ListEmpty._null
null ∷ ListEmpty α ⇒ α β → Bool

-- | A class for types that support the (++) operator.  <h3 > Known Instances</h3> 
--   <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#ListMonoid__lbrack_rbrack" >[]</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#ListMonoid_StringJ" >StringJ</a>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#ListMonoid
class (ListSemigroup α, ListEmpty α) ⇒ ListMonoid α

-- | A class for types that support <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#concat" >concat</a>  <h3 > Known Instances</h3> 
--   <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#ListMonoid__lbrack_rbrack" >[]</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#ListMonoid_StringJ" >StringJ</a> <h3 > Member Functions</h3>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="ListSemigroup._plus_plus" >++</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#ListSemigroup" >ListSemigroup</a> α ⇒ α β → α β → α β<br ></br>
--  <b >infixr</b>  13</span> 
--   
--   concatenate two lists, strings or whatever 
--  <pre>
--  
--   empty ++ x == x &amp;&amp; x ++ empty == x   
--  </pre>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#ListSemigroup
class ListSemigroup α

-- | concatenate two lists, strings or whatever 
--  <pre>
--  
--   empty ++ x == x &amp;&amp; x ++ empty == x   
--  </pre>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#ListSemigroup._plus_plus
(++) ∷  ListSemigroup α ⇒ α β → α β → α β 
infixr  13

-- | A class for things we can view as a list 
--   Such data types are instances of <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#ListMonoid" >ListMonoid</a> and support <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#ListView.head" >ListView.head</a>, <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#ListView.tail" >ListView.tail</a>, <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#ListView.length" >ListView.length</a> and concatenation (<a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#ListSemigroup._plus_plus" >ListSemigroup.++</a>) 
--   This class provides no means to construct a list. <h3 > Known Instances</h3> 
--   <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#ListView_StringJ" >StringJ</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#ListView__lbrack_rbrack" >[]</a> <h3 > Member Functions</h3>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="ListView.drop" >drop</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#ListView" >ListView</a> α ⇒ <b ><a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a></b> → α β → α β</span> 
--   
--   drop a number of initial elements   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="ListView.head" >head</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#ListView" >ListView</a> α ⇒ α β → β</span> 
--   
--   The first element of a list-view, or <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#undefined" >undefined</a> if <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#ListEmpty.empty" >ListEmpty.empty</a>   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="ListView.length" >length</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#ListView" >ListView</a> α ⇒ α β → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a></span> 
--   
--   computes the length of the container in a type dependent way   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="ListView.tail" >tail</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#ListView" >ListView</a> α ⇒ α β → α β</span> 
--   
--   The tail of a list-view, or <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#undefined" >undefined</a> if <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#ListEmpty.empty" >ListEmpty.empty</a>   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="ListView.take" >take</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#ListView" >ListView</a> α ⇒ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Int" >Int</a> → α β → α β</span> 
--   
--   take a number of initial elements   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="ListView.toList" >toList</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#ListView" >ListView</a> α ⇒ α β → [β]</span> 
--   
--   converts a list-view to a list   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="ListView.uncons" >uncons</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#ListView" >ListView</a> α ⇒ α β → <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Maybe" >Maybe</a> (β, α β)</span> 
--   
--   split the input stream in head and tail
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#ListView
class (ListSource α, ListEmpty α) ⇒ ListView α

-- | drop a number of initial elements
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#ListView.drop
drop ∷ ListView α ⇒ Int → α β → α β

-- | The first element of a list-view, or <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#undefined" >undefined</a> if <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#ListEmpty.empty" >ListEmpty.empty</a>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#ListView.head
head ∷ ListView α ⇒ α β → β

-- | computes the length of the container in a type dependent way
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#ListView.length
length ∷ ListView α ⇒ α β → Int

-- | The tail of a list-view, or <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#undefined" >undefined</a> if <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#ListEmpty.empty" >ListEmpty.empty</a>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#ListView.tail
tail ∷ ListView α ⇒ α β → α β

-- | take a number of initial elements
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#ListView.take
take ∷ ListView α ⇒ Int → α β → α β

-- | converts a list-view to a list
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#ListView.toList
toList ∷ ListView α ⇒ α β → [β]

-- | split the input stream in head and tail
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#ListView.uncons
uncons ∷ ListView α ⇒ α β → Maybe (β, α β)

-- | A class of things we can make a list from <h3 > Known Instances</h3> 
--   <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#ListView_StringJ" >StringJ</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#ListSource__lbrack_rbrack" >[]</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#ListSource_Maybe" >Maybe</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#ListSource_Either" >Either</a> <h3 > Member Functions</h3>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="ListSource.toList" >toList</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#ListSource" >ListSource</a> α ⇒ α β → [β]</span> 
--   
--   converts the value to a list
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#ListSource
class ListSource α

-- | converts the value to a list
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#ListSource.toList
toList ∷ ListSource α ⇒ α β → [β]

-- | Eagerly converts a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#String" >String</a> to a list.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#unpacked
unpacked ∷ String → [Char]

-- | convert a list of characters to a string 
--  <pre>
--  
--   packed ['a', 'b', 'c' ] == &quot;abc&quot;
--  </pre> 
--   Not very efficient, may be replaced by a java function that does it with a string buffer later.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#packed
packed ∷ [Char] → String

-- | <span class="code" >strhead s n</span> returns the initial portion of s with at most n characters. if s.<a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#ListView.length" >ListView.length</a> is lower than n, only so much characters are returned.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#strhead
strhead ∷ StringJ α → Int → StringJ α

-- | <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#and" >and</a> returns the conjunction of a Boolean list. For the result to be <b >true</b>, the list must be finite; <b >false</b>, however, results from a <b >false</b> value at a finite index of a finite or infinite list.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#and
and ∷ [Bool] → Bool

-- | <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#or" >or</a> returns the disjunction of a Boolean list. For the result to be <b >false</b>, the list must be finite; <b >true</b>, however, results from a <b >true</b> value at a finite index of a finite or infinite list.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#or
or ∷ [Bool] → Bool

-- | <span class="code" >any p xs</span> tells if any element of <i >xs</i> has property <i >p</i>. This is equivalent to 
--  <pre>
--  
--   fold (||) false (map p xs)
--  </pre> 
--   except that <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#any" >any</a> stops at the first element that has property <i >p</i>. 
--   Note that, according to the identity above, <span class="code" >any p []</span> is always <span class="code" >false</span>.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#any
any ∷ (α→Bool) → [α] → Bool

-- | <span class="code" >all p xs</span> tells if all elements of <i >xs</i> have property <i >p</i>. This is equivalent to 
--  <pre>
--  
--   fold (&amp;&amp;) true (map p xs)
--  </pre> 
--   except that <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#all" >all</a> stops at the first element that hasn't property <i >p</i>. 
--   Note that, according to the identity above, <span class="code" >all p []</span> is always <span class="code" >true</span>.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#all
all ∷ (α→Bool) → [α] → Bool

-- | <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#concat" >concat</a> concatenates the subitems of the argument which is a list of list or a list of strings. 
--   It is ok if the argument is an infinite list or any of the sublists is infinite. In either case, the result will also be infinite.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#concat
concat ∷ (ListEmpty β, ListSemigroup β) ⇒ [β α] → β α

-- | Map a function over a list and concatenate the list or string results.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#concatMap
concatMap ∷ (ListEmpty α, ListSemigroup α) ⇒ (γ→α β) → [γ] → α β

-- | <span class="code" >cycle xs</span> builds a value that is an infinite repetition of <i >xs</i>, which must not be empty.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#cycle
cycle ∷ [α] → [α]

-- | <span class="code" >filter p xs</span> returns the list of elements <i >x</i> from <i >xs</i> where (<i >p x</i>) holds. 
--   <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#filter" >filter</a> will not stop to evaluate its argument list until the first/next element with the property asked for is found. For example 
--  <pre>
--  
--   filter (==true) (repeat false)
--  </pre> 
--   will loop forever, whereas 
--  <pre>
--  
--   filter even [1..]
--  </pre> 
--   will faithfully deliver the list of positive integers that are divisible by 2, one by one.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#filter
filter ∷ (α→Bool) → [α] → [α]

-- | warning: It is strongly advised to use <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#fold" >fold</a> instead - beware of stack overflow! 
--   <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#foldl" >foldl</a>, applied to a binary operator, a starting value (typically the left identity of the operator), and a list, reduces the list using the binary operator, from left to right: 
--  <pre>
--  
--   fold f z [x1, x2, ..., xn] = (((z `f` x1) `f` x2) `f` ...) `f` xn
--  </pre> 
--   Because the operator is applied lazily, <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#foldl" >foldl</a> typically builds up large thunks which, when finally evaluated, may overflow the stack space. Therefore, the use of <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#fold" >fold</a> instead of <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#foldl" >foldl</a> is strongly suggested. 
--   This function exists merely for compatibility with Haskell.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#foldl
foldl ∷ (β→α→β) → β → [α] → β

-- | <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#fold" >fold</a>, applied to a binary operator, a starting value (typically the left identity of the operator), and a list, reduces the list using the binary operator, from left to right: 
--  <pre>
--  
--   fold f z [x1, x2, ..., xn] = (((z `f` x1) `f` x2) `f` ...) `f` xn
--  </pre> 
--   <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#fold" >fold</a> runs in constant stack space, but consumes the entire list before returning a result, so it must not be applied to infinite lists. 
--   This function is known as <span class="code" >foldl'</span> in Haskell where there is a bias in favour of using <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#foldr" >foldr</a>. 
--   In the environment of the JVM stack space is precious, hence one should prefer <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#fold" >fold</a> when one has the choice. 
--   <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#fold" >fold</a> is strict in the accumulator, hence in every recursion the intermediate result is evaluated, thus preventing build up of possibly huge thunks that result in stack overflows on evaluation.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#fold
fold ∷ (β→α→β) → β → [α] → β

-- | The sum of the numbers in a list, same as (<a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#fold" >fold</a> (<a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Num._plus" >Num.+</a>) <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Num.zero" >Num.zero</a>)
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#sum
sum ∷ Num α ⇒ [α] → α

-- | The product of the numbers in a list, same as (<a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#fold" >fold</a> (<a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Num._star" >Num.*</a>) <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Num.one" >Num.one</a>)
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#product
product ∷ Num α ⇒ [α] → α

-- | The minimal value of a non empty list, same as (<a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#foldl1" >foldl1</a> <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Ord.min" >Ord.min</a>)
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#minimum
minimum ∷ Ord α ⇒ [α] → α

-- | The maximal value of a non empty list, same as (<a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#foldl1" >foldl1</a> <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Ord.max" >Ord.max</a>)
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#maximum
maximum ∷ Ord α ⇒ [α] → α

-- | <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#foldl1" >foldl1</a> is a variant of <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#fold" >fold</a> that has no starting value argument and thus must be applied to nonempty lists only.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#foldl1
foldl1 ∷ (α→α→α) → [α] → α

-- | <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#scanl" >scanl</a> is similar to <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#fold" >fold</a> but returns a list of successive reduced values from the left: 
--  <pre>
--  
--   scanl f z [x1, x2, ...] = [z, z `f` x1, (z `f` x1) `f` x2, ... ]
--  </pre> 
--   The following property holds for all finite lists <i >xs</i>: 
--  <pre>
--  
--   last (scanl f z xs) == fold f z xs
--  </pre> 
--   In contrast to <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#fold" >fold</a>, <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#scanl" >scanl</a> can operate on infinite lists.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#scanl
scanl ∷ (α→β→α) → α → [β] → [α]

-- | <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#scanl1" >scanl1</a> is similar to <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#scanl" >scanl</a>, but takes the <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#ListView.head" >ListView.head</a> of the list as starting element and is thus only applicable to non-empty lists. 
--  <pre>
--  
--   scanl1 f [x1, x2, ...] = [x1, x1 `f` x2, (x1 `f` x2) `f` ...]
--  </pre>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#scanl1
scanl1 ∷ (α→α→α) → [α] → [α]

-- | <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#scanr" >scanr</a> is the right-to-left dual of <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#scanl" >scanl</a>. 
--   Note that 
--  <pre>
--  
--   head (scanr f z xs) == foldr f z xs.   
--  </pre>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#scanr
scanr ∷ (α → β → β) → β → [α] → [β]

-- | <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#scanr1" >scanr1</a> is a variant of <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#scanr" >scanr</a> that has no starting value argument.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#scanr1
scanr1 ∷ (α→α→α) → [α] → [α]

-- | Fold over a list from right to left. 
--  <pre>
--  
--   foldr f a (x1:x2:x3:[])
--  </pre> 
--   is the same as 
--  <pre>
--  
--   x1 `f` (x2 `f` (x3 `f` a))
--  </pre> 
--   Note that, if <i >f</i> is strict in the second argument, <span class="code" >foldr f</span> will need stack space proportional to the length of the list. But if <i >f</i> is lazy in it's second argument, <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#foldr" >foldr</a> works on infinite lists. 
--   If <i >f</i> is commutative, the list finite and laziness not an issue, <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#fold" >fold</a> may be the better choice since it runs with constant stack space. Otherwise, if <i >f</i> is not commutative, <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#foldrs" >foldrs</a> will trade time and heap space for stack space by <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#fold" >fold</a>ing the <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#flip" >flip</a>ped <i >f</i> over the <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#reverse" >reverse</a>d list.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#foldr
foldr ∷ (α→β→β) → β → [α] → β

-- | <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#foldr1" >foldr1</a> is a variant of <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#foldr" >foldr</a> that has no starting argument, and thus must be applied to a non-empty list
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#foldr1
foldr1 ∷ (α→α→α) → [α] → α

-- | This function may be used in place of 
--  <pre>
--  
--   foldr f z xs
--  </pre> 
--   if <i >f</i> is strict in its right operand and <i >xs</i> is a finite list, in cases where <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#foldr" >foldr</a> exceeds the stack size, which is usually quite limited in the JVM. 
--   <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#foldrs" >foldrs</a> will need extra CPU cycles and maybe (temporary) heap space for <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#reverse" >reverse</a>-ing its list argument, before <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#fold" >fold</a>ing the <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#flip" >flip</a>ped <i >f</i> over it. 
--   If <i >f</i> is commutative, you may simply use <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#fold" >fold</a> instead. 
--   The following property holds for all finite lists <i >xs</i>: 
--  <pre>
--  
--   foldr f z xs == foldrs f z xs
--  </pre>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#foldrs
foldrs ∷ (β→α→α) → α → [β] → α

-- | Returns all but the last element from a list. 
--   The following property holds for all non-empty finite lists /xs/: 
--  <pre>
--  
--   init xs ++ [last xs] == xs   
--  </pre>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#init
init ∷ [α] → [α]

-- | Returns the last element of a list by taking the <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#ListView.head" >ListView.head</a> of the <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#reverse" >reverse</a>d list. 
--   See also <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#init" >init</a>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#last
last ∷ [α] → α

-- | <span class="code" >map f xs</span> applies <i >f</i> to each element of <i >xs</i> and builds a new list from the results. 
--   Usage of <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#map" >map</a> is safe on infinite lists, it delivers the result list one by one as it is demanded.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#map
map ∷ (β→α) → [β] → [α]

-- | reverses a list
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#reverse
reverse ∷ [α] → [α]

-- | <span class="code" >splitAt n xs</span> returns a tuple where first element is <i >xs</i> prefix of length <i >n</i> and the second element is the remainder of the list.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#splitAt
splitAt ∷ ListView α ⇒ Int → α β → (α β, α β)

-- | <span class="code" >chunked n xs</span> makes a list of chunks of <i >xs</i> with size <i >n</i> 
--   <i >n</i> must be positive, otherwise an infinite list of <span class="code" >[]</span> is returned. 
--   The following should hold: 
--  <pre>
--  
--   n &gt; 0 ==&gt; concat (chunked n xs) == xs   
--  </pre>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#chunked
chunked ∷ Int → [α] → [[α]]

-- | <span class="code" >takeWhile p xs</span> takes leading elements from /xs/ while they satisfy the predicate /p/. 
--   Example: 
--  <pre>
--  
--   takeWhile (&lt;7) [1,2,3,9,4] == [1,2,3]
--  </pre>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#takeWhile
takeWhile ∷ (α→Bool) → [α] → [α]

-- | <span class="code" >dropWhile p xs</span> drops leading elements from <i >xs</i> that satisfy the predicate <i >p</i>. 
--   The following holds for all lists <i >xs</i> 
--  <pre>
--  
--   takeWhile p xs ++ dropWhile p xs == xs
--  </pre>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#dropWhile
dropWhile ∷ (α→Bool) → [α] → [α]

-- | <span class="code" >span p xs</span> returns a tuple whose first element is the longest prefix of <i >xs</i> elements that satisfy <i >p</i> and whose second element is the remainder of the list. 
--  <pre>
--  
--   span p xs == (takeWhile p xs, dropWhile p xs)
--  </pre>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#span
span ∷ (α→Bool) → [α] → ([α], [α])

-- | <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#_break" >break</a>, applied to a predicate /p/ and a list /xs/, returns a tuple where the first element is the longest prefix (possibly empty) of /xs/ elements that do <b >not</b> satisfy /p/ and the second element is the remainder of the list. 
--   <span class="code" >break p</span> is equivalent to <span class="code" >span (not • p)</span>.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#_break
break ∷ (α→Bool) → [α] → ([α], [α])

-- | <span class="code" >e `elem` xs</span> is true if and only if at least one of the elements of <i >xs</i> equals <i >e</i>.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#elem
elem ∷ Eq α ⇒ α → [α] → Bool 
infix  9

-- | opposite of <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#elem" >elem</a>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#notElem
notElem ∷ Eq α ⇒ α → [α] → Bool 
infix  9

-- | <span class="code" >repeat a</span> builds an infinite list where all elements are <i >a</i>.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#repeat
repeat ∷ α → [α]

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#replicate
replicate ∷ Int → α → [α]

-- | <span class="code" >iterate f a</span> builds the infinite list <span class="code" >[a, f a, f (f a), ...]</span>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#iterate
iterate ∷ (α→α) → α → [α]

-- | <span class="code" >zip as bs</span> builds a list of tuples of corresponding elements of /as/ and /bs/. Trailing elements of the longer list are ignored. 
--  <pre>
--  
--   zip (1,2,3) &quot;ab&quot; = [(1, &quot;a&quot;), (2, &quot;b&quot;)]
--  </pre>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#zip
zip ∷ [β] → [α] → [(β, α)]

-- | <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#unzip" >unzip</a> turns a list of tuples into a tuple of lists. It is the opposite of <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#zip" >zip</a> and the following holds for genuine lists 
--  <pre>
--  
--   (curry zip @ unzip) xs == xs
--  </pre> 
--   But note that 
--  <pre>
--  
--   (unzip @ curry zip) (as, bs) == (as,bs)
--  </pre> 
--   will only hold if <span class="code" >length as == length bs</span>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#unzip
unzip ∷ [(β, α)] → ([β], [α])

-- | <span class="code" >zipWith f xs ys</span> zips two lists with function <i >f</i> instead of the standard <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Tuple2" >(,)</a> that is used by <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#zip" >zip</a>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#zipWith
zipWith ∷ (β→γ→α) → [β] → [γ] → [α]

-- | <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#zip3" >zip3</a> zips 3 lists in the same way as <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#zip" >zip</a> does it.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#zip3
zip3 ∷ [γ] → [β] → [α] → [(γ, β, α)]

-- | <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#unzip3" >unzip3</a> unzips a list of triples and returns a triple of lists.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#unzip3
unzip3 ∷ [(γ, β, α)] → ([γ], [β], [α])

-- | <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#zipWith3" >zipWith3</a> <i >f</i> zips 3 lists with function <i >f</i> instead of the standard <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/./PreludeBase.html#Tuple3" >(,,)</a> that is used by <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#zip3" >zip3</a>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#zipWith3
zipWith3 ∷ (α→β→δ→γ) → [α] → [β] → [δ] → [γ]

-- | <span class="code" >intersperse a xs</span> inserts <i >a</i> between every two elements of <i >xs</i> 
--  <pre>
--  
--   intersperse 0 (1..3) == [1,0,2,0,3]
--  </pre>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeList#intersperse
intersperse ∷ α → [α] → [α]

-- | This package provides the <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeMonad#Monad" >Monad</a> class and related classes and functions.
--   The class hierarchy is derived from the (Haskell) proposal <b >The Other Prelude</b> but the traditional method names have been kept.
--   The functions in this library use the following naming conventions:<ul > <li > A postfix "M"" always stands for a function in the Kleisli category: The monad type constructor <i >m</i> is added to function results (modulo currying) and nowhere else. So, for example,</li> </ul>
--  <pre>
--  
--   filter ::               (a -&gt; Bool)   -&gt; [a] -&gt; [a]
--   filterM :: (Monad m) =&gt; (a -&gt; m Bool) -&gt; [a] -&gt; m [a]
--  </pre><ul > <li > A postfix "<i >" changes the result type from (</i>m a<i >) to (</i>m ()_). Thus, for example: </li> </ul>
--  <pre>
--  
--   sequence  :: Monad m =&gt; [m a] -&gt; m [a]
--   sequence_ :: Monad m =&gt; [m a] -&gt; m ()
--  </pre><ul > <li > A prefix "m" generalizes an existing function to a monadic form. Thus, for example: </li> </ul>
--  <pre>
--  
--   sum :: Num a =&gt; [a] -&gt; a
--   msum :: MonadPlus m =&gt; [m a] -&gt; m a
--  </pre>
--   This package is <i >implementation specific</i> insofar as the compiler may assume that certain items are defined here in a certain way. Changes may thus lead to compiler crashes or java code that will be rejected by the java compiler.
--   In particular, desugared <b ><span class="code" >do</span></b> expressions will reference <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeMonad#Monad" >Monad</a>, <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeMonad#Bind._gt_gt_eq" >Bind.>>=</a> and <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeMonad#Monad._gt_gt" >Monad.>></a>.
--   This package is implicitly imported and besides the additional stuff covers most of what one would get by importing <i >Control.Monad</i> and <i >Control.Applicative</i> in Haskell.
module frege.prelude.PreludeMonad

-- | The <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeMonad#Functor" >Functor</a> class is used for types that can be mapped over. Instances of <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeMonad#Functor" >Functor</a> should satisfy the following laws: 
--  <pre>
--  
--   fmap id == id
--   fmap (f . g) == fmap f . fmap g
--  </pre> <h3 > Known Instances</h3> 
--   <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeMonad#Monad_Either" >Either</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeMonad#Monad_ST" >ST</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeMonad#Applicative__minus_gt" >-></a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeMonad#Functor_l_c_r" >(,)</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeMonad#Functor__lbrack_rbrack" >[]</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeMonad#Functor_l_cc_r" >(,,)</a> <h3 > Member Functions</h3>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Functor.fmap" >fmap</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeMonad#Functor" >Functor</a> f ⇒ (a → b) → f a → f b<br ></br>
--  <b >infixl</b>  4</span> 
--   
--   Map a function over a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeMonad#Functor" >Functor</a>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeMonad#Functor
class Functor f

-- | Map a function over a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeMonad#Functor" >Functor</a>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeMonad#Functor.fmap
fmap ∷ Functor f ⇒ (a → b) → f a → f b 
infixl  4

-- | <h3 > Known Instances</h3> 
--   <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeMonad#Monad_Either" >Either</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeMonad#Monad_ST" >ST</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeMonad#Monad__lbrack_rbrack" >[]</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeMonad#Applicative__minus_gt" >-></a> <h3 > Member Functions</h3>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Apply._lt_star_gt" ><*></a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeMonad#Apply" >Apply</a> f ⇒ f (a→b) → f a → f b<br ></br>
--  <b >infixl</b>  4</span>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeMonad#Apply
class Functor f ⇒ Apply f

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeMonad#Apply._lt_star_gt
(<*>) ∷  Apply f ⇒ f (a→b) → f a → f b 
infixl  4

-- | An infix synonym for <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeMonad#Functor.fmap" >Functor.fmap</a>. Left associative with precedence 4.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeMonad#_lt$_gt
(<$>) ∷  Functor f ⇒ (a → b) → f a → f b 
infixl  4

-- | A functor with application, providing operations to <ul > <li > embed pure expressions (<a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeMonad#Applicative.pure" >Applicative.pure</a>), and </li> <li > sequence computations and combine their results (<a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeMonad#Apply._lt_star_gt" >Apply.<*></a>). </li> </ul> 
--   A minimal complete definition must include implementations of these functions satisfying the following laws:  
--   <i >identity</i> 
--   <div > <span class="code" >pure id <*> v = v</span></div>  
--   <i >composition</i> 
--   <div > <span class="code" >pure (•) <<b >> u <</b>> v <<b >> w = u <</b>> (v <*> w)</span></div>  
--   <i >homomorphism</i> 
--   <div > <span class="code" >pure f <*> pure x = pure (f x)</span></div>  
--   <i >interchange</i> 
--   <div > <span class="code" >u <<b >> pure y = pure ($ y) <</b>> u</span></div>   
--   The other methods have the following default definitions, which may be overridden with equivalent specialized implementations: 
--  <pre>
--  
--    u *&gt; v = pure (const id)  &lt;*&gt; u &lt;*&gt; v
--    u &lt;* v = pure const &lt;*&gt; u &lt;*&gt; v
--  </pre> 
--   As a consequence of these laws, the <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeMonad#Functor" >Functor</a> instance for <span class="code" >f</span> will satisfy 
--  <pre>
--  
--   fmap f x = pure f &lt;*&gt; x
--  </pre> 
--   If <span class="code" >f</span> is also a <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeMonad#Monad" >Monad</a>, it should satisfy 
--  <pre>
--  
--   (&lt;*&gt;) = ap
--  </pre> 
--   (which implies that <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeMonad#Applicative.pure" >Applicative.pure</a> and <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeMonad#Apply._lt_star_gt" >Apply.<*></a> satisfy the applicative functor laws). 
--   Minimal complete definition: <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeMonad#Applicative.pure" >Applicative.pure</a> and <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeMonad#Apply._lt_star_gt" >Apply.<*></a>. <h3 > Known Instances</h3> 
--   <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeMonad#Monad_Either" >Either</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeMonad#Monad_ST" >ST</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeMonad#Monad__lbrack_rbrack" >[]</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeMonad#Applicative__minus_gt" >-></a> <h3 > Member Functions</h3>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Applicative._star_gt" >*></a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeMonad#Applicative" >Applicative</a> p ⇒ p a → p b → p b<br ></br>
--  <b >infixl</b>  4</span> 
--   
--   Sequence actions, discarding the value of the first argument.   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Applicative._lt_star" ><*</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeMonad#Applicative" >Applicative</a> p ⇒ p a → p b → p a<br ></br>
--  <b >infixl</b>  4</span> 
--   
--   Sequence actions, discarding the value of the second argument.   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Applicative.pure" >pure</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeMonad#Applicative" >Applicative</a> p ⇒ a → p a</span> 
--   
--   Lift a value
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeMonad#Applicative
class (Functor p, Apply p) ⇒ Applicative p

-- | Sequence actions, discarding the value of the first argument.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeMonad#Applicative._star_gt
(*>) ∷  Applicative p ⇒ p a → p b → p b 
infixl  4

-- | Sequence actions, discarding the value of the second argument.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeMonad#Applicative._lt_star
(<*) ∷  Applicative p ⇒ p a → p b → p a 
infixl  4

-- | Lift a value
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeMonad#Applicative.pure
pure ∷ Applicative p ⇒ a → p a

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeMonad#apply
apply ∷ Apply p ⇒ p (a→b) → p a → p b

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeMonad#liftA
liftA ∷ Applicative f ⇒ (a → b) → f a → f b

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeMonad#liftA2
liftA2 ∷ Applicative f ⇒ (a → b → c) → f a → f b → f c

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeMonad#liftA3
liftA3 ∷ Applicative f ⇒ (a → b → c → d) → f a → f b → f c → f d

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeMonad#liftA4
liftA4 ∷ Applicative f ⇒ (a → b → c → d → e) → f a → f b → f c → f d → f e

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeMonad#liftA5
liftA5 ∷ Applicative f ⇒ (a → b → c → d → e → g) → f a → f b → f c → f d → f e → f g

-- | <h3 > Known Instances</h3> 
--   <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeMonad#Monad_Either" >Either</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeMonad#Monad__minus_gt" >-></a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeMonad#Monad_ST" >ST</a>, <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeMonad#Monad__lbrack_rbrack" >[]</a> <h3 > Member Functions</h3>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Bind._gt_gt_eq" >>>=</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeMonad#Bind" >Bind</a> f ⇒ f a → (a → f b) → f b<br ></br>
--  <b >infixl</b>  3</span> 
--   
--   Sequentially compose two actions, passing any value produced by the first as an argument to the second.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeMonad#Bind
class (Functor f, Apply f) ⇒ Bind f

-- | Sequentially compose two actions, passing any value produced by the first as an argument to the second.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeMonad#Bind._gt_gt_eq
(>>=) ∷  Bind f ⇒ f a → (a → f b) → f b

--  <b >infixl</b>  3</span>

-- | <h3 > Member Functions</h3>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Plus.pzero" >pzero</a> ∷ <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/prelude/PreludeMonad#Plus" >Plus</a> f ⇒ f a</span>
