@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/test/QuickCheckTest#quickCheckWithResult
quickCheckWithResult ∷ Testable prop ⇒ Args → prop → IO Result

verboseCheck ∷ Testable prop ⇒ prop → IO ()

verboseCheckWith ∷ Testable prop ⇒ Args → prop → IO ()

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/test/QuickCheckTest#verboseCheckResult
verboseCheckResult ∷ Testable prop ⇒ prop → IO Result

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/test/QuickCheckTest#verboseCheckWithResult
verboseCheckWithResult ∷ Testable prop ⇒ Args → prop → IO Result

-- | This program reads java class files that are the result of compiling a frege package and writes a documentation of that package. All public classes, instances, data types, type aliases and functions are listed along with programmer supplied documentation from <i >doc</i> comments.
--   Usage:
--  <pre>
--  
--  java frege.tools.Doc [-d docpath] your.frege.Package ...
--  </pre>
--   This creates or updates the documentation files for the packages named on the command line. A documentation file for package <span class="code" >a.b.C</span> will be written in file <span class="code" >docpath/a/b/C.html</span>, where <span class="code" >docpath</span> must be an existing directory.
--   If the <span class="code" >-d</span> flag is not given, the current directory is assumed for <span class="code" >docpath</span>.
--   The generated HTML will contain links to the documentation files of imported packages, which are assumed to exist in the same <span class="code" >docpath</span>.
module frege.tools.Doc

-- | <h3 > Constructors</h3>

--   print a line for each documentation file

-- | Inspect a frege documentation directory and make files that enable framed HTML view.
module frege.tools.MakeDocIndex

-- | regular expression to split path names on <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/tools/../java/IO.html#File.separator" >File.separator</a>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/tools/MakeDocIndex#separatorRE
separatorRE ∷ Regex

-- | regular expression to detect "*.html" files
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/tools/MakeDocIndex#htmlAtEnd
htmlAtEnd ∷ Regex

-- | drop ".html" from the end of a name
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/tools/MakeDocIndex#unHtml
unHtml ∷ String → String

-- | tell if this is the name of a meta file
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/tools/MakeDocIndex#isMeta
isMeta ∷ String → Bool

-- | walk a directory and get all HTML files
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/tools/MakeDocIndex#findHtml
findHtml ∷ String → IO [(String, String)]

-- | We will make the following files: 
--   <span class="code" >fregedoc.html</span> defines 3 frames: left upper, left lower and right. 
--   <span class="code" >prefix-frame.html</span> contains a list of the module prefixes, which are shown in the left upper frame. Each entry causes the left lower frame to display the modules with that prefix. 
--   For each module prefix a file that lists the actual modules. This one is displayed in the left lower frame, and clicking on one of the names causes the module documentation to appear in the right frame. For example, <span class="code" >frame-frege.prelude.html</span> would contain <span class="code" >PreludeBase</span>, <span class="code" >PreludeMonad</span> and so on. 
--   There will be a pseudo module prefix "<span class="code" >All Modules</span>" and a corresponding <span class="code" >frame-All-Modules.html</span> that contains links to all the modules.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/tools/MakeDocIndex#_main
main ∷ [String] → IO Bool

-- | Print the top file with the frameset
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/tools/MakeDocIndex#printFregeDoc
printFregeDoc ∷ String → IO ()

-- | compute the path of a file in a certain directory
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/tools/MakeDocIndex#fileIn
fileIn ∷ String → String → IO String

-- | make the <span class="code" >prefix-frame.html</span> file
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/tools/MakeDocIndex#makePrefixFrame
makePrefixFrame ∷ String → [String] → IO ()

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/tools/MakeDocIndex#makeFrame
makeFrame ∷ String → String → [(String, String)] → IO ()

-- | wrap in html tags, i.e. <span class="code" ><xx>foo</xx></span>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/tools/MakeDocIndex#wrap
wrap ∷ String → String → String

-- | make link from a relative path and a HTML file name
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/tools/MakeDocIndex#linkElem
linkElem ∷ String → String → String

-- | make link to frame
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/tools/MakeDocIndex#frameElem
frameElem ∷ String → String

-- | display name of a module prefix
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/tools/MakeDocIndex#prefixName
prefixName ∷ String → String

-- | file name of a module prefix
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/tools/MakeDocIndex#prefixFrame
prefixFrame ∷ String → String

-- | Looks up quick check predicates in the given modules and tests them. 
--   Usage: 
--   <div > java -cp fregec.jar frege.tools.Quick [ option ... ] modulespec ... </div>  
--   Options:<ul > <li > -v print a line for each predicate that passed </li> <li > -n num run <i >num</i> tests per predicate, default is 100 </li> <li > -p pred1,pred2,... only test the given predicates </li> <li > -x pred1,pred2,... do not test the given predicates </li> <li > -l just print the names of the predicates available. </li> </ul>
--   Ways to specify modules:<ul > <li > module the module name (e.g. my.great.Module), will be lookup up in the current class path.</li> <li > dir/ A directory path. The directory is searched for class files, and for each class files an attempt is made to load it as if the given directory was in the class path. The directory must be the root of the classes contained therein, otherwise the classes won't get loaded.</li> <li > path-to.jar A jar or zip file is searched for class files, and for each class file found an attempt is made to load it as if the jar was in the class path.</li> </ul>
--   The number of passed/failed tests is reported. If any test failed or other errors occurred, the exit code will be non zero.
--   The code will try to heat up your CPU by running tests on all available cores. This should be faster on multi-core computers than running the tests sequentially. It makes it feasible to run more tests per predicate.
module frege.tools.Quick

-- | functionality relies on the absolute name of type <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/tools/../test/QuickCheckGen.html#Gen" >Gen</a>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/tools/Quick#propName
propName ∷ QName

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/tools/Quick#genName
genName ∷ QName

--

--   access field <span class="code" >verbose</span>

-- | This does the magic. 
--   We know that the type of the item is <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/tools/../test/QuickCheckProperty.html#Property" >Property</a> on the Frege level. This will be compiled to something that is a Lambda in Java terms. 
--   Hence the cast is a no-op, and the native interface will believe our claim that the Lambda is a Property and will allow us to use it just like any other <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/tools/../test/QuickCheckProperty.html#Property" >Property</a>.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/tools/Quick#toLambda

native (frege.runtime.Lambda)

-- | The full range goes from the lower range to the upper range, inclusive. 
--   The lower range is determined by going from the original position backwards as long as there are comments or documentation. 
--   The upper range is the last non comment or documentation token before the next definition in the ascending list of definitions, or, if there is no next, the last token in the file.
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/tools/Splitter#fullRange
fullRange ∷ Symbol → Maybe Symbol → StIO Position

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/tools/Splitter#tauDep
tauDep ∷ Global → TreeSet QName → Tau → TreeSet QName

-- | This program creates a parser from the result of running <span class="code" >byacc -v</span> on a yacc grammar. It reads the resulting files "y.tab.c" and "y.output" in the current directory and uses the information therein to construct a frege program.
--   Each grammar rule is associated with a reduction function of type
--  <pre>
--  
--    item1 -&gt; ... -&gt; item2 -&gt; result
--  </pre>
--   where the item types are either tokens (provided as input to the parser) or results of other grammar rules. All rules of a nonterminal grammar symbol will have the same result type. Example:
--  <pre>
--  
--   %{
--   package Calculator
--   numberFrom :: Token -&gt; Double
--   %}
--  
--   %token NUMBER PI
--   %start sum
--   %%
--   sum : product '+' product { \a\_\b -&gt; a + b }  // was: $$ = $1 + $3
--         | product                                // was: $$ = $1
--         ;
--   product: term '*' term { \a\b\c -&gt; a * b }
--         | term
--         ;
--   term: NUMBER              { numberFrom }
--         | PI                { const 3.14159 }
--         | '-' term          { \_\b -&gt; negate b }
--         | '(' sum ')'       { \_\b\_ -&gt; b }
--         ;
--   %%
--   data TokenID = NUMBER | PI | OPERATOR
--   derive Show TokenID
--   derive Ord TokenID
--  </pre>
--  <pre>
--  
--   data Token = N Double | Pi | Op Char
--   derive Show Token
--  </pre>
--  <pre>
--  
--   yyshowToken = Token.show
--  </pre>
--  <pre>
--  
--   yyniceToken (N d) = show d
--   yyniceToken Pi = &quot;pi&quot;
--   yyniceToken (Op c) = show c
--  </pre>
--  <pre>
--  
--   yytoken :: Token -&gt; TokenID
--   yytoken (N _) = NUMBER
--   yytoken Pi    = PI
--   yytoken Op    = OPERATOR
--  
--   yychar :: Token -&gt; Char
--   yychar (Op c) = c
--   yychar _ = const '&sect;'  // paragraph symbol not used elsewhere
--  
--   yyfromId NUMBER = N 42.0
--   yyfromId PI     = PI
--   // yyfromId OPERATOR = not needed, as the parser knows nothing of OPERATOR
--  
--   yyfromCh :: Char -&gt; Token
--   yyfromCh c = Op c
--  
--   yyline = const 0      // no way to know in this example
--  </pre>
--   So far, this is just a good old yacc grammar, except that the semantic actions are frege expressions, and the code before an after the "%%" markers is frege code.
--   Each semantic action is expected to be a function that takes as many arguments as there are items in its rule. Hence, in the first rule of nonterminal "sum" the left product will be bound to /a/, the "+" token is ignored and the right product to /b/. A missing action is equivalent to the identity function, therefore in the second rule of nonterminal "sum", the sum will be just the product.
--   The parser generated from this will have a function
--  <pre>
--  
--   yyparse :: [Token] -&gt; Maybe Double
--  </pre>
--   since Double is the result type of the rules associated with the start symbol and tokens are obviously of type Token (due to application of user supplied function numberFrom). The result will be <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/tools/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Maybe.Nothing" >Maybe.Nothing</a> if the parser could not reduce the start symbol (i.e., when there were nonrecoverable syntax errors) and (<a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/tools/../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Maybe.Just" >Maybe.Just</a> x) otherwise, where /x/ is the result of one of the semantic actions associated with the "%start" symbol.
--   The parser itself does not make any assumptions about what a token is. Instead, it relies on the following user supplied functions:
--  <pre>
--  
--   yytoken  :: token -&gt; tid
--   yyfromId :: tid -&gt; token
--  </pre>
--   where /token/ is the type of tokens and /tid/ is the type of the token constants defined in the "%token" directive. The /yytoken/ function must be total, i.e. all possible token values must produce some token constant, yet this does not have to be one of the constants that is listed in the "%token" directive.
--   The /yyfromId/ function must produce an example token value for each token constant the parser knows of through the "%token" diretive. Both functions have to be there only when a "%token" directive is present.
--   If the grammar uses character constants, the following functions must be present:
--  <pre>
--  
--   yychar :: token -&gt; Char
--   yyfromCh :: Char -&gt; token
--  </pre>
--   The /yychar/ function must be total, all possible token values must be mapped to some character. Use a character value that is not used in the grammar for tokens that have no representation as a character value.
--   The /yyfromCh/ function maps back characters to token values. The /yyfrom../ functions are used in error recovery to supply tokens that are expected, but missing.
--   Here is an example of how the parser may determine what to do in state 42:
--  <pre>
--  
--   yyaction 42 tok = case yychar tok of
--         '*'   -&gt; Shift 57
--         _ -&gt; case yytoken tok of
--             NUMBER -&gt; Shift 96
--             _      -&gt; Reduce 5
--  </pre>
--   In addition, the parser needs the following functions:
--  <pre>
--  
--   yynice :: token -&gt; String
--   yyshow :: token -&gt; String
--   yyline :: token -&gt; Show:a
--   yyerror :: Show:a -&gt; String -&gt; c
--  </pre>
--   /yynice/ is used by the parser to construct error messages like this
--  <pre>
--  
--   &quot;syntax error, expected ',', found &quot; ++ yynice errortoken
--   &quot;syntax error, expected IDENTIFIER, found &quot; ++ yynice errortoken
--   &quot;syntax error on &quot; ++ yynice errortoken
--  </pre>
--   /yyshow/ is used in trace output and is intended for a most detailed display of tokens as they are recognized by the parser.
--   /yyline/ is used to extract line number information from a token, it is thus a good idea to design the lexical analyzer so that a token is able to tell where it was found.
--   /yyerror/ is used to emit messages about syntax errors. The first argument will be either the string "EOF" or the result of applying /yyline/ to a token. The second argument is a string that describes the error. The result of yyerror is evaluated, but ignored.
module frege.tools.YYgen

-- | Represents an abstract text sequence  <h3 > Constructors</h3>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Text.E" >E</a> (<a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/tools/doc/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#String" >String</a>)</span>

--   symbols like &forall; &rarr; ...   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Text.Label" >Label</a> <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/tools/doc/../../compiler/types/QNames.html#QName" >QName</a>   <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/tools/doc/Utilities#Text" >Text</a></span> 
--   
--   <a name="#label">text<\/a>   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Text.P" >P</a> (<a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/tools/doc/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#String" >String</a>)</span>

--   plain text   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Text.PRef" >PRef</a> <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/tools/doc/../../compiler/types/Packs.html#Pack" >Pack</a>   (<a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/tools/doc/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#Maybe" >Maybe</a> <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/tools/doc/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#String" >String</a>)   <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/tools/doc/Utilities#Text" >Text</a></span> 
--   
--   reference to a package with optional item   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Text.Ref" >Ref</a> <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/tools/doc/../../compiler/types/QNames.html#QName" >QName</a>   <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/tools/doc/Utilities#Text" >Text</a></span> 
--   
--   <a href="...">N.n<\/a>   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Text.Seq" >Seq</a> <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/tools/doc/Utilities#Text" >Text</a>   <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/tools/doc/Utilities#Text" >Text</a></span> 
--   
--   concatenation of 2 texts   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Text.T" >T</a> <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/tools/doc/Utilities#Attr" >Attr</a>   <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/tools/doc/Utilities#Text" >Text</a></span> 
--   
--   text with character attributes   
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Text.XLbl" >XLbl</a> (<a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/tools/doc/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#String" >String</a>)   <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/tools/doc/Utilities#Text" >Text</a></span>

--   generic label

-- | symbols like &forall; &rarr; ...
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/tools/doc/Utilities#Text.E
E (String)

-- | <a name="#label">text<\/a>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/tools/doc/Utilities#Text.Label
Label QName   Text

-- | plain text
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/tools/doc/Utilities#Text.P
P (String)

PRef Pack   (Maybe String)   Text

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/tools/doc/Utilities#Text.Ref
Ref QName   Text

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/tools/doc/Utilities#Text.Seq
Seq Text   Text

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/tools/doc/Utilities#Text.T
T Attr   Text

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/tools/doc/Utilities#Text.XLbl
XLbl (String)   Text

-- | generic ref
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/tools/doc/Utilities#Text.XRef
XRef (String)   Text

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/tools/doc/Utilities#fref
fref ∷ QName → Global → Text

-- | makes a single text from a list of texts
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/tools/doc/Utilities#seq
seq ∷ [Text] → Text

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/tools/doc/Utilities#_colon_minus
(:-) ∷  Text → Text → Text 
infixr  13

eForall ∷ Text

-- | attribute values for use in <a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/tools/doc/Utilities#Text" >Text</a>  <h3 > Constructors</h3>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="Attr.A" >A</a> (<a class="tref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/tools/doc/../../prelude/PreludeBase.html#String" >String</a>)</span>

--   <span class="code" ><a name="Attr.Bold" >Bold</a> </span>

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/tools/doc/Utilities#docop
docop ∷ TokenID → Text

label ∷ QName → Text

-- | compile a doc comment to a list of paragraphs
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/tools/doc/Utilities#docit
docit ∷ Global → Maybe String → [Paragraph]

-- | we have the following parapgraph kinds: <ul > <li > plain </li> <li > headers </li> <li > unordered list item </li> <li > ordered list item </li> <li > definition list item </li> <li > preformatted </li> </ul> <h3 > Constructors</h3>  
--   <span class="code" ><a name="PKind.DItem" >DItem</a> </span> 
--    
--   <span class="code" ><a name="PKind.Header" >Header</a> </span> 
--    
--   <span class="code" ><a name="PKind.OItem" >OItem</a> </span> 
--    
--   <span class="code" ><a name="PKind.Plain" >Plain</a> </span> 
--    
--   <span class="code" ><a name="PKind.Pre" >Pre</a> </span> 
--    
--   <span class="code" ><a name="PKind.UItem" >UItem</a> </span>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/tools/doc/Utilities#PKind
data PKind

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/tools/doc/Utilities#PKind.DItem
DItem

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/tools/doc/Utilities#PKind.Header
Header

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/tools/doc/Utilities#PKind.OItem
OItem

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/tools/doc/Utilities#PKind.Plain
Plain

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/tools/doc/Utilities#PKind.Pre
Pre

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/tools/doc/Utilities#PKind.UItem
UItem

-- | tag paragraph with kind, each paragraph must have at least one line
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/tools/doc/Utilities#tagP
tagP ∷ [String] → (PKind, [String])

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/tools/doc/Utilities#docpars
docpars ∷ Global → [(PKind, [String])] → [Paragraph]

ungt ∷ StringJ α → StringJ α

unnl ∷ String → [String]

unws ∷ String → String

isEnd ∷ [String] → Bool

lsToPs ∷ [String] → [[String]]

pres ∷ String → Bool

uitem ∷ String → Bool

oitem ∷ String → Bool

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/tools/doc/Utilities#orex
orex ∷ Regex

ditem ∷ String → Bool

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/tools/doc/Utilities#drex
drex ∷ Regex

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/tools/doc/Utilities#header
header ∷ String → Bool

-- | check if this is the start of a list item
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/tools/doc/Utilities#litem
litem ∷ String → Bool

-- | check if this is a normal paragraph line
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/tools/doc/Utilities#item
item ∷ String → Bool

-- | Checks the property that, after applying <a class="fref" href="http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/tools/doc/Utilities#unws" >unws</a>, a string is either empty or it contains at least a non space character
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/tools/doc/Utilities#prop_unws
prop_unws ∷ Property

-- | Check whether <span class="code" >file1</span> is newer than <span class="code" >file2</span> 
--   If both files are modified at the same time, <span class="code" >file1</span> is considered newer thus <span class="code" >File.new "X.class" `newer` File.new "X.java"</span> works as expected. 
--   If <span class="code" >file1</span> does not exist, it is <b >not</b> newer than any file. 
--   newer :: File -> File -> Bool newer file1 file2 | file1.exists = file1.lastModified >= file2.lastModified | otherwise = false 
--   given a package name and an extension, create a file name e.g. 
--  <pre>
--  
--  packToFile &quot;frege.system.IO&quot; &quot;.fr&quot; == frege/system/IO.fr
--  </pre>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/tools/doc/Utilities#packToFile
packToFile ∷ String → String → String

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/tools/doc/Utilities#packToFileRef
packToFileRef ∷ Pack → Global → IO String

-- | given a directory name and a file or directory name, compute the name of the directory relative to that filename, e.g. 
--  <pre>
--  
--   relPath &quot;foo&quot;   &quot;foo&quot;         == &quot;.&quot;
--   relPath &quot;foo&quot;   &quot;foo/x.html&quot;  == &quot;.&quot;
--   relPath &quot;foo&quot;   &quot;bar/z.html&quot;  == &quot;../foo&quot;
--  </pre>
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/tools/doc/Utilities#relPath
relPath ∷ Maybe (MutableIO File) → Maybe (MutableIO File) → IO String

-- | create a full HTML page with CSS and documentation
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/tools/doc/Utilities#htmlDoc
htmlDoc ∷ Docu → StIO ()

emitHtml ∷ Bool → Docu → StIO ()

@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/tools/doc/Utilities#emitCss
emitCss ∷ StIO ()

-- | emit a HTML structure
@url http://www.frege-lang.org/doc/frege/tools/doc/Utilities#htmlParagraph
htmlParagraph ∷ Paragraph → StIO ()

lt ∷ Regex

gt ∷ Regex
